<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cars, Tractors in Conflict on Roads  </HEADLINE>
By JAMES HANNAH, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio (AP) -- As urban sprawl puts more people from cities
and suburbs onto rural highways, they are finding a danger hidden
in broad daylight.
</P>
<P>
   During spring planting season, tractors with wide tillage
equipment and planters crawl along rural roads. In the fall, the
roads are filled with mammoth, slow-moving combines that farmers
use to harvest their fields.
</P>
<P>
   Add unfamiliar, impatient and even enraged drivers to the mix,
and the results can be deadly accidents without any of the usual
traffic hazards -- bad weather, darkness, hills or curves, alcohol
or youthful inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics from the Ohio Department of Highway Safety show the
accidents most often occur in the late afternoon, involve sideswipe
or angle collisions, and are often preceded by motorists trying to
pass as farmers make left turns.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you ever want a real thrill ride, take a ride with a farmer
on a tractor on a state highway and have him make a left-hand
turn,'' said Steve Homan, who operates a 200-acre dairy farm near
Chickasaw, Ohio. ''If farm prices don't kill the farmer, these
roads will.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Safety Council, 88 people were killed
and 700 to 800 injured in U.S. traffic accidents involving farm
vehicles in 1998, the latest year for which figures were available.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis in the Journal of Agricultural Safety and Health
questioned whether motorists realize farm vehicles are turning or
misjudge the speed of the turn. It also said the numbers may
suggest that motorists simply don't realize how slow farm vehicles
move.
</P>
<P>
   Homan theorized that motorists become accustomed to the flashing
rear lights of the farm vehicle and do not notice the turn signal.
</P>
<P>
   William Field, director of Purdue University's agricultural
safety and health program, said the statistics tell him that
motorists are simply driving too fast on rural roads.
</P>
<P>
   ''People just can't stop in time when suddenly they have a
tractor in front of them,'' he said. ''It's like hitting a tree.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger hit home for Homan in October 1998, when he lost a
close friend, Kenneth Wuebker, a 48-year-old father of three.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was making a turn with a tractor, and a young fellow went
around him at the wrong time, flipped the tractor over, and it
killed him,'' said Homan. The other driver was estimated to be
going 65 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Just recently, Homan, 44, was on the road with his tractor and
three cars backed up behind him. The first two drivers were patient
and slowed down, but not the third.
</P>
<P>
   ''He passed me and went halfway in the ditch to get around me,''
Homan said. ''It's definitely getting worse. The traffic has picked
up a lot more. And everybody tends to push the pedal.''
</P>
<P>
   Leroy Billman, director of safety programs for the Ohio Farm
Bureau, said most farm vehicles can go no faster than 20 mph but
need to use rural highways. Driving them on the side of the road is
usually not an option because of ditches, mailboxes and private
property, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem occurs when the farmer and the motorist
become irate at the same time. ''It ends up being a situation very
similar to road rage,'' Billman said.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue's Field said he has noticed more ''Tractor Ahead''
warning signs in his travels around the country. Manufacturers also
are starting to place turn signals higher on farm vehicles so
motorists can see them better, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
