<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pope Honors Modern-Day Heroes  </HEADLINE>
By FRANCES D'EMILIO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Choosing as his backdrop the Colosseum, the ancient
arena associated with Christianity's first martyrs, Pope John Paul
II paid tribute to those who suffered for the faith in some of the
20th century's cruelest places, among them Soviet gulags, Nazi
extermination camps and Chinese forced labor factories.
</P>
<P>
   As Christianity begins its third millennium, John Paul is
worried that faith might be weakening, and he wanted Sunday night's
ceremony at the Roman monument to give Christians fresh examples of
courageous faithful from modern times.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the 20th century, and maybe even more than in the first
period of Christianity, there has been a vast number of men and
women who bore witness to the faith through sufferings that were
often heroic,'' John Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   The pope invited members from other Christian denominations to
join him in the tribute. Orthodox, Anglicans and many Protestant
representatives participated.
</P>
<P>
   ''Countless numbers refused to yield to the cult of false gods
of the 20th century and were sacrificed by Communism, Nazism, by
the idolatry of state or race,'' John Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican did not make public a list of 12,000 names sent in
by bishops throughout the world as candidates to be honored.
Reportedly on the list are Baptist Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., the
slain American civil rights leader, and an Italian priest, Giuseppe
Puglisi, who was killed by the Sicilian Mafia after speaking out
against organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul, whose voice often sounded slurred during the 2{-
hour-long service, used one hand to cradle his head as he listened
to accounts of persecution from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The account of a seminarian in Burundi who survived a 1997
massacre at a seminary in which 40 colleagues were killed was among
the most vivid: ''As we lay in the blood, we prayed and begged
pardon. 'Father, forgive them for they do not know what they are
doing.'''
</P>
<P>
   A Trappist priest stepped forward to tell of a 1996 massacre in
an Algerian monastery during that North African nation's civil war.
</P>
<P>
   A prayer was also said for Oscar Romero, the Salvadoran
archbishop who was assassinated in 1980 after delivering a sermon
asking the military to halt its repressive tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to his years preparing for the priesthood as a young
man in Poland during World War II, John Paul said: ''I myself am a
witness of much pain and many trials,'' and he noted that in Dachau
concentration camp alone, 3,000 priests were interned.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Christians honored on Sunday the pope said: ''The names
of many are unknown; the names of some have been denigrated by
their persecutors, who tried to add disgrace to martyrdom; the
names of others have been concealed by their executioners.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope mentioned two modern martyrs by name: Orthodox
Metropolitan Benjamin, from St. Petersburg, martyred in 1922 in the
upheaval that followed the Russian Revolution, and Lutheran Pastor
Paul Schneider, who spoke of his faith to those guarding his cell
in Buchenwald concentration camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
