<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Child of Wartime Rape Seeking Home  </HEADLINE>
By DANICA KIRKA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIZREN, Yugoslavia (AP) -- It's hard to imagine that no one in
Kosovo wants to adopt Arta.
</P>
<P>
   This healthy 3-month-old with pale blue eyes kicks up her toes
when strangers enter the maternity ward at Prizren's hospital,
gurgling cheerfully and grabbing outstretched fingers. She
recognizes the nurses that hover around her white steel crib making
faces, rewarding them with an open toothless smile.
</P>
<P>
   Still, prospective parents pass her by. After all, her history
is known: She is the daughter of an ethnic Albanian teen-ager raped
by a Serb soldier during Kosovo's war.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager's father snatched Arta from her weeping
17-year-old mother's bed soon after she was born. Without
discussion, he signed the papers that put her up for adoption and
pointedly told Dr. Fellanza Gjergjizi that she was a child of rape.
</P>
<P>
   Arta was not welcome under his roof, and during the months
since, it has become clear that the only place she is wanted is
this hospital 55 miles south of the capital, Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one really wants these children,'' Gjergjizi said. ''They
say, 'Who knows about the father?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights workers like Corey Levine of the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe describe Kosovo's children of
rape as a ''lost group.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Communities are not going to accept them -- nobody is going to
accept them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   No one really knows how many children resulted from rapes
committed during Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's campaign
of repression in this southern province, a crackdown that ended
after a 78-day NATO air campaign and the arrival of peacekeepers in
June.
</P>
<P>
   Even discounting the fact that the rapist in this case was a
Serb, hated by most ethnic Albanians, the stigma attached to rape
is so strong -- particularly in Kosovo's rural hinterlands -- that
few women will ever reveal they were attacked, much less that a
child resulted. Abortion is available here, and human rights
workers say women have taken advantage of it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, rights workers point to anecdotal evidence that the
children of rape are out there. Some of the evidence comes from
scattered reports of abandoned infants -- virtually unknown before
the war in this society where extended families traditionally step
in to provide care for children if anything happens to their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. police have noted a handful of cases in recent weeks. In
the capital, Pristina, the U.S. humanitarian group Save the
Children said the main hospital held 24 abandoned children at one
point after the end of the bloodshed, though only nine now remain.
</P>
<P>
   At Prizren's hospital, Gjergjizi said that before the war, she
might have a single case of an abandoned child all year. Since
then, though, she's had nine instances in which mothers simply left
the hospital after giving birth, walking away without a word -- and
without their infant.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the babies, the hospital was able to find adoptive
parents because pediatricians could honestly say they had no
details about the conception.
</P>
<P>
   The admission by the teen-ager's father is what makes Arta's
case different from the 3-week-old girl that lies in the
neighboring crib. For the other girl, no background was offered by
the mother before she left the child behind.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not her fault that she was born into this situation,''
Gjergjizi said of Arta.
</P>
<P>
   Nurses in Prizren like Lulijeta Bajra, Lule Krasniqi and Igballe
Gygjin have been doing their best to be surrogate mothers, offering
a simple hug to the little girl whose home for now is at the end of
the row by the door.
</P>
<P>
   The other infants may sleep in bare cribs, but Arta's has
decorations: a pink bunny, a purple and green elephant, and a
garland of plastic teething toys. Her crib is also the only one
with a name -- a piece of masking tape with 'Arta' written in large
block letters. She gets to squirm in footed pajamas decorated with
blue kittens. The other kids just get wrapped in white blankets.
</P>
<P>
   The nurses can only offer the little signs of affection, though,
and know their long-term patient should move out soon. Gjergjizi
hopes that Arta can find a home abroad, far from the stigma that
would cloud her future here.
</P>
<P>
   ''If anyone wants her, please take her, because no one here
will,'' Gjergjizi said. ''She would have a better life outside
Kosovo. No one will know what happened. It's better that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
