<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Gladiator' Tops Box Office  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN, AP Entertainment Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- For movie-goers, all roads led to Rome and
''Gladiator.''
</P>
<P>
   Director Ridley Scott's spectacle of ancient Roman gore and
glory topped the box office with $32.7 million in its opening
weekend, according to studio estimates Sunday. The movie starring
Russell Crowe grossed more than the next six movies combined.
</P>
<P>
   ''U-571,'' the top movie for the previous two weekends, dropped
to second place with $7.6 million. The sci-fi thriller
''Frequency'' remained at No. 3 in its second weekend with $6.5
million, while ''The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas'' slipped two
spots to No. 4 with $6.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   In ''Gladiator,'' Hollywood's first Roman epic since the 1960s,
Crowe stars as a general who falls into slavery but uses his combat
skills to become a hero gladiator and seek revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Using digital effects, the movie recreates Roman pageantry on a
level that dwarfs such classics as ''Ben-Hur'' and ''Spartacus.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a real Roman epic, the kind of spectacle that hasn't
been made in 30-plus years,'' said Jim Tharp, head of distribution
for DreamWorks, which released ''Gladiator.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie did not approach any records by other pre-summer
blockbusters that had PG or PG-13 ratings. With an R rating and a
running time of 2 hours, 30 minutes, DreamWorks ''thought it would
be very difficult to hit $30 million'' in the opening weekend,
Tharp said.
</P>
<P>
   ''DreamWorks really built up excitement for this movie,'' said
Paul Dergarabedian, president of box-office tracker Exhibitor
Relations. ''The trailers they showed were very effective in
getting audiences psyched, and the movie had all the elements
people were looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's other big new movie, Kim Basinger's ''I Dreamed of
Africa,'' was a bust with $2.5 million for eighth place. Based on a
real story, the movie follows a woman's adventures and heartbreaks
in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in 2,112 theaters, ''I Dreamed of Africa'' averaged a
weak $1,184 per cinema, compared with $11,130 in 2,938 theaters for
''Gladiator.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Kim got very good reviews, but unfortunately, the film as a
whole did not,'' said Ed Russell, executive vice president for
publicity at Sony, which released ''I Dreamed of Africa.'' ''Adult,
female films like this are really driven by good, solid reviews.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimated ticket sales for Friday through Sunday at North
American theaters, according to Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc.:
</P>
<P>
   1. ''Gladiator,'' $32.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   2. ''U-571,'' $7.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   3. ''Frequency,'' $6.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   4. ''The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas,'' $6.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   5. ''Where the Heart Is,'' $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   6. ''Love and Basketball,'' $3.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   7. ''Keeping the Faith,'' $2.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   8. ''I Dreamed of Africa,'' $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   9. ''Rules of Engagement,'' $2.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   10. ''28 Days,'' $2.35 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
