<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Editors, Publishers To Meet in NYC  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Member publishers and editors of The Associated
Press gathered today for a report on the news cooperative, a panel
on the 2000 election and talks by Vice President Al Gore and
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright.
</P>
<P>
   The annual meeting and luncheon are attended by executives
representing AP's 1,546 member newspapers. They are the major
events of the first full day of activities of the Newspaper
Association of America's convention.
</P>
<P>
   AP chairman Donald E. Newhouse was to call the meeting to order
and president and chief executive officer Louis D. Boccardi was to
report on the state of AP.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting also will include the announcement of election
results for the board of directors, held by all-mail balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Boccardi also was to moderate a discussion of political
campaigns with three AP correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the news cooperative also were expected to hear
from Alan Diaz, the photographer who took the AP photographs inside
the house where 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez was seized by federal
agents late last month.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, titled ''A Conversation: Campaign 2000,'' includes
Walter Mears, AP vice president and Washington columnist; Ron
Fournier, chief political writer in Washington; and Marc A.
Humbert, New York State political editor based in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was scheduled to speak after the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Albright was the featured speaker at the luncheon following the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   There were 10 candidates for six board seats -- five full 3-year
terms and the one year remaining when a member stepped down. Two
candidates ran in a separate election to represent a city of less
than 50,000 population.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
