<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Shuts Down Los Alamos Lab  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE ROCK, N.M. (AP) -- A fire intended to improve the watershed
in Bandelier National Monument was burning out of control late
Sunday near Los Alamos, shutting down the Los Alamos National
Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ''We could see the flames up in the mountains,'' said Edwina
Cisneros, who was evacuated from a mobile home park where she was
visiting her parents. ''It didn't look that far away, so we were
pretty scared.''
</P>
<P>
   No injuries had been reported from that fire or another blaze in
south-central New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Lab spokesman John Gustafson said the blaze had spread to Water
Canyon on the lab's western boundary near a work site. The site is
where much of the lab's work with high explosives is conducted, but
officials said all explosives had been put in fire-resistant
bunkers.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the fire has not approached any areas where
radioactive materials are stored.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not close enough to'' threaten any structures, Gustafson
said. ''But it's close enough (for us) to take some precautionary
moves.''
</P>
<P>
   A news release from the lab said only workers engaged in
emergency response or other critical activities should report to
work Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, a bank teller in Los Alamos who was with her
2-year-old son Kyle, was sent to the White Rock Baptist Church to
join about a dozen other evacuees. Pastor Chuck McCullough said the
church can hold about 200 people and will refer the people to
church families.
</P>
<P>
   The Bandelier fire, about 70 miles north of Albuquerque, has
burned about 1,000 acres, said State Forestry Division spokeswoman
Terri Wildermuth. Residents in western Los Alamos and some campers
were asked to leave the area.
</P>
<P>
   The monument is known for its ancient Indian dwellings and
artifacts. The National Park Service had planned to burn about 900
acres in the area, but dry, windy conditions pushed it out of
control. It was subdued Saturday, but shifting winds reignited the
blaze Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In south-central New Mexico, another fire in Ruidoso burned an
estimated 400 acres and forced the evacuation of about 150 homes on
Sunday, said Lincoln Zone Interagency Prevention Team spokeswoman
Gwen Shaffer. Winds were blowing the fire away from town, but it
did destroy at least three homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
