<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Refugees Brace for Hardship  </HEADLINE>
By PRISCILLA CHEUNG, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Dinh Thi Yen, born nine years ago in Hong Kong,
speaks perfect Cantonese, the territory's official dialect. But her
classmates never let her forget she doesn't belong.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kids beat me up at school because I'm Vietnamese,'' the
second-grader says.
</P>
<P>
   Thi Yen has grown up in the Pillar Point refugee camp,
surrounded by barbed-wire and close to drab warehouses and a
dockyard in a remote corner of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   The government is closing the camp May 31, but the refugees
regard that as a mixed blessing. The closure will force 1,100
Vietnamese residents out into the mainstream of Hong Kong, with its
notoriously steep rents and its market for unskilled labor
particularly tight as the territory recovers from a bruising
recession.
</P>
<P>
   The government calls the closure a ''humanitarian solution,''
for both the refugees and their Hong Kong-born children, who have
known no home but the camp.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is better for them to be able to integrate into the
society,'' says Brenda Ku, a camp supervisor with Caritas-Hong
Kong, the Roman Catholic charity that runs Pillar Point. ''They
would really welcome the new policy if they didn't have to worry
about potential financial problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Closing the camp, which is free to refugees, will officially end
the odyssey of Hong Kong's boat people, the Vietnamese who began
fleeing their homeland when the communist North defeated the
U.S.-backed South in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   About 1 million Vietnamese fled to neighboring countries on foot
or by boat to escape political persecution and poverty. Hong Kong,
then a British colony, gave unconditional asylum to people awaiting
resettlement in the West until 1988, when it added a screening
process to separate political and economic refugees. The latter
were eventually sent home.
</P>
<P>
   Phan Thi Van's family pawned six gold rings for her 20-day
passage with 40 strangers in a rickety fishing junk on the high
seas in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   She was detained as an economic refugee, an illegal immigrant,
but before she could be deported, Phan married a political refugee
and gained the right to stay in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Now 30, Phan says she and her three children -- ages 1 to 6 --
will have to rely solely on her husband's income as a part-time
construction worker when they leave the camp. And they don't know
where they will live.
</P>
<P>
   A camp bulletin board offers neat rows of notices for low-paying
construction and factory jobs and tiny apartments. One hardly pays
for the other. Factory workers typically earn $500 to 1,000 a
month, but monthly rents for one-bedroom apartments in urban areas
are at least $1,000. Even in outlying districts, small apartments
run close to $500.
</P>
<P>
   Phan's husband takes home the equivalent of $230 each day he
works, but he usually gets only four or five days of work a month.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm worried sick. But what can I do?'' Phan says. ''I can't
work because I have to look after the children.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial worries are not the refugees' only concerns as they
prepare to leave the camp's familiar confines. Discrimination
against the Vietnamese and other migrants such as Filipinos and
Indians is rife in Hong Kong. Refugees complain that shopkeepers
are rude, and the media often poke fun at them.
</P>
<P>
   ''Local kids don't play with me,'' Thi Yen says casually as she
dances around a wooden pushcart with her friends.
</P>
<P>
   The government is granting residency rights to the displaced
camp occupants. They had already been free to leave the camp and
work outside, but many chose to stay, despite the camp's
inconvenient location and occasional violence.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as the mid-1990s, 5,000 people were packed into the
two- and three-story barracks. Crime was common, and the close
quarters led to sporadic brawls, especially between south and north
Vietnamese. Last June, eight people were injured and a building was
set on fire by a gasoline bomb in a clash at Pillar Point.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter visited recently, the camp was clean and
orderly. Children played tag and soccer while men chatted outside
their houses. Vietnamese music with operatic vocals drifted from
barrack windows. Aromas of sizzling Vietnamese eggrolls and
dumplings filled the air.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 223,000 Vietnamese refugees have passed through Hong Kong
since the war ended in 1975. About 144,000 gained asylum abroad,
mostly in the United States, Canada and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong granted permanent status to some, but mounting
political pressure and financial strain forced the government to
scrap its asylum policy in 1998. It closed government-run camps and
sent most of the remaining refugees back to Vietnam if they
couldn't show that would put them at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Most Vietnamese still stranded in Hong Kong are classified as
political refugees and theoretically qualify for political asylum
abroad. But realistically, few have prospects of resettling because
they have no relatives to sponsor them or they have criminal
records and drug abuse problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
