<DOCNO> APW20000508.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore: Hitting His Marks for TV  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The forward hatch of Air Force Two operates a
bit like a stage curtain: On the outer side of the threshold, Al
Gore is in pressed pants and hairspray. Inside, the man the Secret
Service code-named ''Sundance'' pads about in flip-flops and short
shorts, with a briefing book or cold Heineken in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Those who hold backstage passes to Campaign 2000 hear the
question a lot: What's Gore really like? Glimpses behind the
curtain offer some surprising answers -- like goofy.
</P>
<P>
   In a receiving line of VIPs at the snowy Rochester, N.Y.,
airport, the vice president encountered the insolent pout of
2-year-old Emily Forth. Instead of saying hello and moving on, Gore
mimicked her pose -- eyes narrowed, lower lip stuck out -- and made a
game of it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to count to 10,'' he told the tot, as nervous pilots
waited to get him aboard to begin deicing. ''I bet I can make you
smile before I get to 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Gore's playfully stern stare, Emily made it to four before
dissolving in a giggle.
</P>
<P>
   Before speeches, Gore regularly does an offstage shuffling dance
-- to loosen up, he explained to aides. In private, he sings country
tunes on-key but with such an exaggerated twang that he can sound
like a baying hound dog.
</P>
<P>
   A master practical joker, Gore approved the wallpapering of a
corridor in the New Orleans Fairmont Hotel with photocopied posters
noting the resemblance between campaign press secretary Chris
Lehane and TV's Eddie Munster.
</P>
<P>
   At other moments, it's easy to see how this famously robotic
politician got his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   In the high-tech control room of Covad, a firm in California's
Silicon Valley, Gore stood at an ''X'' marked in masking tape on
the floor for a round robin of quickie interviews with five local
TV news crews.
</P>
<P>
   ''Two-camera shoot?'' he asked a pair from KRON-Channel 4 as he
expertly clipped a microphone to his tie and tucked its wire out of
sight. A former journalist, Gore is a pro talking to cameras and
can turn himself on or off as if flipping a switch.
</P>
<P>
   Between interviews, he zoned out, staring into space and
whistling. A loud ''Ahem'' from Lehane roused Gore from his reverie
and he was back, giving KTVU-Channel 2 an impassioned spiel on
school violence.
</P>
<P>
   In another scene, in the back seat of his limousine, Gore
rattled off Social Security statistics and talking points against
Republican presidential rival George W. Bush, all the while keeping
an eye on the window for people to wave to.
</P>
<P>
   At his foot was the nylon cooler bag his valet keeps at the
ready with a cold soda, hairbrush, spray (Gore is said to be
obsessed with the growing bald spot at his crown) and small bath
towel.
</P>
<P>
   Prone to profuse sweating, Gore learned on New Hampshire primary
night -- when he nearly went on live television with a shred of
tissue pasted to his damp cheek -- that terry cloth is better for
toweling off.
</P>
<P>
   It could be body heat that explains why Gore changes into
running shorts even for brief flights on a plane kept so chilly
that some people wrap themselves in blankets.
</P>
<P>
   Or, it could be vanity.
</P>
<P>
   At 52, he doggedly maintains his marathon runner's legs and
wears his sweaters tucked in at the waist where they show off the
fruits of traveling with an ''Ab roller,'' a set of weights and a
fitness book, ''The Pilates Body.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore sucks in his stomach when he knows cameras are watching and
his ramrod-straight posture -- a ballerina's envy, except that his
is punctuated by size 10{-wide feet -- never slips.
</P>
<P>
   A peek at his private daily schedule reveals ''attire notes''
for each stop so he will never be over- or underdressed.
</P>
<P>
   As his motorcade headed to the Manchester, N.H., American Legion
hall, the candidate had an aide radio ahead to see if veterans
there were wearing their Legion hats. (Gore, who served five months
in Vietnam as an Army reporter, travels with his.) The message that
came back: Only a few hats. ''We recommend he go sans chapeau.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore devours every word written about him and, even weeks later,
can recite a reporter's exact wording in phrases that delighted or
offended him.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is to suggest he is entirely self-absorbed. Despite
a host of aides, Gore lugged his grandson's car seat and diaper bag
off the plane after a recent flight.
</P>
<P>
   Markedly unlike President Clinton, Gore considers it rude to be
more than 12 minutes late for any occasion and longtime aides
report never having heard him raise his voice.
</P>
<P>
   He reprimands with low, icy utterances and often evades
questions he doesn't like by questioning his questioner -- menacing
and well-meaning alike.
</P>
<P>
   One Clinton habit does show up in Gore.
</P>
<P>
   At the Milford, N.H., Riverhouse Cafe, Gore ate fingers-to-mouth
from the pile of corned beef hash warming on the grill while he
used the kitchen phone to talk with ESPN radio. He waved off the
appalled chef's insistence upon a plate and fork.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 0146 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000508.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> D.C. Building Becoming Luxury Hotel  </HEADLINE>
By CARL HARTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Designed by the architects of the Capitol and
the Washington Monument, the city's first marble building -- 161
years old and boarded up for the last five -- will reopen next year
as a luxury hotel with a subsidy from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ''Preservation goes beyond simple restoration -- it means
realizing a building's full potential as this new plan will do,''
said Richard Moe, president of the National Trust for Historic
Preservation.
</P>
<P>
   The company doing the job, at an estimated cost of $32 million,
will get a federal tax credit of about $3.2 million to restore the
Tariff Building. The trust noted that businesses can earn such
restoration credits for as much as 20 percent of the cost of a
project.
</P>
<P>
   An effort to get a similar credit for restoring private houses,
with a cap of $20,000 or $50,000, is pending in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''So many historic houses are in rundown and decaying
neighborhoods,'' said Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., a sponsor of
the legislation. ''The restoration and preservation of such houses
is just as important as other types of historic rescue.''
</P>
<P>
   Planners hope the new hotel will help restore a neighborhood,
once the center of Washington's downtown, that went downhill but is
showing signs of revival. Nearby structures include the National
Portrait Gallery, National Museum of American Art, the Shakespeare
Theatre and the new MCI Center arena for sports and other events. A
department store and other nearby buildings have been closed for
years.
</P>
<P>
   The building that the hotel will occupy once housed the federal
Tariff Commission. For most of the 1800s it was national
headquarters of the Post Office, and the first U.S. stamps, money
orders and post cards were developed there.
</P>
<P>
   The Tariff Building occupies a square block between E and F
Streets and 7th and 8th Streets in the capital's northwest
quadrant. The federal General Services Administration has started a
$5 million cleanup of the three-story structure, including the
massive Greek columns and two historic plaques.
</P>
<P>
   One plaque tells how on the building site in 1845, Samuel F.B.
Morse opened and operated the first public office in the United
States for sending messages by wire. It adds, in quotation marks,
the biblical text ''What hath God wrought,'' the first message
Morse sent from the Capitol to Baltimore the year before, over the
first American intercity telegraph line.
</P>
<P>
   The other plaque tells of Washington's first theatrical
performance in a building on the site, and how Congress met there
after British troops burned the Capitol in 1814.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mills, who designed the Treasury Building and the
Washington Monument, drew up the plans for the first part of the
Tariff Building in 1839. Thomas Walter began extending it in 1855,
and later also added the wings and dome to the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The government has leased the building for 60 years to the
Kimpton Hotel and Restaurant Group, which has two hotels in San
Francisco and one in Seattle. The group plans to turn the offices
into a 172-room upscale hotel.
</P>
<P>
   A restaurant will open in the old courtyard, reached from the
street by the original cobblestone carriageway.
</P>
<P>
   The national trust has scheduled a ceremony to ''unboard'' the
building Thursday, formally opening the door and linking the
project to its Historic Preservation Week, which starts May 14.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 0147 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
