<DOCNO> APW20000508.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebels Halt Advance in Sierra Leone  </HEADLINE>
By ALEXANDRA ZAVIS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Rebel and U.N. leaders insist
there is no cause for alarm after weekend fighting upset Sierra
Leone's fragile peace process.
</P>
<P>
   However, hundreds of U.N. personnel were still being held
hostage by rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the rebel Revolutionary United Front and U.N.
officials flew together by helicopter Sunday to check out the area
where their forces clashed a day earlier in this West African
nation.
</P>
<P>
   No rebel soldiers could be seen along the route in central
Sierra Leone, and there were no signs of violence, said Brig. Gen.
Mohammed Garba, a U.N. deputy force commander. The group traveled
from just outside the capital, Freetown, to the town of Lunsar, 50
miles to the northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to assure the general public that there is no cause for
alarm,'' Garba said Sunday. He called the trip a
''confidence-building mission'' following an erroneous U.N. report
the day before that rebels had advanced to Freetown's edge.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the trip was longtime rebel official Col. Laurence
Wormandia, who said the clash between his forces and U.N. soldiers
happened 60 miles east of Freetown, at the key crossroad town of
Rogberi. The government then sent a helicopter gunship to the
fight, and fired ''a substantial amount of rockets at the RUF,''
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Wormandia said the advance began Saturday after media reports
filtered back to rebel fighters that Foday Sankoh, the RUF leader
seen as a semi-deity by many of his followers, had been placed
under house arrest in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   ''They wanted to come as far as'' Freetown, Wormandia said
Sunday, adding that Sankoh then radioed his commanders and ordered
them to stop the advance. Sankoh was not officially under house
arrest Sunday, but his home was surrounded by U.N. troops.
</P>
<P>
   Garba, who appealed to Sankoh on Saturday to halt his forces,
said the rebels then ''melted away,'' into the jungle after the
rebel leader's calls.
</P>
<P>
   In the past week, hundreds of U.N. personnel have been taken
hostage by the rebels, and at least one is presumed dead following
the clashes, Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
   The number went up Saturday, when the U.N. said it had had lost
contact with a 200-man peacekeeper unit. If those peacekeepers --
all Zambian -- have been captured by the rebels, it would bring the
numbers of RUF hostages to nearly 500.
</P>
<P>
   Why they were seized remained unclear Sunday, and the rebels
continued to deny they had taken the U.N. staff hostage.
</P>
<P>
   British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook suggested that it was the
peacekeepers' moves toward Sierra Leone's diamond-rich regions --
long controlled by the rebels -- that could be at the root of the
confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the cause, nerves remained deeply frayed in Sierra
Leone, where an 8-year civil war ended in July with a peace accord
that brought the rebels -- in principle -- into a power-sharing
government.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials insisted that Freetown remained well-protected,
with 2,100 U.N. troops in the capital -- 500 Jordanians and 1,600
Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
   However, President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah expressed disappointment
at the way U.N. soldiers ''capitulated'' to rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
   ''But we have not yet reached the stage where we believe the
U.N. is incapable of fulfilling of its mandate,'' he said in a
speech broadcast on state radio.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to revive morale among the peacekeepers and follow the
crisis more closely, the head of U.N. peacekeeping operations,
Bernard Miyet, was expected to arrive in Freetown on Tuesday,
Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of people, including aid workers, missionaries and
other civilians, have been evacuated in recent days. On Sunday, the
United States and Britain reduced the number of embassy staff and
advised or helped their citizens to leave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 0151 </TRAILER>
