<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia, N.Korea Resume Relations  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN THORNHILL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) -- Australia restored diplomatic
relations with North Korea on Monday, joining a handful of Western
nations that have established new ties with the reclusive communist
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Alexander Downer announced the resumption of
diplomatic representation, effective immediately, nearly 25 years
after ties were severed. Officials from the two countries had been
holding meetings on resuming ties since last September.
</P>
<P>
   The development ''is a positive contribution to improved
relations among countries in the Asia-Pacific region and to
strengthening regional linkages,'' Downer said in a statement. ''I
trust it will also add impetus to the spirit of dialogue and
compromise on the Korean peninsula.''
</P>
<P>
   Downer said Australia and North Korea would appoint ambassadors
soon. In the meantime, Australia's ambassador in Beijing would be
in charge of North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Australia and North Korea set up diplomatic ties July 31, 1974,
but cut them Nov. 8, 1975, in circumstances that have never been
fully explained.
</P>
<P>
   Australia became the second nation this year to normalize ties
with Pyongyang after Italy established relations in January.
</P>
<P>
   Japan and the United States have also been in talks aimed at
normalizing diplomatic ties with North Korea, but no accords have
been reached.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate announcement Monday, Australian Prime Minister
John Howard said he would visit South Korea from May 19-21 for
talks to strengthen economic and political ties with that country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
