<HEADLINE> Dow Up 48; Nasdaq Down 75  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today as investors worried
about rising interest rates and took some profits from Friday's
market rally. Blue-chip stocks shook off early weakness and turned
higher on the surprising strength of financial shares.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 48.27 at 10,626.13.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were lower. The Nasdaq composite index
was down 75.82 at 3,741.00 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
down 4.33 at 1,428.30.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said many investors were selling stocks to capture
short-term gains from a solid rally on Friday, when the Dow rose
165 points and the Nasdaq rose 96 points. With interest rate
worries settling over Wall Street, many investors appeared
reluctant to take significant new positions. Trading was extremely
light.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve is expected to raise interest rates by as
much as a half-percentage point at its next meeting on May 16. The
Fed has raised interest rates five times since last June in a
series of modest, quarter-percentage point hikes.
</P>
<P>
   Rising interest rates are generally bad for stocks because they
cut into corporate profits by increasing the cost of borrowing
money. This time around, however, many analysts believe a heftier
increase could mollify investors because it might signify that the
Fed is nearing the end of its cycle of rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks, which led Friday's rally, were mostly lower
today. Hewlett-Packard fell 3[ to 133| and Intel fell 3 to 120].
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems fell 3 3/16 to 87 5/16 and PMC-Sierra fell 5}
to 174\.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, many analysts expect those technology stocks -- among
the most established and best-capitalized -- to regain leadership of
the market.
</P>
<P>
   ''Within this environment of lingering interest rate concerns,
we believe stock selection ought to focus on those companies with
strong earnings momentum,'' said John H. Shaughnessy, chief
investment strategist at Advest Inc. For the most part, Shaughnessy
said, that means technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors remain leery of the volatile technology sector.
Cisco fell 3] to 64] after an article in Barron's said the
company's rapid growth rate could slow if Cisco stops acquiring
companies at a rapid rate.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks shook off interest-rate worries and helped the
Dow turn higher. American Express was up 3~ to 150.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 250.01 million
shares, behind Friday's quiet pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 4.98 to 507.86.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
