<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 92; Dow Falls 5  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly lower today as investors
worried about rising interest rates and took some profits from
Friday's rally. Technology stocks, which fueled Friday's gains, led
the decline today.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 5.22 at 10,572.64.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were lower. The Nasdaq composite index
was down 92.35 at 3,724.47 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
down 7.84 at 1,424.79.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said many investors were selling stocks to capture
short-term gains from a solid rally on Friday, when the Dow rose
165 points and the Nasdaq rose 96. With interest rate worries
settling over Wall Street, many investors appeared reluctant to
take significant new positions. Trading was extremely light.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve is expected to raise interest rates by as
much as a half-percentage point at its next policymaking meeting on
May 16. The Fed has raised interest rates five times since last
June in a series of modest, quarter-percentage point hikes.
</P>
<P>
   Rising interest rates are generally bad for stocks because they
cut into corporate profits by increasing the cost of borrowing
money. This time around, however, many analysts believe a heftier
increase could mollify investors because it might signify that the
Fed is nearing the end of its cycle of rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks were mostly lower today. Hewlett-Packard fell
2| to 134[ and Intel fell 4 9/16 to 118 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems fell 4] to 86[ and PMC-Sierra fell 9 5/16 to
170 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, many analysts expect those technology stocks -- among
the most established and best-capitalized -- to regain leadership of
the market.
</P>
<P>
   ''Within this environment of lingering interest rate concerns,
we believe stock selection ought to focus on those companies with
strong earnings momentum,'' said John H. Shaughnessy, chief
investment strategist at Advest Inc. For the most part, Shaughnessy
said, that means technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors remain leery of the volatile technology sector.
Cisco fell 3 11/16 to 64 1/16 after an article in Barron's said the
company's rapid growth rate could slow if Cisco stops acquiring
companies at a rapid rate.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks shook off interest-rate worries and helped the
Dow contain its losses. American Express was up 3 13/16 to 149
15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 354.45 million
shares, behind Friday's quiet pace.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, decliners led by an 11-to-7 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 6.02 to 506.82.
</P>
