<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Kate,' 'Music Man' Lead Tony Nods  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA, AP Drama Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Broadway celebrated old favorites such as ''Kiss
Me, Kate'' and ''The Music Man,'' while snubbing Disney's ''Aida''
and combative actor Patrick Stewart as the Tony Award nominations
were announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kate,'' a revival of the Cole Porter musical adapted from
Shakespeare's ''Taming of the Shrew,'' walked off with 12
nominations, more than any other show, followed by Meredith
Willson's ''The Music Man,'' which received eight.
</P>
<P>
   They face each other in the best musical-revival category, along
with new productions of ''Jesus Christ Superstar'' and ''Tango
Argentino.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the year of double, triple and, in two cases, quadruple
nominations. Susan Stroman, who directed and choreographed both
''Contact'' and ''The Music Man,'' received four nominations, and
will be competing against herself for best choreography and best
director of a musical. Composer and book writer Michael John
LaChiusa picked up four nominations, two each for his musicals
''Marie Christine'' and ''The Wild Party.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Contact,'' three stories told through dance, faces ''The Wild
Party,'' ''James Joyce's The Dead'' and ''Swing!'' for best
musical, and is the early favorite.
</P>
<P>
   The winners, chosen by more than 700 theater professionals and
journalists, will be announced June 4 on CBS. Rosie O'Donnell will
serve as host.
</P>
<P>
   Left out of the running for the top musical prize was ''Aida,''
Disney's lavish retelling of an ancient Egyptian love triangle,
although its star, Heather Headley, was nominated, as were its
composer and lyricist, Elton John and Tim Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was passed over for his performance as an unrepentant
bigamist in Arthur Miller's ''The Ride Down Mt. Morgan.'' The actor
had sparred publicly with the show's producers over what he
perceived as lack of support for the play.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mt. Morgan'' did get a nomination for best play, along with
''Copenhagen,'' Michael Frayn's drama about the controversial
meeting of two physicists on opposite sides during World War II;
''Dirty Blonde,'' Claudia Shear's warm-hearted biography of sex
symbol Mae West; and ''True West,'' Sam Shepard's savage 1970s
comedy about two battling brothers that already has had two
productions off-Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   For actor, nominators picked the two stars of ''True West,''
Philip Seymour Hoffman and John C. Reilly; Gabriel Byrne, who
portrays a dissolute actor in ''A Moon for the Misbegotten'';
Stephan Dillane, the adulterous writer in ''The Real Thing''; and
David Suchet, who plays Mozart's rival in ''Amadeus.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Stewart, also shut out of acting nominations were such
names as Derek Jacobi and Roger Rees of ''Uncle Vanya'' and the two
stars of the critically praised ''Copenhagen,'' Philip Bosco and
Michael Cumpsty.
</P>
<P>
   The entire cast of ''Dirty Blonde'' -- Claudia Shear, Kevin
Chamberlain and Bob Stillman -- was nominated in various acting
categories.
</P>
<P>
   For best actress, Shear, who plays Mae West in the show, will
compete against a mother-daughter match-up: Rosemary Harris, who
stars in Noel Coward's ''Waiting in the Wings,'' and her daughter,
Jennifer Ehle, who appears in ''The Real Thing.'' Also nominated
were Cherry Jones, from ''A Moon for the Misbegotten; and Jayne
Atkinson of ''The Rainmaker.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 1427 </TRAILER>
