<HEADLINE> European Stocks Close Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed lower Monday on low volume
as fears over the telecommunications sector hit bourses while
losses on the Nasdaq Composite weighed on technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Markets across Europe fell in early trading, dragged down by
technology and telecom losses.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is surprising that the markets did start down after Wall
Street's positive close (Friday),'' said Ben Funnell, strategist at
Merrill Lynch. ''But then some of the U.S. data released was not
great and many on Wall Street are beginning to predict'' a
half-percentage point interest rate hike.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom names fell across Europe from the beginning of trade as
the breakdown of merger talks between KPN of the Netherlands and
Spain's Telefonica sapped investor confidence in a sector already
hurt by the high prices of mobile phone licenses.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a lot of negative sentiment out there, and that is
unlikely to change in the near future,'' said Steve Trowbridge,
telecom analyst at Teather &AMP; Greenwood. ''Investors just do not
know what the bill is yet -- there is a lot of uncertainty.''
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts predict a week of range-trading across Europe,
with little news to push the market either way; although the
European Central Bank Governing Council meeting will provide some
focus on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks companies in
countries that joined the single currency, was down 4.2 points at
441.3. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index was down 66.6 points at
5,285.
</P>
<P>
   London's FTSE-100 Share Index fell 0.4 percent to 6,216.3;
Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index fell 1.6 percent to 7,408.09; Paris'
CAC-40 Index was down 0.5 percent to 6,514.42; Milan's MIBtel Index
was down 0.6 percent; Amsterdam's AEX Index was down 0.2 percent to
668.87.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
