<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain To Talk Reform With Bush  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Two months after ''Super Tuesday'' decided
their presidential primary fight, the vanquished and the victor are
finally meeting. And John McCain still wants to talk reform with
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's said he's a reformer with results,'' McCain says ''That's
his slogan. I'd like to know what those are and how I can be
helpful in achieving a reform agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said on Monday, the day before the former Republican
rivals' meeting, ''I'm confident we'll have a conversation that
will cover a lot of subjects, none more important than reform,
reform of our Social Security system.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I look forward to talking to John about education and campaign
funding reform,'' he added. ''I don't anticipate any changes on his
part or my part, but there's a lot of area for us on which to agree
and I look forward to having that discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and the Texas governor are planning to meet without any
of their staff present. The Arizona senator isn't expected to
endorse Bush on Tuesday, but wait until a separate event later in
the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that whether we have an endorsement tomorrow or not is
really not what's important,'' Bush said. ''What's important is to
sit down and visit. He has said over and over that he's going to
support me as the nominee of the Republican Party and I take him at
his word.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men's primary campaign included sharp disagreement on
rules covering contributions to political campaigns. McCain favors
greater restriction.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, in comments to the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette, said anew
that he did not want to be Bush's vice-presidential running mate,
but he wouldn't rule out all possible posts in a potential Bush
administration, such as defense secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've made it clear I'd prefer to stay in the United States
Senate,'' said McCain. But he added, ''For me to start ruling out
every possibility would be just foolish. You can't say I would
refuse to serve in one of those capacities. It's not the same as
vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would urge Bush to appoint Colin Powell, the former
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, as secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said there would be ''no demands, no negotiation'' with
Bush when they meet privately at a Pittsburgh hotel.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believes Bush will defeat Vice President Al Gore in
November and will be a ''great president.'' The meeting Tuesday
will help determine how enthusiastically he supports the campaign,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are more things that we agree on than we disagree on,
and I believe he would be a good president of the United States,''
McCain said. ''There is no point in me looking back in rancor or
anger or bitterness in the campaign. It's over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
