<HEADLINE> AM-NJ--Students Sickened, 1st Ld-Writethru,150  </HEADLINE>
Tests confirm that 'date rape' drug sickened four Raritan students
<TEXT>
<P>
   RARITAN TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) -- Laboratory tests confirm that the
so-called ''date rape'' drug sickened four students at Hunterdon
Central Regional High School in March, police said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Hunterdon County authorities await results from urine tests of
the students before determining whether to file charges, Capt.
Glenn S. Tabasko said.
</P>
<P>
   A 15-year-old boy lost consciousness and the others, two girls,
ages 16 and 14, and a 16-year-old boy, became ill after drinking a
liquid substance that the 16-year-old boy had brought to school the
morning of March 29, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The ninth- and 10th-graders were treated at Hunterdon Medical
Center and released later that day, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey State Police lab found the substance to be the
designer drug gamma hydroxybutyrate, or GHB, a depressant some use
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-08-00 1455 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
