<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grand Marnier Files Trademark Suit  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- To the makers of Grand Marnier liquor, the
proof of their trademark claim against Silver Palate Kitchens Inc.
is right on the label: ''Fudge Sauce Grand Marnier.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cressville, N.J.-based Silver Palate does not have
permission to use the Grand Marnier name, according to the
Paris-based maker of the liquor, Societe des Produits
Marnier-Lapostelle.
</P>
<P>
   The French company filed a trademark infringement lawsuit last
month in U.S. District Court here against Silver Palate, seeking
unspecified monetary damages and an order barring Silver Palate
from using the Grand Marnier name.
</P>
<P>
   ''They can't trade on the reputation or the quality without
getting the consent or getting the license,'' Michael S. Elkin, a
lawyer for Marnier-Lapostelle, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Through an aide, Joyce Hunt, Silver Palate president Peter
Harris said Monday that he believes there should be no lawsuit and
that it is an error. Hunt declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Palate is known for its packaged goods and The Silver
Palate Cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   The label on the sauce, reproduced in the lawsuit, describes the
product as, ''A dark rich sauce with lots of Grand Marnier. Perfect
on chocolate, vanilla or orange ice cream. Pour over cream puffs,
eclairs, dessert souffles, cheesecake or fresh berries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
