</P>
<P>
   Treasury Urges Low-Cost Banking
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration will propose this
week a $30 million plan to help low-income people open low-cost,
basic bank accounts, Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said
today. An estimated 10 percent of U.S. households do not have bank
accounts. They are predominantly poor and minority and often
elderly or disabled, according to government officials. Among the
reasons: rising bank and ATM fees, the closing of bank branches in
poor city neighborhoods and rural towns, and mistrust of banks in
general. The administration has noted that the ''unbanked''
population often falls prey to storefront check-cashing services
that charge excessive fees.
</P>
<P>
   Polymer Cos. Plan $570M Merger
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Geon Co. and M.A. Hanna Co. are merging in a
$570 million deal that company officials say will form the world's
largest polymer services company. The combination links Geon's
manufacturing strengths with Hanna's experience in making and
distributing polymer products, which can be plastics, rubber,
resins and industrial film. Geon's specialty is vinyl plastics.
When combined, the companies expect to benefit from raw materials
savings, market-related opportunities and overhead reductions by
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo SmithKline Merger Gets OK'd
</P>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Commission today approved
the merger between British pharmaceutical companies Glaxo Wellcome
PLC and SmithKline Beecham PLC, which will make it the world's
largest pharmaceuticals firm. The EU's executive office made the
approval conditional upon the companies' agreeing to either sell
off certain drug licensing agreements or voluntarily license some
drug trademark rights to competitors within the European market.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan Backs China Trade Bill
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a united stand, three former presidents
today joined President Clinton in giving Congress a strong push to
grant China permanent trade benefits. The pact also won an
endorsement from Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan. ''In
economic terms, the case is clear,'' said Presidents Ford, Carter
and Bush. Greenspan, in a letter to House Banking and Financial
Services Chairman James Leach, R-Iowa, said he believed passage of
the legislation was ''in the interests of the United States.''
Labor unions and the two top House Democratic leaders are fighting
the legislation, suggesting it will hurt U.S. jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Taps Sears As CFO
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Michael Sears, a 30-year veteran of The Boeing
Co., was appointed today as the aerospace giant's chief financial
officer. Sears, 52, was most recently the president of the
company's $13 billion military division and also served in the
commercial aircraft and space divisions. He replaces Debby Hopkins,
the popular CFO credited for a rapid financial turnaround at
Boeing, who recently took a similar job at Lucent Technologies Inc.
Walt Skowronski, vice president of finance and treasurer, had been
appointed acting CFO.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's NTT Buying ISP Verio
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- NTT Communications Corp. has agreed to buy U.S.
Internet service provider and Web hosting company Verio Inc., for
about $5 billion in cash. The news sent Verio's shares soared on
the news. Its stock was up 22 7/16 or 62 percent at 58] in
afternoon trading today. NTT Communications, a long-distance
telephone service provider and subsidiary of telecommunications
giant Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp., has been expanding its
global network, focusing on Asia, to meet growing demand for
high-speed data services over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi Studies Hyundai Alliance
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Mitsubishi Motors Corp. and DaimlerChrysler AG both
denied today that they had reached a production alliance with
Hyundai Motor Co., despite statements affirming an agreement from
Hyundai's president. A Mitsubishi spokesman downplayed statements
yesterday by Hyundai president Lee Kye-ahn, who said that the three
automakers had agreed on the terms of an alliance to jointly
develop a small car. Mitsubishi's Masayuki Sekino said today in an
interview. ''I don't think we've gotten as far as discussing the
specific terms of an alliance, but it is under active
consideration.'' DaimlerChrysler spokesman Eckhard Zanger said
DaimlerChrysler was not in talks with Hyundai on producing small
cars.
</P>
<P>
   German Industry Warned of Boycott
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- German companies risk product boycotts in the
United States if they fail to contribute to a compensation fund for
Nazi-era forced and slave laborers, a German official said today.
The warning from Otto Lambsdorff, Germany's chief negotiator in
talks on a settlement, was part of growing pressure on the
country's industry to quit stalling on the planned $4.6 billion
fund. German industry agreed last December to chip in half the
total, with the government to pay the other half. But companies
have contributed only $1.3 billion, just over half their share.
</P>
<P>
   European Stocks Close Lower
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed lower today on low volume
as fears over the telecommunications sector hit bourses while
losses on the Nasdaq Composite weighed on technology stocks.
Telecom names fell across Europe from the beginning of trade as the
breakdown of merger talks between KPN of the Netherlands and
Spain's Telefonica sapped investor confidence in a sector already
hurt by the high prices of mobile phone licenses. The Dow Jones
Euro Stoxx Index was down 4.2 points at 441.3. London's FTSE-100
Share Index fell 0.4 percent to 6,216.3; Frankfurt's Xetra DAX
Index fell 1.6 percent to 7,408.09; Paris' CAC-40 Index was down
0.5 percent to 6,514.42; Milan's MIBtel Index was down 0.6 percent;
Amsterdam's AEX Index was down 0.2 percent to 668.87.
</P>
