<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 127; Dow Down 21  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks sank in a quiet session today as
investors worried about interest rates and took profits from a
modest rally on Friday. Technology stocks led the decline.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow
Jones industrial average was down 21.45 at 10,556.41.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also fell. The Nasdaq composite index
was down 127.07 at 3,689.75 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
down 14.13 at 1,418.50.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said the most significant action in the market came from
investors selling stocks to capture short-term gains from a solid
rally on Friday, when the Dow rose 165 points and the Nasdaq rose
96.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks, which led Friday's gains, were mostly lower
today. Hewlett-Packard fell 3 to 133} and Intel fell 5 11/16 to 117
11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems fell 5 5/16 to 85 3/16 and PMC-Sierra fell 12
to 168.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco fell 5{ to 62\ after an article in Barron's said the
company's stunning growth rate could slow if Cisco stops acquiring
companies at a rapid rate.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the technology sector, investors stayed resolutely on the
sidelines, pondering the upcoming meeting of the Federal Reserve,
which is expected to raise interest rates for the sixth time since
last June.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists expect the Fed to raise rates by as much as a
half-percentage point at its next policymaking meeting on May 16.
The last five rate increases have come in a series of modest,
quarter-percentage point hikes.
</P>
<P>
   While some Wall Street analysts believe investors would welcome
a sharper increase as a sign that the Fed is finally nearing the
end of its cycle of rate increases, the uncertainty has contributed
to a sharp drop in trading activity in the past few sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Despite the entrenched optimism in the market, investors will
not be able to ignore a more aggressive Federal Reserve,'' said
Sung Won Sohn, chief economist at Wells Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   Rising interest rates are generally bad for stocks because they
cut into corporate profits by increasing the cost of borrowing
money. Last week, the rate-sensitive financial sector bore the
brunt of investors' worries and fell steeply.
</P>
<P>
   Today, financial stocks outperformed the broader market as
investors bought them at reduced prices. American Express was up 4
9/16 to 150 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 607.99 million
shares, behind Friday's quiet pace.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, decliners led by a 9-to-5 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 10.37 to
502.47.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
