<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boccardi, Gore Address AP Members  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Plans to enhance The Associated Press' state
news coverage and Internet presence were announced today by Louis
D. Boccardi, president and chief executive officer, at the news
cooperative's annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was attended by executives representing AP's 1,546
member newspapers on the first full day of the Newspaper
Association of America's convention. The meeting also featured a
panel on the 2000 election and talks by Vice President Al Gore and
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright.
</P>
<P>
   AP Chairman Donald E. Newhouse called the meeting to order, and
Boccardi reported on the state of AP.
</P>
<P>
   Boccardi assured the convention that the coming year would bring
''an ever-stronger world and national news report; further
exploration of the opportunities and challenges the Internet
presents, (and) sharper focus on better performance on all
levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Boccardi specifically mentioned the AP's state reports as a
target for enhancements. The company is adding two new
Chicago-based positions in that regard: a writing coach, the AP's
third, and a deputy director of state news.
</P>
<P>
   He also cited the introduction of a Web site called the AP
Election Center, ''for online readers who want as much detail as
they can get on the candidates, the issues and the campaigns, from
the White House to this interesting little thing we've got going on
in New York state this year.'' He was referring to the U.S. Senate
race between first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Several other initiatives related to the Internet were mentioned
by Boccardi, including forthcoming delivery of the state reports in
a format that enables editors of online editions to post them
easily to newspaper Web sites, and the addition of Web site
addresses at the bottom of many AP stories.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the likely Democratic presidential nominee, told the
executives that he would accept invitations from any newspaper to
debate likely GOP opponent George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president added that he would keep ''an open mind'' on
whether current FCC regulations banning dual ownership of a
newspaper and a television or radio station in a single market
should be changed.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore said he would consider revising estate tax laws that
make it difficult for families to maintain ownership of newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the news cooperative also heard from Alan Diaz,
the photographer who took the AP photographs inside the house where
6-year-old Elian Gonzalez was seized by federal agents late last
month.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of the raid, ''I had the instinct, the hunch,
that something was going to go down,'' Diaz said. When the raid
began, he immediately sprinted into the house and set up in the
room where the boy was being hidden in a closet.
</P>
<P>
   His overriding memory of the raid? ''All I could hear, and all I
could remember, was Elian crying,'' Diaz said.
</P>
<P>
   Boccardi also moderated a discussion of political campaigns with
three AP correspondents. The panel, titled ''A Conversation:
Campaign 2000,'' includes Walter Mears, AP vice president and
Washington columnist; Ron Fournier, chief political writer in
Washington; and Marc A. Humbert, New York State political editor
based in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Humbert, talking about the New York senate race between Giuliani
and Clinton, said the battle between the two was already
''intense'' -- and it promised not to let up.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're going to be so sick of seeing Rudy Giuliani and Hillary
Clinton ads on television that come November, you probably won't
want to vote for either of them,'' Humbert said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, the featured speaker at the luncheon following the
meeting, spoke about some of the most controversial areas of
foreign policy in the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   She said the upcoming vote in Congress on whether to create
normal trade relations with China ''may well be the most
significant economic and national security decision Congress faces
this year.'' On the conflict in the Balkans, she said she was
certain U.S. involvement had been ''the right thing,'' but added:
''We admit we made a mistake when we said our forces would be out
of there in a year. It was an artificial deadline.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about recent scandals at the State Department over
security lapses, she said: ''I was both angered and embarrassed ...
On behalf of all employees of the state Department, I'm
humiliated.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the meeting began with the announcement of election
results for the board of directors, held by all-mail balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Four incumbents and three new members were elected to the board.
</P>
<P>
   Elected to new terms were John J. Curley, chairman and CEO,
Gannett Co. Inc., Wilmington (Del.) News-Journal; Newhouse,
president, Advance Publications Inc., Newark (N.J.) Star-Ledger;
John W. Madigan, chairman, president and CEO, Tribune Co., Chicago
Tribune and Orage Quarles III, publisher, Raleigh (N.C.) News &AMP;
Observer.
</P>
<P>
   New members are Walter E. Hussman Jr., president and CEO, WEHCO
Media Inc., Arkansas Democrat-Gazette; Julie Inskeep Walda,
publisher, Fort Wayne (Ind.) Journal Gazette; and Sue Mayborn,
president and publisher, Temple (Texas) Daily Telegram. Walda was
selected to fill one year left in the term of Richard J.
Harrington, who is stepping down. Mayborn was selected to represent
a city of less than 50,000 population.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.ap.org
</P>
