<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nebraska, W.Va. Primaries Are Tues.  </HEADLINE>
By KEVIN O'HANLON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- Two top Republican state officials are
battling it out in Tuesday's primary for a chance to fill the seat
being vacated by the only Democrat in Nebraska's congressional
delegation -- Sen. Bob Kerrey.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Don Stenberg and Secretary of State Scott Moore
are expected to lead the GOP primary race, which is now down to
four candidates after two deep-pocketed contenders stopped
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   The winner is likely to take on former Gov. Ben Nelson, who left
office in 1999 with an 80 percent approval rating after two terms.
He faced token opposition in the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   In other races Tuesday, former University of Nebraska football
coach Tom Osborne, the most popular person in this football-crazy
state, has two opponents in a GOP congressional primary.
</P>
<P>
   In West Virginia, Republican Gov. Cecil Underwood faces a
painting contractor, a housewife and an unemployed construction
worker in the GOP primary. Underwood, 77, was so confident that he
did not campaign and planned to spend election night watching a
minor league baseball game.
</P>
<P>
   The more dramatic West Virginia race was for the House seat
being left by Rep. Bob Wise, who is running in the Democratic
primary to challenge Underwood.
</P>
<P>
   Four Democrats are vying for the seat Wise has held since 1982 --
including Secretary of State Ken Hechler, an 85-year-old former
congressman whose political career dates back to the New Deal. He
faces popular state Sen. Martha Walker, Harrison County
Commissioner Beth Taylor and lawyer Jim Humphreys, who spent $3
million of his own money and leads in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will take on Republican Shelley Moore Capito, a
member of the state House of Delegates and the daughter of former
Gov. Arch A. Moore Jr., the state's only three-term governor.
</P>
<P>
   There are also presidential primaries Tuesday in Nebraska and
West Virginia, but both are essentially meaningless since Al Gore
and George W. Bush have sealed their parties' nominations.
</P>
<P>
   In Nebraska, Republicans were giddy when Kerrey, a rare Democrat
in the conservative state, declined to run for a third term. Kerrey
instead will become president of New School University in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Stenberg, who recently defended Nebraska's ban against so-called
partial birth abortions before the Supreme Court, had been running
for the Senate for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   But Kerrey's decision also prompted Moore, one of Stenberg's
most prominent backers, to enter the race. Moore has raised
$224,000 this year, compared with $144,000 for Stenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Agribusinessman David Hergert and former state Sen. John DeCamp
are also on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Nelson's popularity, the Republicans -- who tried to woo
him to switch parties in 1998 -- know he can be beat. Nelson lost a
Senate race in 1996 to Chuck Hagel.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne considered running for the GOP Senate nomination but
instead decided to seek the House seat held by Republican Bill
Barrett, who is retiring after five terms.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne's opponents, longtime state GOP leader John Gale and
state Board of Education member Kathy Wilmot, have tried not to let
the former coach's celebrity hinder their campaigns. And the race
has mainly focused on the issues -- namely the struggling farm
economy.
</P>
<P>
   But the voters clearly are fascinated with Osborne, who coached
Nebraska for a quarter-century and led the Cornhuskers to three
national championships in the 1990s. He would face Democrat Rollie
Reynolds in November.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think people in the state of Nebraska have had a chance to
see me operate up close and personal for 25 years,'' Osborne said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 1601 </TRAILER>
