<DOCNO> APW20000508.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> With AP Photos  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Hailed by friends and followers at a touching
funeral Mass, Cardinal John O'Connor arrived Monday at his final
resting place beneath St. Patrick's Cathedral -- completing his
journey from local priest to the nation's most prominent Roman
Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton headed a long list of dignitaries attending
the funeral Mass for O'Connor, who came to New York in 1984 from
Scranton, Pa. O'Connor proved a perfect fit in the media capital of
the nation, serving as Pope John Paul II's American point man.
</P>
<P>
   ''He made this pulpit unique in the history of the Catholic
Church in the United States,'' said Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston,
a close friend and confidante of O'Connor for the last 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''God gifted him with a keen and subtle intellect, an uncommon
rhetorical skill, a knack for the dramatic gesture, a sharp wit and
an outrageous sense of humor -- all of which he used in the service
of preaching,'' Law said in a heartfelt homily.
</P>
<P>
   The pope, though Vatican secretary of state Cardinal Angelo
Sodano, sent his condolences to O'Connor's family. Speaking at the
start of the service, Sodano -- who carried the late cardinal's
staff into the church -- sounded a theme of celebration rather than
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lord, we don't complain because you have taken him from us,''
Sodano told a hushed crowd of 3,500 inside the great Manhattan
cathedral. ''But rather we will thank you for giving him to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mass combined pageantry and prayer, opening with a 45-minute
procession of O'Connor's fellow clergy. Each passing priest gently
touched the cardinal's coffin, which was draped with a white linen
cloth.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the priests wore special vestments designed for the
pope's 1995 visit to New York. Among those in attendance was Bishop
Edward Egan of Bridgeport, Conn., the perceived front-runner to
replace O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the service, O'Connor's dark wood casket was
splashed with holy water, symbolic of the sacrament of baptism. It
was then carried by pallbearers to a crypt beneath the altar where
O'Connor had preached most Sundays for the last 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   The church erupted in spontaneous applause for the cardinal just
before the casket disappeared from the church. A one-legged boy,
propping himself up on small crutches, stood clapping in the aisle
as the casket went past.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor was involved in planning the funeral, handpicking many
of the songs and prayers. The recessional hymn, ''Lift High the
Cross,'' was performed when O'Connor was installed as head of the
archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor was often most at ease among the sick and poor of his
2.4 million member flock, but his funeral prompted an outpouring of
high-profile mourners at the invitation-only Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Attending were Clinton and his wife, Hillary; former President
George Bush; presidential candidates Al Gore and George W. Bush;
United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan; U.S. Senators Daniel
Patrick Moynihan and Charles Schumer; Gov. George Pataki; Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani; and 15 cardinals from the Vatican, the United
States and four other countries.
</P>
<P>
   There were also those whose lives the cardinal had touched. U.S.
Rep. Carolyn McCarthy was a Long Island housewife in 1993 when her
husband was killed and her son critically wounded by a gunman on
the Long Island Rail Road.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal sent her a letter offering his sympathy but
promising the shootings would change the path of her life. McCarthy
was subsequently elected to Congress as an antigun candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what made him a great man,'' she said. ''He always
reached out to ordinary people. It didn't matter what religion you
were. He was truly a shepherd to all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the church, on a sweltering 91-degree day, hundreds of
people stood 8-to-10 deep behind police barricades as the funeral
Mass was broadcast over loudspeakers. Over the previous four days,
tens of thousands of New Yorkers visited O'Connor's open casket to
pay their final respects.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, 80, died last Wednesday after a lengthy battle with
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   After the Mass, an honor guard carried O'Connor's casket down a
narrow staircase to a crypt beneath St. Patrick's altar, where all
previous archbishops of New York are buried.
</P>
<P>
   His coffin was placed near that of Pierre Toussaint, a
19th-century Haitian whose cause for sainthood was supported by
O'Connor. That portion of the ceremony was private, with only
O'Connor's relatives and a small group of church officials present.
</P>
<P>
   lm -- h/outs, television
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
