<DOCNO> APW20000508.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dog days of spring for zoo animals as heat wave continues  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE MAY COURT HOUSE, N.J. (AP) -- The goats hid under a wooden
walkway, cowering from the midday sun. Tosh, a 350-pound Bengal
tiger, lolled around in the shade, pausing only for an occasional
dip in his pool.
</P>
<P>
   In another corral, the emus waited for zookeeper Sheri Hickok to
spray them down. Then the big flightless birds stepped into the
puddles that the water had made to cool off.
</P>
<P>
   So it went Monday at the Cape May County Park &AMP; Zoo, where
animals shifted into slow motion and zoo visitors doused themselves
with bottled water to keep cool. As a spring heat wave beat on for
a third day, living things big and small did their best to cope
with 90-degree temperatures and high humidity.
</P>
<P>
   ''They definitely don't like the heat, especially happening this
early in the season,'' said Hickok. ''Most of these animals, you've
got to give them a little help. We hose down the birds of prey, and
we make little mud puddles for the pigs, because they don't sweat
and they need help.
</P>
<P>
   ''The panda bears hate the heat. They don't like being hosed or
misted, either, so we put ice blocks in their cages so they can rub
up against them.''
</P>
<P>
   Zoo enthusiasts, who paid $1 for bottled water, used much of it
on their own heads.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to stay in the shade and drink plenty of water,''
said Jedon Lilliston of Oceanview, who was with her 4-year-old son,
Johnny. ''We've already been in the sprinkler at home, so we
decided to come here.''
</P>
<P>
   The animals, meanwhile, took a smarter approach.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is that saying? 'Only mad dogs and Englishmen go out in
the noonday sun?' Animals are smarter than people. When it gets
hot, they get in the shade,'' said Bill Sturm, director of the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   In Bridgeton, workers at the Cohanzick Zoo were fighting a
similar battle.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bears and tigers have air conditioning in their buildings,
so they're OK,'' said zoo curator John Swank. ''For the reindeer,
we provide misters, which spray water. For the chinchillas, we
freeze two-liter bottles of water and put them in their cages. They
can rub against them if they want. But generally, all the animals
are much less active in the heat.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Atlantic City International Airport, a 90-degree high
tied a 36-year-old record for May 8, according to the National
Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   ''This heat is above normal, but not unusual,'' said
meteorologist Bill Christ. ''Normally, we should be in the high 70s
at this time of year.''
</P>
<P>
   No relief is in sight until Wednesday or Thursday, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
