<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wet Outlook Dampens Grain, Soybeans  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean prices tumbled Monday on the
Chicago Board of Trade after forecasts called for significant rain
in the central United States this week.
</P>
<P>
   Weekend rains set previously bullish investors back on their
heels to start the week, and a selloff ensued when midday forecasts
said as much as two inches of rain might fall on the Midwest this
week. The soggy weather would wash away some of the concerns about
a severe drought impact this year.
</P>
<P>
   Corn took the biggest fall, with America's top crop already
largely planted and particularly vulnerable to dry soil conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans also plunged, but less steeply.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat was pressured by the declines in corn and soybeans as well
as the wet forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery fell 4 cents to $2.68} a bushel; July
corn fell 7\ cents to $2.41 a bushel; July oats fell 1} cent to
$1.23\ a bushel; July soybeans fell 7 cents to $5.59 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef futures finished mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
while pork futures retreated.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle fell .05 cent to 68.57 cents a pound; August
feeder cattle rose .40 cent to 85.17 cents a pound; June lean hogs
fell .48 cent to 74.17 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell .68
cent to 93.57 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
