<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congressional Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a year of inflation of political claims by
both parties, Republicans had an unusual reaction to a recent
primary election in Indiana. They basically surrendered in their
effort to knock out first term Democratic Rep. Baron Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a not a targeted race we're now looking at for the
fall,'' said Jim Wilkinson, a spokesman for the GOP campaign
committee. As if to underscore the point, the GOP issued a written
statement that spoke enthusiastically of its chances for victory in
other Indiana contests. It omitted mention of Hill's seat.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP had long touted Hill as a potential victim, but
congressional party leaders' hopes soured when Kevin Kellems, a
former aide to Sen. Richard Lugar, lost the nomination. Some GOP
strategists view the winner in the primary, Michael Bailey, as too
much a one-note candidate to defeat Hill. Bailey is a longtime
anti-abortion crusader.
</P>
<P>
   ''I encourage Christians to invade politics,'' Bailey said
recently. ''Every time we run, we force the party a little bit to
the right.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey has become known for graphic anti-abortion commercials
depicting images of dead fetuses. In victory, he pledged to broaden
his campaign platform, and said he will advocate gun rights and
oppose free trade and legal recognition of homosexual unions.
</P>
<P>
   A gain of six seats would give Democrats control of the Senate.
Like several other states, Indiana has enough competitive races to
assure plenty of attention from the two parties.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats insist they have a chance to defeat three-term
incumbent John Hostettler. Hostettler will face Paul Perry, a
surgeon who largely financed his own campaign, in November. Perry
defeated John Hamilton, a nephew of ex-Rep. Lee Hamilton, to win
the Democrats' nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ''His profile on the issues fits the distict,'' Erik Smith,
spokesman for the Democratic Campaign Committee, said about Perry,
who opposes both abortions and gun control. ''Hostettler has not
had to run against a candidate who is this conservative before.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans issued a statement saying Perry's views on health
care and other issues ''are extreme and out of touch.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Another oddity in a fiercely contrested election is the growing
number of lawmakers running without major party opposition. The
list now totals 36, divided equally between Republicans and
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The latest to escape major party opposition include Republicans
John Linder of Georgia and three GOP members from Alabama: Sonny
Callahan, Bob Riley and Spencer Bachus.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Rep. Bud Cramer of Alabama is without a GOP opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of legislation to grant permanent normal trade
relations to China are counting on last week's vote on a different
subject to boost their cause. Democratic strategists say they
expect that the vote to establish trade rules with Africa will ease
the way for senior Democratic on the House Ways and Means
Committee, Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, to join supporters of
the China bill.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel is officially uncommitted, but a spokesman, Dan Maffei,
said ''getting Africa helps, insofar as it frees (him) up to focus
on the pros and cons of granting PNTR to China.'' Maffei said the
New Yorker also is closely following an effort by Rep. Sander
Levin, D-Mich., to include in the legislation a commission to
monitor China's record on human rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Africa trade bill, expected to clear the Senate this week
and be signed by President Clinton, would to give economically
struggling sub-Saharan nations better access to American markets
and open up trade with Caribbean states as well.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel is in line to become chairman of the Ways and Means
Committee, with access over taxes, trade and welfare issues, should
Democrats win the House in November's elections. The party's two
top leaders in the House oppose the China trade measure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 1616 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000508.0090 </DOCNO>
