<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pair swap driving duties during 20-mile chase  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ELIZABETH, N.J. (AP) -- A man and a woman heading to court on
Monday stole a truck and led officers on a 20-mile chase that
reached speeds of about 100 mph before crashing, the Middlesex
County sheriff said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The pair, who switched driving duties during the chase,
sideswiped several vehicles while speeding up the New Jersey
Turnpike, before the truck flipped at exit 13, Sheriff Joseph C.
Spicuzzo said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Orlando Santiago and Stacey A. Berman had suspended
driver's licenses, and Santiago had a prior conviction for eluding
police, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago attempted to run and was caught; Berman was injured, he
said. Both were taken to University Hospital in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, a 20-year-old from Rahway, suffered a severe cut on
her right arm was admitted, hospital spokesman Rogers Ramsey said.
</P>
<P>
   The man, a 27-year-old, from Union, had a cut left wrist and was
released into the custody of sheriff's officers and taken to the
Middlesex County Jail, Spicuzzo said. Numerous charges are being
considered against both, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two were to appear in East Brunswick Municipal Court on drug
charges when ''they apparently changed their mind'' and stole a
pickup truck loaded with grass clippings that was parked at an
apartment building by the township complex, Spicuzzo said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, two of his investigators driving nearby on Route 18
northbound heard about the theft on their police radio, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''When the hot line message came on the air, they found
themselves right behind the truck,'' Spicuzzo said.
</P>
<P>
   Berman was driving at the time, and she refused to pull over for
the investigators, who pulled alongside, yelled and showed their
badges because they were in an unmarked station wagon, he said.
</P>
<P>
   They followed the truck onto the turnpike at exit 9, notified
state police and saw Santiago take over the driving, Spicuzzo said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They started to reach some high speeds, and over the radio I
ordered them to back off,'' the sheriff said. ''I just wanted them
to keep them in sight.''
</P>
<P>
   After sideswiping three or four cars, the blue 1994 Ford F250
pickup flipped by exit 13, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-08-00 1624 </TRAILER>
