<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Ex-Presidents Back China Bill  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton turned up the pressure on
Congress to grant permanent trade status to China, recruiting three
former presidents and a highly respected Republican central banker
to stand with him in staunch support of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents Ford, Carter and Bush on Monday wrote an open letter
backing legislation to grant permanent normal trade relations to
China. Shoring up support on the right, Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan said he too is behind the measure, which would ease
the communist nation's long-desired entry into the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ''In economic terms, the case is clear,'' the former presidents
wrote in their two-page letter released by the White House. ''The
agreement to bring China into the WTO is the product of more than
13 years of tough negotiations conducted by four administrations,
Democratic and Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Ford and Carter will join President Clinton, Vice
President Al Gore, former secretaries of state, including Henry
Kissinger, and former national security advisers at the White House
to rally support for the legislation. And the Democratic Leadership
Council is to deliver to Clinton a national petition in support of
PNTR signed by more than 140 state and local elected leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions and the two top House Democratic leaders are
fighting the legislation, suggesting it will hurt U.S. jobs. The
Clinton administration, Republican leaders and U.S. business groups
have been lobbying lawmakers for weeks to get the legislation
passed.
</P>
<P>
   If the House approves the measure in a vote expected later this
month, Senate passage is likely.
</P>
<P>
   The former presidents said granting China permanent trade
benefits would build upon market-opening initiatives pursued by
every American president since World War II. ''It will open China's
markets to us without increasing China's access to our market,''
the presidents said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, who soon begins his fourth term as Fed chairman, said
China's membership in the WTO would promote economic development in
China and help lift the country's poor out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   In a May 5 letter to House Banking Committee Chairman Rep. James
Leach, R-Iowa, Greenspan also said permanent trade relations would
ease political liberties inside the nation of 1 billion people.
</P>
<P>
   ''History has demonstrated that implicit in any removal of power
from central planners and broadening of market mechanisms as would
occur under WTO is a more general spread of rights to
individuals,'' Greenspan wrote. ''Such a development will be a far
stronger vehicle to foster other individual rights than any other
alternative of which I am aware.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for House Democratic Whip Daniel Bonoir of Michigan,
a leading opponent of extending permanent most favored nation
status to China, said opinion polls show three-quarters of
Americans oppose the deal.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bonoir and about a dozen members of his working
group against the legislation, will hear from actress Goldie Hawn,
who will express her concerns about China's human rights offenses
in the ongoing debate over trade, Bonoir's spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The former presidents disagree, saying a vote for PNTR will
soften U.S.-China relations and make positive change within China
more likely by opening doors to the information revolution and
speeding up reforms that are dismantling many state controls over
the economy and society.
</P>
<P>
   ''A vote against PNTR will make it far more difficult to attain
these critical goals,'' the presidents wrote in their open letter.
''It would be read in China as a vote for confrontation and as an
argument for hunkering down, instead of continuing to reach out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
