<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Despite astronomical odds, lottery frenzy continues  </HEADLINE>
By ERIN McCLAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- How big is the Big Game jackpot?
</P>
<P>
   Bigger than the total prize money given away on ''Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire'' -- 19 times over. Enough cash to pay the entire
Minnesota Twins baseball team until 2020.
</P>
<P>
   The jackpot ballooned Monday to $325 million -- an astronomical
level almost inconceivable to anyone but superstar athletes and
dot-com tycoons. If it goes to just one person after Tuesday's
drawing, the prize will be the richest in world history.
</P>
<P>
   In seven states, gas stations and grocery stores were swamped
Monday with long lines of people hoping their numbers -- some
carefully chosen, others computer-picked -- would change their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're dreaming of what they'll do with it for that minute
they're buying it,'' said Kevin Finneran, owner of a Li'l Peach
convenience store in South Boston. ''People love talking about it
for that minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Game officials said they expect to sell more than 140
million tickets before the winning numbers are picked Tuesday at 11
p.m. EDT -- including a crush of sales near state lines, where
people drive hours to get in on the game.
</P>
<P>
   ''If sales are going strong or are higher than anticipated, or
if the bond interest rates go higher -- that also helps us increase
the jackpot,'' said Virginia Haines, New Jersey Lottery executive
director.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's previous record lottery jackpot was $295.7 million,
set in the multistate Powerball game in 1998. That prize was shared
by 13 machinists from Westerville, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The frantic pace of ticket sales leading up to Friday's drawing
had increased the jackpot from $230 million to $250 million just in
the hours before that night's numbers were picked.
</P>
<P>
   Total sales from last Tuesday's drawing to Friday night exceeded
$122 million. New Jersey led with sales of nearly $34 million. The
game also is played in Georgia, Illinois, Maryland, Massachusetts,
Michigan and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Haines attributed record New Jersey sales to large volumes of
ticket buyers from New York and Pennsylvania, states that do not
participate in multistate games.
</P>
<P>
   At Circle Liquor Store in Somers Point, N.J., Big Game tickets
were selling faster than beer -- quite an accomplishment given the
90-degree heat and the store's location next to booze-free Ocean
City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ''On Friday, we sold about 6,000 tickets,'' said Joseph Cox, who
was working the lottery machine. ''Normally, we sell about $500 on
the day of a drawing.''
</P>
<P>
   By 2 p.m. Monday, 1,400 tickets had been sold for Tuesday
night's drawing.
</P>
<P>
   Players were in good spirits, Cox said. Most weren't regular
players but couldn't resist the lure of the record jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   ''Usually, I don't like working the lottery. But it's been fun
this time. Half these people don't know what they're doing, but
they're having fun doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lena McKelvey, 21, of Doylestown, Pa., was one of them. She
bought two tickets Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I won, I'd go traveling, probably take a one-month cruise
to the Caribbean. And I'd buy my mother a nice BMW. And I'd take a
million and set up a shelter for the homeless,'' McKelvey said.
</P>
<P>
   At the 7-Eleven store in Northfield, N.J., co-owner Liz
Krakowski took up permanent residence on a stool next to the
store's lottery machine, punching numbers and listening to players
dreaming aloud.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody's so excited about it. And the groups are incredible
with their pools. They're buying 300 tickets at a time. Everyone's
saying how it's too much money, they don't know what they'd do if
they won. But no one's planning on going back to work,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Cana, Va., just across the North Carolina state line, 200
lottery players queued up at an Exxon station before sunrise. One
man bought $3,050 in tickets, and gasoline sales suffered all day
because the parking lot was full.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the sixth day in a row it's been that way,'' manager
Leo Bobbitt said.
</P>
<P>
   After taxes, one person who wins the jackpot would get either
$8.5 million a year for 26 years or a one-time payment of $110
million.
</P>
<P>
   The $325 million jackpot could grow Tuesday, when lottery
officials confer by telephone. It already tops the previous
American record, a $295.7 million Powerball payout split by 13
machinists in Westerville, Ohio, two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The world's lottery record is $1.2 billion, set in December by
Spain's El Gordo, or the Fat One. But that game spreads itself thin
-- thousands of prizes are awarded in a four-hour ceremony that
brings the country to a standstill as orphaned children sing out
the winning numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The odds in Tuesday's Big Game are exponentially stacked against
players. The chance that a $1 ticket will match all six numbers is
one in more than 76 million.
</P>
<P>
   Those are roughly the same odds as putting a finger down
randomly on a list of everyone in America and landing on an
ex-president. Or of flipping a coin and seeing heads 26 consecutive
times.
</P>
<P>
   W. Scott Wood, who teaches a class on psychology and gambling at
Drake University in Iowa, explains the long odds to his students
this way: ''Try to imagine the equivalent of sticking a pin in the
Los Angeles white pages and hitting your cousin's name. Or throwing
a rock off the Empire State and hitting someone you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Temple University math professor John Allen Paulos said the game
amounts to a cheap dream.
</P>
<P>
   ''A man is hundreds of times more likely to suffer a heart
attack between the time he buys the ticket and the drawing than he
is to win the jackpot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the fever created by the record jackpot only increases the
chances that more than one person will pick correctly.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't stop the frenzy Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, so many people tried to access the lottery's Web
site that the server crashed.
</P>
<P>
   And in western Maryland, the line outside Grantsville Liquors
was half a city block long. Inside, Bernadette Fedornak waited in
line for an hour and a half after driving from Pittsburgh to buy
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   She said most of her numbers would be computer-chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll play a couple of numbers when I get up there,'' Fedornak
said. ''But I'm not going to tell you what they are.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The Big Game: http://www.theofficialbiggame.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-08-00 1652 </TRAILER>
