<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Seeks US Immigration Rule End  </HEADLINE>
By ANITA SNOW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Cuba announced a campaign Monday to end U.S.
immigration policies it says encourage citizens to undertake the
same type of dangerous sea journeys that killed the mother of Elian
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every grave incident of a boatwreck, kidnapping or death will
be known by our people and by world public opinion as irrefutable
proof of the cynicism of the policies of the United States against
Cuba,'' the Communist Party daily Granma said in a front page
story.
</P>
<P>
   During the 5{-month battle to repatriate the 6-year-old Cuban
child to his homeland, Fidel Castro has repeatedly lashed out at a
1966 U.S. law that allows Cubans who reach American soil to avoid
deportation, characterizing it as a ''killing machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it appears that Castro's long-standing fight against the
Cuban Adjustment Act will not only be expanded, but is likely to
continue long after the Elian custody case is resolved. The
newspaper promised an ''energetic fight against the violations of
the sacred right to life of our citizens,'' using state television,
radio and youths to get out the message.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes three days after 14 severely dehydrated
and sunburned Cubans were found floating off Miami's coast in an
aluminum boat. They had been at sea for 10 days and had to share a
small bag of crackers and drink salt water and their own urine to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Cuban officials published a small note in the
Juventud Rebelde daily referring to the trip as ''another crime of
the murderous law.''
</P>
<P>
   Passed at the height of the Cold War, the U.S. law allows any
Cuban who reaches American soil to apply for permanent residency
after being in the United States for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Elian fell under this law because after he was rescued at sea in
late November, he was brought to a hospital in the United States.
If he had come from almost any other country, Elian would have been
deported right away. Instead he was released into temporary custody
of relatives living in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 Cubans rescued at sea Friday also were covered by the law
because they, too, were admitted into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Castro and other senior officials complain that the U.S. law
violates 1994 and 1995 migration accords between the two countries,
designed to prevent a repeat of the so-called ''rafters crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Cuban government said it would no longer stop people
from leaving the island, more than 30,000 rafters set out across
the straits, with hundreds of people leaving daily in the summer of
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Under the migration agreements, the U.S. Coast Guard is charged
with repatriating the majority of would-be Cuban immigrants
intercepted at sea -- even a short distance from land.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government is also obliged to help encourage legal
migration to the United States by providing a minimum of 20,000
visas to Cubans every year.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban officials, meanwhile, are charged with trying to prevent
the illegal departure of Cubans for the United States. They
vigorously deny sporadic rumors that pop up in Miami's Cuban exile
community that Castro is planning another mass exodus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 1700 </TRAILER>
