<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Pockets of scattered showers and a few thunderstorms
were
scattered across the nation from the Northwest through the northerain
Plains into New England on Monday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   High temperatures continued across parts of the easterain half of
the nation, but with fewer record high temperatures than during the
weekend, By mid-afterainoon, Bridgeport, Conn., had a record of 86;
Newark, N.J., tied its record of 92; New York City tied its record
of 91, and South Bend, Ind., tied its record of 87.
</P>
<P>
   An area of low pressure over the Northwest spread areas of light
rain across Washington, Oregon, Idaho, northerain sections of Nevada
and Utah, and westerain areas of Montana and Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front produced a ribbon of showers from easterain Utah
through Colorado into Nebraska, Iowa and southerain Minnesota. Radar
showed areas of thunderstorms in easterain Colorado and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   As the cold front drifted toward the east, thunderstorms also
were possible during the night in parts of Kansas, Missouri and
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service issued a torainado watch for parts of
southeasterain Iowa, northerain Missouri and west-central and northerain
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   At the northeasterain end of the cold front, low pressure moving
across the northerain Mississippi Valley produced showers and
thunderstorms in parts of Minnesota, Wisconsin and Michigan's Upper
Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Wind gusted as high as 50 mph in parts of Wisconsin, knocking
down power lines, and about 2,600 Wisconsin Electric customers lost
power briefly in the moraining in the Milwaukee suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   In the Northeast, warm, muggy air kicked off scattered showers
and thunderstorms that spread from easterain New York through parts
of Vermont, Connecticut, Massachusetts, New Hampshire and Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a
moraining low of 21 at Cut Bank, Mont., to a midday reading of 93 at
Fort Belvoir, Va. The highest midday heat index was 96 at
Baltimore, and the lowest wind chill was 11 at Cut Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
