<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lott Biggest Corporate Flight User  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott flies
frequently on aircraft belonging to various private companies with
issues before Congress, writing checks totaling $101,029 for
corporate flights since Jan. 1, 1995, more than any other senator
up for re-election this fall, a new study shows.
</P>
<P>
   In second place was Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., whose campaign
spent $18,730 on corporate flights, according to the Campaign Study
Group, a non-partisan consulting firm that analyzes campaign
spending. Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., was third with $17,757.
</P>
<P>
   Many senators take advantage of a practice in which they use
corporate jets and then reimburse the companies for the price of a
first-class flight, far below the going rate for chartering a
private jet. The money comes from the senators' campaign accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The practice has advantages for both: Lawmakers do not have to
worry about airline schedules or making connections; companies
providing the planes often have a lobbyist aboard to schmooze a
virtually captive one-person audience.
</P>
<P>
   ''Private corporate jet travel is still one of the biggest scams
in Washington,'' Charles Lewis, director of the watchdog Center for
Public Integrity, said Monday. ''The average American cannot afford
to travel on a private jet and the face time it affords lobbyists
with lawmakers is absolutely invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are being subsidized by the interests who have business
before them. It's no more complicated than that,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's campaign committee reimbursed U.S. Tobacco Co. $18,196
for flights, R.J. Reynolds $2,876 and Philip Morris $2,107. Lott
has opposed Clinton administration efforts to regulate tobacco as a
drug and raise federal cigarette taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The senator also paid Schering-Plough $1,924 for the use of its
corporate jet. The company is pushing legislation that would allow
a two-year extension of its patent for the anti-allergy drug
Claritin.
</P>
<P>
   Lott also flew aboard planes owned by telecommunications
companies BellSouth and MCI Worldcom. The companies are on opposite
sides of legislation to allow local Bell operating companies to
send data over long-distance phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is fully disclosed, privately funded and totally legal
travel for a leader whose job demands he be on the road quite a
bit,'' Lott spokesman John Czwartacki said. ''We are complying with
the law and sparing the taxpayers the cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy reimbursed the law firm of Ness Motley Loadholt
Richardson &AMP; Poole $4,856 for flights. The firm opposes efforts in
Congress to impose restrictions on liability lawsuits. Kennedy also
paid $3,311 to Raytheon, a defense contractor, and $2,149 to the
American Family Life Assurance Company, which has lobbied hard
against restrictions on selling cancer insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Challengers as well as incumbents flew the corporate skies.
</P>
<P>
   First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, seeking a Senate seat from
New York, reimbursed FHC Health Systems $9,175 for flights. FHC,
based in Norfolk, Va., is the nation's second-largest mental health
managed care firm. Her expected Republican opponent, New York City
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, flew on a plane owned by Canandaigua
Brands, an upstate New York winery. He paid $486.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Tobacco was reimbursed the most over the five-year period,
$31,293. Besides Lott, other senators who flew in the company's
planes included Conrad Burns, R-Mont.; John Ashcroft, R-Mo.; Jon
Kyl, R-Ariz.; and Spence Abraham, R-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   In second place was Federal Express, which supplied planes to
Lott, Kennedy and Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn. The company was
reimbursed $15,253.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do it when senators or congressmen request a plane,''
company spokesman Jess Bunn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 1716 </TRAILER>
