<HEADLINE> Weather, maintenance prompt call to conserve power  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Utility officials on Monday declared a
power watch as an early bout of summer-like weather drove up demand
for air conditioners and fans throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures topped 80 in most of Connecticut for the third
straight day. In Hartford, the mercury soared to 91, breaking the
date's previous high of 90 set in 1936, the National Weather
Service in Taunton, Mass., reported.
</P>
<P>
   Danbury reached 86 Monday and Bridgeport hit 85.
</P>
<P>
   The heat is coupled with humidity being pulled out of the Gulf
of Mexico and over the Midwest, NWS meteorologist Mike Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Around here, if the wind is coming out of the west, it's
coming off land and that produces a considerable amount of heat,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the warm weather, several power plants were out of
service Monday for annual maintenance, according to ISO New
England, the operator of the region's electricity generating
stations. The loss of those plants strained resources when demand
unexpectedly increased so early in the year, spokeswoman Ellen
Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The generation that's out of service right now will be going
full-tilt this summer, when we usually have this kind of weather,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The power watch, the first of the year, was lifted at 4:30 p.m.
after about four hours. The advisory is the least serious issued by
ISO.
</P>
<P>
   Customers on Monday were being asked to consider shutting off
lights and electrical appliances. Business were requested to help
by unplugging office equipment such as computers.
</P>
<P>
   ISO New England has said they will be ready to handle the
summer's peak demand, expected to top last year's record usage of
22,544 watts on July 6. Officials said several new power plants
would be operational and the region's nuclear plants looked ready
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut will be in better shape because Millstone 2 and 3 --
down all last summer -- are expected to be online this year.
</P>
<P>
   The region's power supply was repeatedly strained during last
summer's a record-breaking heat wave and drought.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said the heat is not expected to break until at least
Wednesday night, when a cold front over the Midwest carries in
cooler air.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-08-00 1726 </TRAILER>
