<HEADLINE> Glaxo-SmithKline Merger Gets OK  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Commission Monday approved
the merger between British pharmaceutical companies Glaxo Wellcome
PLC and SmithKline Beecham PLC, which will make it the world's
largest pharmaceuticals firm.
</P>
<P>
   The EU made the merger conditional upon the merged company
selling certain drugs. They are: SmithKline's Kytril, for the
treatment of nausea associated with chemotherapy, SmithKline's
Famvir, a herpes drug, and either SmithKline's Vectavir cream or
Glaxo's Zovirax, both of which treat cold sores.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the merged company could be required to sell its asthma
drug Ariflo if its European rivals don't get approval to market a
new asthma drug.
</P>
<P>
   The deal still faces approval by U.S. regulators, though the
companies said they expect it by the end of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo agreed to buy SmithKline last January in a deal now valued
at $76.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, to be called Glaxo SmithKline, will have 7.3
percent of global sales in its sector, the commission said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 1729 </TRAILER>
