<DOCNO> APW20000508.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> May Department Stores Earnings Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- May Department Stores Co.'s first-quarter
earnings dropped 1.7 percent from a year ago, as cooler-than-normal
weather in April depressed sales of spring clothing.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis-based company said Monday that it earned $120
million, or 35 cents a share, for the quarter ended April 29,
compared with earnings of $122 million, or 34 cents per share, in
the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   A share buyback helped boost the company's earnings per share,
but not enough to top Wall Street analysts' expectations of 36
cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   May's stock still rose on Monday, climbing 37{ cents to $28.75
on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Sales were $3.04 billion, up 3.5 percent from $2.94 billion a
year earlier. Sales at stores open at least a year, an industry
gauge of success, were flat with the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Like many retailers -- especially those with a big focus on
clothes, May's business was hurt by dreary, wet weather through
most of April. That dampened demand for everything from shorts to
sandals.
</P>
<P>
   May also announced three executive promotions on Monday: Thomas
D. Fingleton to executive vice president for finance and
operations; Kenneth L. Wilkerson to chairman of Hecht's; and Mark
J. Weikel to chairman of Foley's.
</P>
<P>
   May operates 422 stores in 36 states and the District of
Columbia. Year-to-date, the retailer has opened 14 new stores and
plans to open nine additional new stores in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Its stores include Lord &AMP; Taylor, Hecht's, Strawbridge's,
Foley's, Robinson-May, Filene's, Kaufmann's, Famous-Barr, L.S.
Ayres, The Jones Store, Meier &AMP; Frank and ZCMI.
</P>
</TEXT>
