<HEADLINE> Euro Down Against Dollar  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The euro slid against the dollar once again
Monday as traders expected little action from European financial
officials to support the currency.
</P>
<P>
   In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at 89.70 cents,
down slightly from 89.79 cents late Friday. Despite the decline,
the euro was a full cent above the record low of 88.45 cents it
reached on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Currency markets have been looking ahead to a Thursday meeting
of European Central Bank officials and other European financial
officials, but indications so far have been that no firm action to
support the flagging euro is likely to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   The euro has been drifting lower in recent weeks as the U.S.
economy continues to show strong staying power.
</P>
<P>
   In other trading Monday, the dollar was quoted at 109.03
Japanese yen, up from 108.34. The dollar also was quoted at 1.7276
Swiss francs, down from 1.7307, and 1.4917 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.4913.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
Based on Monday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.1803 German
marks, up from 2.1790; 7.3124 French francs, up from 7.3079; and
2,158.49 Italian lire, up from 2,174.49.
</P>
<P>
   The British pound rose to $1.5321 from $1.5274.
</P>
</TEXT>
