<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Hopeful on Chernobyl Cover  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said
Monday construction of a permanent cover over the Chernobyl nuclear
power plant will be a ''welcome gift for the people of Ukraine and
a great environmental victory for all of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright commmented after a meeting with Ukraine Prime Minister
Prime Minister Viktor Yushchenko. She said Yushchenko reaffirmed
the promise of President Leonid Kuchma to close the last Chernobyl
reactor by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Albright at a news conference was Foreign Minister
Joschka Fischer of Germany, where a pledging conference will be
held in July to raise funds for the construction of a new cover for
the Chernobyl plant.
</P>
<P>
   A cover, or sarcophagus, that was built not long after the 1986
nuclear disaster is considered unstable.
</P>
<P>
   Some $360 million in addition to $400 million already raised is
needed for the new cover.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official who attended Albright's meeting
with Yushchenko said he believes the donor countries will come up
with the money.
</P>
<P>
   Ukraine is concerned about alternate energy supplies once
Chernobyl is shut down completely. The senior official, asking not
to be identified, said two new nuclear reactors being contemplated
would cost about $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Chernobyl disaster caused an estimated 4,000 deaths among
those who took part in the cleanup, and 70,000 people were disabled
by radiation, according to Ukrainian government figures.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, about 3.4 million of Ukraine's 50 million people,
including some 1.26 million children, are considered affected by
Chernobyl, and many may not show the affects for years.
</P>
<P>
   Yushchenko also plans to President Clinton, National Security
Adviser Sandy Berger and Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summer during
his stay here.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton expects to visit Ukraine on June 2.
</P>
<P>
   About $225 million in U.S. assistance goes to Ukraine each year,
making it one of the highest recipients of U.S. aid dollars.
Geography and size make it one of the most important of the former
Soviet republics.
</P>
<P>
   A sore point in the relationship, the senior official said, is
the presence of factories that turn out pirated compact discs,
including many by American artists.
</P>
<P>
   The United States wants to work with the Ukrainians to end the
production, the official said.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Department:
www.state.gov/www/regions/nis/index.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 1731 </TRAILER>
