<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Sweeney Todd' at NY Philharmonic  </HEADLINE>
By MARY CAMPBELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Voices from opera and Broadway mingled
seamlessly in the New York Philharmonic's new concert version of
''Sweeney Todd,'' a show that is still strong with a score that is
superlative.
</P>
<P>
   The Philharmonic recorded the concerts on Thursday, Friday and
Saturday nights, and will issue a CD on its Special Editions label.
Andrew Litton, music director of the Dallas Symphony, conducted.
</P>
<P>
   George Hearn sang the lead in Stephen Sondheim's musical about a
19th century ''demon barber'' with deep emotion, conveying regret,
sadness and love for his long-lost wife and baby. Hearn, who had
followed the original 1979 lead, Len Cariou, on Broadway and sang
the part on television, was filling in for Metropolitan Opera
bass-baritone Bryn Terfel, who is recovering from back surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Vocally, Hearn dipped back and forth between sanity and madness,
turning into a vengeful monster who slices throats instead of
giving shaves.
</P>
<P>
   Patti LuPone, in her first Sondheim show, was sprightly and
optimistic -- with a voice that can belt -- as the practical Mrs.
Lovett, who has the bright idea to use the corpses in the meat pies
she sells.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Plishka of the Met sang Judge Turpin, who sent Todd to
Australia as a convict and made Todd's daughter, Johanna, his ward.
Heidi Grant Murphy of the Met sang Johanna while Davis Gaines of
''The Phantom of the Opera'' played the young sailor who loves her,
and there was no clash of styles in their duets.
</P>
<P>
   Other classical singers included John Aler and Stanford Olsen as
the judge's pal, the Beadle, and another barber.
</P>
<P>
   Audra McDonald, who has three Tony awards for Broadway roles,
sang an old beggar and Neil Patrick Harris, from the TV series
''Doogie Howser'' and Broadway's ''Rent,'' sang Tobias, the boy who
offers to protect Mrs. Lovett with the song ''Not While I'm
Around.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Philharmonic presented a concert version of Sondheim's
''Follies'' in 1985, the cast stood in front of the orchestra to
sing the songs. ''Sweeney Todd'' has been upgraded to semi-staged.
The New York Choral Artists stood on risers across the back of the
Avery Fisher Hall stage, but could walk quickly down each side wall
to the front.
</P>
<P>
   The principals used the front of the stage, as when Mrs. Lovett
played an imaginary harmonium, and, on a raised stage in the middle
of the orchestra, Todd cut his victims' throats. A red light hit
them at the moment of murder, but there was no blood or chute for
the body. Still, a viewer felt a frisson of horror.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 1737 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000508.0127 </DOCNO>
