<P>
   'Love Bug' Virus Suspect Arrested
</P>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- A bank employee in the Philippines is
under arrest on suspicion of links to the ''ILOVEYOU' computer
virus that overwhelmed networks around the world. His girlfiend is
also under suspicion. But relatives of the man, Reomel Ramones,
said they believe the real culprit may be a third person who lived
in the couple's apartment -- the girlfriend's unemployed sister, who
recently graduated from a computer school that a U.S. security firm
has been tied to the ''Love Bug'' virus. Investigators raided the
suspects' apartment in Pandacan, a lower-middle-class Manila
neighborhood, and seized computer diskettes, wires, telephones and
other computer accessories, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Prepares Counterproposal
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. is reported to be exploring a
number of possible alternatives to the government's plan for a
company breakup. The company is due to submit its response to the
government on Wednesday. Spokesman Mark Murray said today it is too
soon to talk publicly about what Microsoft will do. But media
reports suggest it will raise the possibility of allowing computer
makers more flexibility in installing and altering the Windows
operating system. Another possibility is that Microsoft also might
suggest offering a version of Windows without the Internet Explorer
Web browser tied to it. The linkage was one of the first charges
leveled at the company by the U.S. Justice Department and 19 state
attorneys general.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Urges Low-Cost Banking
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is proposing a $30
million plan to help millions of low-income people open low-cost,
basic bank accounts, Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said
today. An estimated 10 percent of U.S. households, or some 10
million families, do not have bank accounts. They are predominantly
poor and minority and often elderly or disabled, according to
government officials. The so-called ''First Accounts'' plan will be
proposed to Congress this week, Summers told the Consumer Bankers
Association that the plan would provide subsidies such as tax
incentives to banks, thrifts and credit unions to offer low-cost,
''no frills'' checking accounts for lower-income people.
</P>
<P>
   Cable Execs Want TV Rules Changed
</P>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Still stinging from last week's highly
publicized spat between ABC and Time Warner, cable executives who
gathered for their annual convention said today the laws governing
their transmission deals with broadcasters need to be re-examined.
Time Warner chief Gerald Levin said the law never should have
permitted the showdown that left 3.5 millions of his customers
without a local ABC signal for a day and a half. A week ago, ABC
service was cut off for Time Warner customers in seven cities after
the two companies failed to reach agreement on a transmission deal.
Service resumed when they agreed to extend negotiations until
mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   ExciteAtHome Picks New Chairman
</P>
<P>
   REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) ---- Internet access company
ExciteAtHome announced company chief executive George Bell has
succeeded Thomas Jermoluk as chairman of the board. Jermoluk, 43,
last week stepped down as chairman, but will remain on the board,
according to the company, which sells Internet access through cable
companies such as AT&AMP;T, Comcast Corp. and Cox Communications. Bell,
who also is ExciteAtHome's president, took on the additional
responsibilities after the company said it expected to report
operating losses through the remaining of the fiscal year as
first-quarter expenses tripled and sales were below Wall Street
expectations.
</P>
