<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israelis Honors Fallen Soldiers  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- With a wail of sirens, Israel slowed its usual
frenetic activity Monday and began a solemn, nationwide tribute to
nearly 20,000 soldiers killed in the nation's wars and terror
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In a uniquely Israeli contrast, Memorial Day is followed
immediately by raucous Independence Day celebrations, underlining
the link the people see between the wars and their nation's fate.
</P>
<P>
   Since Nov. 29, 1947, when the United Nations approved the
creation of the state of Israel, 19,109 people have been killed in
military service or in hostile acts, according to the Defense
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   In a close-knit country of 6 million people, that translates
into a personal sense of mourning.
</P>
<P>
   Most businesses close early for the ceremonies that run from
Monday evening to Tuesday evening, and Israelis visit cemeteries to
honor fallen friends, relatives and schoolmates.
</P>
<P>
   Air raid sirens sound twice on Memorial Day, once Monday night
and again Tuesday morning, directing Israelis to stop what they are
doing and pay tribute. Traffic comes to a halt, and drivers stand
next to their cars on streets and highways.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak and President Ezer Weizman, both
ex-generals, attended the opening ceremony at the Western Wall in
the Old City of Jerusalem, Judaism's holiest site.
</P>
<P>
   ''Again we are with you, my brothers,'' army chief Lt. Gen.
Shaul Mofaz said at the ceremony, ''and the pain that scorches like
the burn of forged iron is too hard to bear.''
</P>
<P>
   After the two-year war that followed the creation of the state,
Israeli soldiers went to battle again in 1956, 1967, 1973 and 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, a transition ceremony is to take place at the Mt.
Herzl military cemetery in Jerusalem, marking the end of Memorial
Day and the beginning of Independence Day, complete with a
fireworks display.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 1741 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000508.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FBI: Kentucky to seek death penalty for suspect in kidnap-murder  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Kentucky authorities will seek the death
penalty for a New Jersey man accused of kidnapping and murdering a
British computer consultant last month, the FBI said Monday.
However, a Kentucky prosecutor said no decision has yet been made.
</P>
<P>
   Dental records confirmed that the victim was Paul Jeffrey Gale,
who died of strangulation, according to autopsy results announced
Monday by Special Agent Sandra Carroll, a spokeswoman for the
Newark office.
</P>
<P>
   She said dental records were needed because Gale's body had been
burned in an effort to hinder identification following his
abduction April 17 from a hotel room in Florence, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have not determined where Gale was killed, but so
far believe the murder happened in Kentucky, Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   Gale's family has taken his body back to England, Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe Gale, 28, of Naples, Fla., was kidnapped and
killed by Gregory J. Marcinski because Gale was dating Marcinski's
former lover.
</P>
<P>
   Marcinski, 23, of Brick, was arrested April 20 and extradited to
Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   The body was found in a shallow grave about two miles from
Marcinski's residence April 27 after his housemate, Preston C.
Foray Jr., admitted he helped hide the body and gave agents the
location, the FBI has said in a court filing.
</P>
<P>
   ''They torched the body and apparently ran over it several times
with a truck'' while burying Gale in New Jersey, Carroll said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Foray, 21, was arrested April 26. He faces a federal charge of
being an accessory after the fact of a kidnapping. The two young
men lived with Marcinski's grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   A Kentucky prosecutor handling the case, Linda Tally Smith, an
assistant commonwealth attorney for Boone County, said Monday that
no decision has been made on whether to seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until we get all the lab results back, I don't think it's
prudent to make a definitive statement,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The case will be presented to a Boone County grand jury,
probably on May 23, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Under Kentucky law, kidnapping can be elevated to a capital
offense if the victim is not released alive, and four types of
penalties are available for capital offenses, Smith said: death,
life without parole, no parole for at least 25 years, and a prison
term of at least 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   According to investigators and court papers, Marcinski drove his
grandmother's Buick 800 miles and flashed bogus FBI credentials to
get into Gale's room at the Holiday Inn in Florence, Ky., a city
across the Ohio River from Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Marcinski awakened Gale, handcuffed him, and drove off.
Marcinski told Foray that he killed the man after driving for about
an hour, Foray told agents.
</P>
<P>
   Gale, a native of Birmingham, England, had apartments in Naples,
Fla., and in Mount Laurel, N.J., where he worked as a computer
programmer for TRW Integrated Supply. At the time of his death, he
was working for TRW in Kentucky as a consultant in the merger of
two pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
