<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Marks Bombing of Embassy  </HEADLINE>
By ELAINE KURTENBACH, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- In contrast to last year's violent protests,
China marked the first anniversary of NATO's bombing of its embassy
in Yugoslavia with low-key forums, wreath-laying for three people
killed, and newspaper editorials claiming a Chinese triumph over
''evil.''
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, there was no repeat of the angry mobs who hurled
concrete and shouted anti-American slogans outside the U.S. Embassy
and protested in 20 other cities after five bombs slammed into the
Chinese Embassy on May 7 Belgrade time, May 8 in the Chinese
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Just five or six extra police were stationed Monday in streets
outside the U.S. Embassy. As usual, dozens of people patiently
waited for visa appointments outside the mission's consular
section, which remained open.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got a nice quiet spring day in Beijing, for which we are
grateful,'' U.S. Ambassador Joseph Prueher said, walking out of the
renovated embassy compound, which a year ago was besieged, its
front paint-smeared, its windows shattered.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an event that neither the people in the United States nor
the people in China can forget,'' Prueher said. ''This is an event
that occurred that is part of the fabric now of the U.S.-China
relationship. So we must deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials, colleagues and relatives of Shao Yunhuan, Xu Xinghu
and Zhu Ying, three Chinese journalists killed in the attack, laid
flowers Monday at their graves in a cemetery in western Beijing,
the official Xinhua News Agency reported. It said the bombing and
NATO were condemned at forums for student representatives, scholars
and journalists in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Universities that last year organized buses from campuses to the
embassy district were ordered to keep students under control.
</P>
<P>
   At Peking University, whose students protested in large numbers,
the anniversary passed largely unremarked. The campus was covered
in red banners. Posters advertised opportunities for overseas study
in the United States, Canada and other NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just because we're not out protesting doesn't mean we don't
think about it. We're still angry,'' said Xiong Yuanmeng, an
economics major.
</P>
<P>
   The attack sent China-U.S. relations to their lowest point in a
decade and prompted an outburst of patriotism that the ruling
Communist Party has used to bolster its hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   ''In this contest between justice and evil and between truth and
power politics, we launched a firm struggle and won a major
victory,'' People's Daily, the party newspaper, said in a
front-page editorial marking the bombing that all national
newspapers also carried.
</P>
<P>
   China opposed NATO's war with Yugoslavia over Kosovo and still
accuses the United States and other Western powers of interfering
in the affairs of less powerful nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
