<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Still Reeling Over Real  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL ASTOR, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- The high cost of credit,
complicated tax systems, inefficient governments and unruly
macroeconomic indicators were all blamed for hindering Latin
America's competitiveness during a major trade conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But the tension simmering below the surface at the Mercosur
Economic Summit had mostly to do with last year's devaluation of
the Brazilian real and the monkey wrench it threw into trade
relations between Brazil and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ''Much has been done quickly, but not quickly enough considering
(recent financial problems) in Mexico, Russia, Asia and last year's
devaluation in Brazil,'' said Arturo T. Acevedo, president of
Argentine steel maker Acindar.
</P>
<P>
   The January 1999 devaluation sharply raised the prices of
Argentine goods in Brazil, quickly dampening Argentina's chief
export market. Further aggravating matters, many Argentine
companies fled to Brazil where the cost of doing business is
significantly cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina's former finance minister, Domingo Cavallo, recently
said the devaluation had effectively killed the Mercosur trade
bloc, comprised of Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay, Bolivia
and Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Created in 1991, Mercosur represents a market with a combined
gross domestic product of more than $1 trillion and a consumer
market made up of the region's 200 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders also used the conference to rail at
protectionism in the first world.
</P>
<P>
   Jorio Dauster, president of Brazilian mining giant Companhia
Vale do Rio Doce, complained of what he called ''a deeply
asymmetrical globalization,'' in which first world countries have
easy access to third world markets for their exports while traffic
in the opposite direction is often impeded.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to recognize a deep inequality in that Latin American
products don't have access to markets that would be correct and
desirable in capital terms,'' Dauster said, adding that in many
cases these barriers were cloaked in the veil of environmental or
social protections.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping above the fray, Brazilian Central Bank President Arminio
Fraga offered an upbeat assessment of the economy and said the cost
of credit would decline as economic indicators improved.
</P>
<P>
   Fraga said the country should grow 4 percent this year and more
than 5 percent in the medium-term.
</P>
<P>
   But Fraga also conceded that advances needed to be made in the
area of education, tax reform and financial transparency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 1750 </TRAILER>
