<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ky. School Team Wins Science Bowl  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A team from a Louisville, Ky., high school won
the Energy Department's National Science Bowl on Monday, with a
physics question about measuring extremely small distances.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont Manual High School defeated last year's winning team,
Montgomery Blair High School in Silver Spring, Md., in final
minutes of the competition between the five-member teams. The
10-year-old science bowl, held this year in Chevy Chase, Md., is
among the first of this season's national academic competitions.
The National Geographic Geography Bee and the Scripps Howard
Spelling Bee will be held later this month.
</P>
<P>
   In a format similar to the ''College Bowl'' and ''Jeopardy''
quiz shows, the students from DuPont Manual buzzed first to answer
the final question just before time ran out.
</P>
<P>
   The final question, in physics, was: ''An angstrom is equal to
how many picometers?'' The Kentucky team's correct answer, ''100,''
gave them the title and an expenses-paid hiking trip across
Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   An angstrom -- referring to a value used to measure wavelengths
of visible light and other forms of electromagnetic radiation such
as ultraviolet or X rays -- is one ten-billionth of a meter.
</P>
<P>
   For 8 days in July, the students will tour and study the state's
environment with scientists from the Energy Department's Pacific
Northwest National Laboratory, which conducts a variety of nuclear
and environmental research. The trip begins at the Hanford Reach of
the Columbia River and ends in the Cascade Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The Maryland students will take the second-place prize trip to
South Carolina for alligator-watching and an archaeological dig at
the Energy Department's Savannah River environmental research site.
</P>
<P>
   The trips are designed to provide hands-on educational
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, who presented the trophy,
invited the nation's youth to ''test the waters of math and
science, which will provide the high-paying jobs of the 21st
Century.''
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top five teams, which also received trophies
and calculators, were A&AMP;M Consolidated High School, College
Station, Texas; North Hollywood High School, North Hollywood,
Calif., and Gateway High School of Monroe, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ----On the Net: The Energy Department will post complete results
at: http://www.doe.gov/sciencebowl/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
