<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philly May Adopt All-Uniform Rule  </HEADLINE>
By TINA MOORE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The days of short shorts and concert
T-shirts appear to be numbered in the city's 256 public schools
under a proposal that would make Philadelphia the first big-city
district in the nation to require all students to wear uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   The school district board was scheduled to vote Monday night on
a dress-code policy for its 217,000 students. The policy would go
into effect immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The measure does not call for a single, Roman
Catholic-school-style uniform; instead, schools could decide
individually how students should dress.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is certainly not the answer to academic achievement or
school climate, but I think it can be one component to establishing
respect for the school,'' said Christine James-Brown, head of the
six-member committee of the school district's board that
recommended the policy last week.
</P>
<P>
   James-Brown said schools would be pushed to look at clothes that
are inexpensive and readily available. Punishment for failing to
abide by a dress code would probably not be attached to the policy
for the rest of the school year, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Discipline and other particulars, such as provisions for
students who can't wear the uniforms for religious reasons, would
be worked out by a committee of parents, students and educators.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce D. Ryan, principal of James Elverson Middle School,
believes uniforms will also cut back on competition among students.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it will help add to uniformity of thought,'' Ryan
said. ''It will take their minds off the social aspect of
interacting and put it more on the important facts of learning.''
</P>
<P>
   But student Khayree Campbell, an 18-year-old senior at Benjamin
Franklin High School, is strongly opposed to wearing a uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ''What does that have to do with learning?'' said Campbell, who
was wearing a tank top and shorts. ''I feel as though you should be
able to wear whatever you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanneka Henry, 15, said she looked forward to the break from
buying fancy clothes to impress friends. ''Everybody wants that
name-brand stuff,'' she said. She said she would use the money she
saves for college.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, educators grappling with school violence are trying
to bust up cliques and limit adolescent isolation. President
Clinton has endorsed dress-code policies, and the Philadelphia
school board looked into the issue last month at the request of
Mayor John Street.
</P>
<P>
   While other cities have uniform policies, no city as large as
Philadelphia, the fifth-biggest in the nation, has a district-wide
policy. In Miami, 60 percent of public schools require uniforms. In
Chicago, the number is 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Parents in New York City's elementary schools voted last year on
whether or not they wanted their children to wear uniforms. About
half of the schools now have a uniform policy.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the National Association of Elementary School
Principals in 1998 found that 52 percent of principals requiring
uniforms reported a boost in student performance.
</P>
<P>
   At John L. Bernstein PS 137 in New York City, students arrived
at school in September wearing crisp, new blue and white uniforms.
In the beginning, the policy appeared to boost student morale,
Principal May Beyda said.
</P>
<P>
   However, in light of the recent heat wave in the city, Beyda
plans to rescind the uniform policy for June. ''We don't have air
conditioning and not all my kids can afford the shorts,'' Beyda
said.
</P>
<P>
   Parents at Beyda's school can write a note excusing their
children from wearing uniforms. Otherwise, Beyda said, the school
would face multiple lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Stefan Presser, legal director of the American Civil Liberties
Union of Pennsylvania, said his organization might challenge
Philadelphia's policy if it were to violate a student's rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''Aside from reading and writing, public schools are supposed to
be teaching democracy,'' Presser said. ''Uniforms are antithetical
to teaching people how to make choices.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.phila.k12.pa.us
</P>
<P>
   http://www.naesp.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.aclu.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
