<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Nixes Rebel Cease-Fire  </HEADLINE>
By LAURINDA KEYS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Sri Lankan officials said Monday they
will reject a proposal by the Tamil Tiger rebels for a temporary
cease-fire that would allow the evacuation of 40,000 government
troops from the northern city of Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
   The safe passage offer amounted to a call for the surrender of
the city of 500,000 ''to prevent the further escalation of violence
and a blood bath,'' according to the rebel statement. It was faxed
Monday to news agencies in the Sri Lankan capital, Colombo, and in
New Delhi from the London office of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam.
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire offer will not be accepted because of the
evacuation condition, a senior government official told The
Associated Press in Colombo. He said President Chandrika
Kumaratunga favors peace talks, but will not accept any conditions
or compromise the sovereignty of Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said a formal statement would be issued later.
</P>
<P>
   In Colombo, Kumaratunga delivered a 30-minute television address
Monday, reiterating her determination to win the war and bring
peace to the country despite the ''temporary setback, a serious
setback.''
</P>
<P>
   She blamed the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, or LTTE, for
not giving a favorable response to her attempts to initiate peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the last year I tried through various means to initiate a
peace process with the LTTE. We even obtained the assistance of
foreign countries, but the LTTE did not react favorably,'' she
said, without referring to Monday's cease-fire offer.
</P>
<P>
   The government has indicated it is prepared to fight to hold on
to the city and the nearby Palali air base, the crucial supply link
for troops defending Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
   The offer of a truce came as the Sri Lankan air force bombed
rebel artillery positions at Elephant Pass, the land bridge that
the rebels captured last month between the Jaffna Peninsula and the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials said the army was using weaponry newly
acquired on the international arms market to strengthen the new
military defense line, 15 miles southeast of Jaffna, in the hope of
stopping a rebel advance toward the city.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffna, considered the center of Tamil culture and history, was
under the rebels' control from 1990-95. During that time, it was
the capital of a virtual Tamil state, which had its own police,
judiciary and border controls. However, the government never lost
control of the Palali airport.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of the truce offer were delayed in Sri Lanka by military
censorship that has been imposed on the local and foreign media.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers' statement said the LTTE ''is prepared to declare a
temporary cease-fire suspending all armed hostilities against the
Sri Lankan armed forces to facilitate the beleaguered government
troops to be evacuated safely from the Jaffna peninsula.''
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire would come into effect as soon as the Sri Lankan
government responds that it is willing to observe a halt in
fighting, the rebel statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels called upon the International Committee of the Red
Cross ''to supervise and assist the orderly evacuation of troops.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebels, who were in retreat for years after the Jaffna
peninsula fell to the army in 1996, turned the tide of the war with
an offensive last November that reclaimed hundreds of square miles
in the northern jungles.
</P>
<P>
   They scored another important victory last month when they
seized Elephant Pass, forcing 10,000 Sri Lankan troops to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are demanding an independent country for the Tamil
minority because they say the majority Sinhalese discriminate
against them. The government has denied the charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 1752 </TRAILER>
