<HEADLINE> New Kosovo Commander at Helm  </HEADLINE>
By DANICA KIRKA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Amid a rash of violence, the new
commander of NATO peacekeepers in Kosovo warned Monday that Western
governments will withhold support if attacks on minority groups
persist.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish Lt. Gen. Juan Ortuno pledged that his term in command of
NATO-led troops would be marked by efforts to foster harmony in a
province struggling to overcome a war and a decade of oppression
under the government of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Ortuno told reporters in his first news conference that he
wanted to win the ''hearts and minds'' of ethnic Albanians, the
Serbs and others that make up Kosovo -- in part by fighting for more
funding to the perennially cash-strapped mission.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he warned that Western efforts to help must be met in
equal measure by efforts from Kosovo residents to take individual
responsibility in promoting tolerance -- or ultimately risk losing
support.
</P>
<P>
   ''The focus of the world is still on Kosovo, but this will not
last forever,'' he said. ''The people of Kosovo must work together
to build coexistence and to foster tolerance to send the right
signal to the international community.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortuno spoke amid reports of new violence -- much, if not all,
apparently ethnically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Four Kosovo Serbs were shot and wounded by ethnic Albanians on
Sunday, and a former regional commander of the disbanded Kosovo
Liberation Army was shot and killed Monday in the southern town of
Prizren, peacekeepers and U.N. police reported.
</P>
<P>
   Ekrem Rexha, better known by his nickname Drini, was the former
KLA commander for southern Kosovo. He was killed outside his home.
U.N. police said Drini was now serving in the local Prizren
government.
</P>
<P>
   Ortuno, who took command from German Gen. Klaus Reinhardt in
April, suggested that people should register to vote in coming
elections and support Western initiatives, such as the return of
refugees to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of Serbs and other minorities have fled from
their homes since the arrival of peacekeepers after NATO's 78-day
air war last year to halt Milosevic's attacks on ethnic Albanians.
The Serbs and other minorities have feared attacks leveled in
revenge for Milosevic's 18-month-long crackdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
