<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assembly committee passes $90 million fire sprinkler bill  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Public and private colleges in New Jersey
would have to install fire sprinklers in every dorm room, but
they'd have five years -- instead of two -- to do it, under a bill
that passed an Assembly committee on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers responded to pleas from college representatives and
the people who install the sprinklers for more time to get the work
completed.
</P>
<P>
   They said the original two-year deadline, approved by the Senate
in March, would be impossible to meet.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is in response to a fire at Seton Hall
University in January, which killed three students and injured 62
others. Seton Hall is installing sprinklers in every room in time
for the fall semester.
</P>
<P>
   State senators and the Whitman administration had been pushing
to get the sprinklers installed in all New Jersey dorms within two
years. But they had also acknowledged that the deadline would be
tough to meet.
</P>
<P>
   So, Assembly lawmakers proposed a compromise: two years to
outfit the dormitory common areas and four years to finish all the
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   During a hearing Monday before the Assembly Housing Committee,
representatives from both colleges and the sprinkler industry
rejected that compromise, saying it would make the job more
difficult and more costly.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Richman, assistant commissioner at the state Department
of Community Affairs, pushed for the tighter deadlines, saying the
industry could get all the work done in four years.
</P>
<P>
   But, Richard Hodvance, vice president of the New Jersey State
Association of Pipe Trades, said doing the work in phases would add
15 percent to 20 percent to the total cost.
</P>
<P>
   The committee unanimously passed the bill that calls for a
five-year time frame, requiring schools to complete 20 percent of
the work each year for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges and universities would also have to submit a plan to
the state Department of Community Affairs four months after the
bill is signed into law.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Girgenti, D-Passaic, said he expects the Senate to
concur with the changes.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers hope to have the bill in place by June.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would also appropriate $90 million to help pay for
the sprinklers. Public and private colleges and universities would
get zero-interest loans, while boarding schools, military academies
and other schools that have dorms would have to repay the loans at
2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The bill allows exemptions for certain buildings. That would
most likely apply to ''very small'' buildings, said Richman.
</P>
<P>
   State officials estimate that more than 36,000 college dorm beds
are located in rooms without sprinklers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-08-00 1821 </TRAILER>
