<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Llosa Calls Fujimori a Dictator  </HEADLINE>
By MONTE HAYES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Peru's famed novelist Mario Vargas Llosa
lashed out on Monday at President Alberto Fujimori, calling him a
dictator who uses extortion and spying to cling to power.
</P>
<P>
   On a rare visit to his homeland, the 64-year-old Vargas Llosa
called the Peruvian president a modern-day version of Dominican
strongman Rafael Leonidas Trujillo, who is the subject of the
author's latest novel entitled ''The Goat's Party.''
</P>
<P>
   During a meeting with foreign correspondents, the author, who
was defeated by Fujimori in the 1990 presidential election, said
Trujillo resorted to murder and torture to hang onto power for
three decades until he was assassinated in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   He said Fujimori, on the other hand, has had to maintain a
democratic facade because overt dictatorships face international
isolation in today's world. He said that Fujimori instead has used
electronic surveillance, blackmail, tax audits and threats of
expropriation of property to silence critics and maintain control.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Trujillo's brutality, ''these intimidating methods are
invisible, and cannot be proven or demonstrated,'' he said. ''In
many cases it seems like paranoia by citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Vargas Llosa's stunning upset loss to Fujimori in 1990 initiated
a decade in power for Fujimori that would be extended another five
years if he wins re-election in this month's presidential runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas Llosa, who has visited Peru only three times in the last
eight years, said one of the reasons he had returned was to express
support for Fujimori's opponent, economist Alejandro Toledo, in the
May 28 election.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo's 11th hour surge from a field of eight opposition
candidates blocked Fujimori from winning a majority of votes in the
first round, which he needed to avoid a runoff. Fujimori fell a
hair short, with 49.9 percent of the votes to Toledo's 40.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''The truth is that what happened in the first round surprised
me, as I think it surprised everyone inside and outside Peru. I
saw, as many did, a light at the end of the tunnel,'' Vargas Llosa
said.
</P>
<P>
   The author said Fujimori tried to rig the vote total to win a
first-round victory on April 9, but was frustrated by international
monitors and massive street protests on the night of the election.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas Llosa predicted that if international pressure is
maintained and Peruvians remain alert against any signs of fraud,
''we can put an end to these eight years of an authoritarian regime
that has made our country the exception to the rule.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Fujimori shut down an opposition-controlled Congress
and the courts, saying they were crippling his efforts to defeat
leftist rebels and impose free-market reforms to end economic
chaos. Fujimori supporters won control of a new Congress elected
six months later.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas Llosa, who now lives in London, denied charges by
Fujimori's defenders that he has condemned Peru's government as
dictatorial because he is bitter over his election defeat by
Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   ''The truth is Peruvians did me a favor by returning me to my
writer's desk in 1990 because only good things have happened to me
as a writer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to his time on the campaign trail, he added, ''I
learned a lot of things about my country. I also learned a lot
about myself. I learned I wasn't a politician.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 1821 </TRAILER>
