<HEADLINE> Independence Party faction complains about Clinton  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A faction of Independence Party leaders
called Monday for U.S. Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton to
apologize for remarks she made at a party forum if she wants their
support.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady was close to receiving endorsement from party
leaders even without a primary before her speech at the April 29
forum, said Jeff Graham, former Watertown mayor and party leader.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this point in time, her chances of a primary-proof
convention are virtually nil,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had said she would not share a ticket with conservative
Pat Buchanan if he runs on the Reform Party's line for president.
The Independence Party is Reform's New York wing.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady also took a direct slap at Lenora Fulani, a
former leader of the left-leaning New Alliance Party, who has
become a force in the Independence Party.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pat Buchanan and his ally Lenora Fulani have a long history of
making divisive and anti-Semitic statements and Hillary isn't going
to apologize for speaking the truth,'' Clinton campaign spokesman
Howard Wolfson said. ''The person who should apologize is Rudy
Giuliani for waffling on running on the same ticket as Pat
Buchanan.''
</P>
<P>
   Independence Party Secretary Laureen Oliver accused Clinton
Monday of trying to ''sabotage'' the party by speaking ill of some
of its leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the past six years, state Democrats have tried to take
over this party,'' Oliver said. ''And now Hillary Clinton comes
along and tries to sabotage it because her and her party can't
control it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton's Senate rival New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani later expressed similar reservations about Buchanan, those
at Monday's news conference said the Republican mayor was not as
much at fault because his remarks were not made at the party's
forum.
</P>
<P>
   Hope released a statement Monday saying she ''never meant to
imply that all leaders and members of the Independence Party
indulge in anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign did not immediately return a call though
Hope's statement said she looks forward to continuing a good
working relationship with ''much of the Independence Party
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Kaufman, also of the Democratic Party, called charges
about taking over the Independence Party ''nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Mentioned briefly at the news conference was squabbling among
the party leaders. Last month, a state judge reinstated Jack
Essenberg as party chairman, overturning his earlier ouster by
others in the party including Frank MacKay, who was voted in as the
party's new chairman. MacKay took part in Monday's news conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
