<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spaniards Protest Writer's Slaying  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM BROWN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Spaniards stood in silence nationwide
Monday to protest the killing of a newspaper columnist, a slaying
blamed on Basque separatists.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the news media expressed fear that separatists may
target other journalists or intimidate them against telling the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands gathered in silence throughout the day in
Madrid, Barcelona, San Sebastian and other Spanish cities and towns
to remember Jose Luis Lopez de Lacalle, a political columnist and
critic of ETA, who was gunned down early Sunday in the Basque
region.
</P>
<P>
   ETA -- whose initials in the Basque language stand for Basque
Freedom and Homeland -- has killed some 800 people since 1968, when
it began its independence campaign of shootings and bombings.
</P>
<P>
   ETA did not claim responsibility for the Lopez's killing.
Spanish police, news media and politicians blamed the shooting on
separatist commandos.
</P>
<P>
   In Andoain, Lopez's hometown, a large crowd shouted ''Freedom,
freedom'' and ''ETA out'' as the journalist's coffin was carried
into the hearse.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish government ministers, the president of the Basque
region, and politicians from different parties joined Lopez's
family to bury the journalist.
</P>
<P>
   After the funeral, thousands of people marched in silence
through Andoain to where the shooting took place Sunday outside
Lopez's home.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, King Juan Carlos and Queen Sofia joined a silent vigil
from a balcony of the southern city hall of Jerez de la Frontera,
one of many vigils in front of city and town halls.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar, on an official visit to
Morocco, condemned the killing and called for early elections in
the Basque country, saying that democracy and the ballot box are
''the only answer.''
</P>
<P>
   ''You must be democratic before being nationalist,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Employees of El Mundo, the newspaper that ran Lopez's weekly
column, held a somber gathering outside the newspaper's office in
Madrid to remember their colleague.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, 62, was shot as he strolled home from his routine morning
walk to a newspaper stand and then to a cafe for a croissant and
coffee in the Basque town of Andoain.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, ETA has mostly targeted police officers, soldiers and
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish journalists say Lopez's slaying and recent attempts on
the lives of other journalists show the group has added easier prey
-- the press -- to its list of targets.
</P>
<P>
   ''ETA wants to provoke fear in society and doesn't want
journalists to tell the truth,'' said Casimiro Garcia Abadillo, a
director at El Mundo.
</P>
<P>
   ''Journalists are an easy target. They don't have bodyguards or
protection, and they don't take the same precautions as a
politician or a Civil Guard,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
