<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Ends Down 147; Dow Up 25  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks drifted to a mixed finish in the quietest
session of the year Monday as investors worried about interest
rates and took profits from a modest rally on Friday. Technology
stocks fell.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 147.44 to close at 3,669.38 and
the Dow Jones industrial average rose 25.77 to close at 10,603.63.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 fell 8.46 to 1,424.17.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said the most significant action in the market came from
investors selling stocks to capture short-term gains from a solid
rally Friday, when the Dow rose 165 points and the Nasdaq rose 96.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks, which led Friday's gains, were mostly lower
Monday. Hewlett-Packard fell 1 1/16 to 135 11/16 and Intel dropped
5} to 117|.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems fell 5[ to 85] and PMC-Sierra fell 12{ to 167{.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco dropped 5 to 62} after an article in Barron's said the
company's stunning growth rate could slow if Cisco stops acquiring
companies at a rapid rate.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the technology sector, investors stayed resolutely on the
sidelines, pondering next Tuesday's meeting of the Federal Reserve,
which is expected to raise interest rates for the sixth time since
last June.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists expect the Fed to raise rates by as much as a
half-percentage point. The last five rate increases have come in a
series of modest, quarter-percentage point hikes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The momentum in the economy gives the Fed ample reason to
boost rates'' by a half-point, said Joseph T. Keating, chief
investment officer for the Kent Funds in Grand Rapids, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   While some Wall Street analysts believe investors would welcome
a sharper increase as a sign that the Fed is finally nearing the
end of its cycle of rate increases, the uncertainty has contributed
to a sharp drop in trading activity in the past few sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Despite the entrenched optimism in the market, investors will
not be able to ignore a more aggressive Federal Reserve,'' said
Sung Won Sohn, chief economist at Wells Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   Rising interest rates are generally bad for stocks because they
cut into corporate profits by increasing the cost of borrowing
money. Last week, the rate-sensitive financial sector bore the
brunt of investors' worries and fell steeply.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks outperformed the broader market as investors
bought them at reduced prices. American Express rose 5 7/16 to 152
1/16 and J.P. Morgan rose 3 11/16 to 125 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   ''Financial stocks are probably due for a rebound,'' Keating
said. ''But that sector, more than any other, needs some sign that
the Fed's tightening cycle is coming to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Mergers and acquisitions stimulated some trading activity.
Verio, an Internet service provider and Web hosting company, soared
22] to 58 5/16 after Japan's NTT Communications Corp. agreed to
acquire it for about $5 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Ancor Communications rose 7 to 38 3/16 after agreeing to be
acquired by Qlogic Corp. in a stock deal valued at about $1.7
billion. Both Ancor and Qlogic make equipment for computer-storage
networks. Qlogic shares plunged 25 3/16 to 74}.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 11-to-7 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange and by a 9-to-5 margin on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE composite volume totaled 946.33 million shares, compared
with 964.65 million in the previous session. The Nasdaq also had
its quietest day of 2000, with 1.11 billion shares changing hands
as of 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 12.76 to
500.08.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.3 percent.
Germany's DAX index fell 1.6 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 fell 0.4
percent, and France's CAC-40 closed 0.5 percent lower.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
