<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that are moving substantially or trading
heavily today on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock
Market.
</P>
<P>
NYSE
</P>
<P>
Telefonica S.A., down 2 47/64 at 64 13/16
</P>
<P>
   Telefonica ended merger negotiations with Dutch
telecommunications company Royal KPN NV because of objections from
the Spanish government and key shareholders. The combined company
would have been valued at more than $120 billion.
</P>
<P>
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, up 1] at 11~
</P>
<P>
   The company is scheduled to release its first-quarter earnings
report on Tuesday. Wall Street analysts expect strong results from
the company, a retailer of trendy casual clothing.
</P>
<P>
Geon Co., up \ at 24\
</P>
<P>
   Geon will merge with M.A. Hanna Co., potentially forming the
world's largest manufacturing and services company in the
engineered plastics field. The merger is a stock swap valued at
about $570 million.
</P>
<P>
NASDAQ
</P>
<P>
Cisco Systems, down 4~ at 62~
</P>
<P>
   Barron's said in an article that because Cisco's market value is
driven by its steady pace of acquisitions and its solid earnings,
growth could suffer if revenue flags or if the company stops
acquiring companies at a rapid pace.
</P>
<P>
Verio Inc., up 22] at 58 5/16
</P>
<P>
   The Internet services company agreed to be acquired by NTT
Communications Corp., the long-distance unit of Nippon Telegraph &AMP;
Telephone Corp. in a cash tender offer valued at $5 billion. NTT
already had a 10 percent stake in Verio.
</P>
<P>
Qlogic Corp., down 25 3/16 at 74}
Ancor Communications Inc., up 7 at 38 3/16
</P>
<P>
   Qlogic plans to acquire Ancor in a stock deal valued at about
$1.7 billion, bringing together two companies that make equipment
for computer-storage networks. Both companies' share prices have
fallen in recent months.
</P>
<P>
Emmis Communications Corp., down 10 1/16 at 33{
</P>
<P>
   Emmis agreed to buy eight network affiliate and seven satellite
television stations from Lee Enterprises Inc. for $562.5 million.
Emmis is purchasing stations in Portland, Oregon; Omaha, Neb.;
Tucson, Ariz.; Hawaii; New Mexico; Colorado; Kansas and West
Virginia.
</P>
