<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Member publishers attend AP annual meeting  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Associated Press is launching new
initiatives to help members tap Internet opportunities as it
enhances state reports and political coverage, Louis D. Boccardi,
the AP's president and chief executive officer, told the news
cooperative's annual meeting Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was attended by executives representing AP's 1,546
member newspapers on the first full day of the Newspaper
Association of America's convention. The meeting also featured a
panel on the 2000 elections and talks by Vice President Al Gore and
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright.
</P>
<P>
   AP Chairman Donald E. Newhouse called the meeting to order, and
Boccardi reported on the state of AP.
</P>
<P>
   Boccardi said the coming year would bring ''an ever-stronger
world and national news report; further exploration of the
opportunities and challenges the Internet presents, (and) sharper
focus on better performance on all levels.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, the AP is introducing a Web site called
the AP Election Center, ''for online readers who want as much
detail as they can get on the candidates, the issues and the
campaigns, from the White House to this interesting little thing
we've got going on in New York state this year'' -- referring to the
U.S. Senate race between first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and New
York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Another Web site for political reporters called AP Politics
offers a wealth of information, including campaign finances and
poll results, he said. And a forthcoming Web site called Your AP
will allow editors to access election results in November as soon
as the come into the AP system, rather than waiting for updates to
move on the wire.
</P>
<P>
   ''You'll know what we know when we know it,'' Boccardi said.
</P>
<P>
   Your AP will be an ongoing resource that keeps member editors
and publishers up to date on the AP news report and developments
within the AP.
</P>
<P>
   Boccardi said state news reports will soon be delivered in a
format that will enable editors of online editions to post them
easily to newspaper Web sites, and Web site addresses have been
added to the bottom of many AP stories.
</P>
<P>
   The AP's continuing commitment to improving state reports has
resulted in two new Chicago-based positions, Boccardi said. One is
a new writing coach -- AP's third -- and the other is a new deputy
director of state news.
</P>
<P>
   Gore used his appearance to bash as too risky a proposal by his
Republican presidential rival George W. Bush to invest a portion of
Social Security taxes in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is associated with some risk because ideas that look very
beguiling when the markets are great may not look so great if the
market turns,'' the vice president said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's spokesman Dan Bartlett later defended the proposal by
saying that ''what history has shown is the market, over a period
of time, has had a rate of return far greater than the Social
Security trust fund.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor is to address many of the same executives by
satellite Wednesday as part of the NAA convention.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also said he was open to a change in federal rules that
prohibit the same company from owning a newspaper and TV or radio
station in the same area, although he noted that it is up to the
Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he supported revising estate tax laws that create
hardship for families trying to pass a newspaper on from one
generation to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who spoke at the event's luncheon, said President
Clinton was approaching his summit talks with Russian President
Vladimir Putin with an open mind on the subject of U.S. missile
defenses.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton decides later this year whether to proceed with an
anti-missile program, he will weigh potential threats as well as
the merits of the technology and the costs, Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   AP members also heard from Alan Diaz, the photographer who took
the AP photographs inside the house where 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez
was seized by federal agents late last month.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of the raid, ''I had the instinct, the hunch,
that something was going to go down,'' Diaz said. When the raid
began, he immediately sprinted into the house and set up in the
room where the boy was being hidden in a closet.
</P>
<P>
   His overriding memory of the raid? ''All I could hear, and all I
could remember, was Elian crying,'' Diaz said.
</P>
<P>
   Boccardi also moderated a discussion of political campaigns with
Walter Mears, AP vice president and Washington columnist; Ron
Fournier, chief political writer in Washington; and Marc A.
Humbert, New York State political editor based in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Mears noted candidates try to avoid negative attacks on their
opponents these days because they think voters don't like it. But
Fournier pointed out that ''the new form of negative campaigning
seems to be to accuse your opponent of going negative.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting began with the announcement of election results for
the board of directors, held by all-mail balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Four incumbents and three new members were elected to the board.
</P>
<P>
   Elected to new terms were John J. Curley, chairman and CEO,
Gannett Co. Inc., Wilmington (Del.) News-Journal; Newhouse,
president, Advance Publications Inc., Newark (N.J.) Star-Ledger;
John W. Madigan, chairman, president and CEO, Tribune Co., Chicago
Tribune and Orage Quarles III, publisher, Raleigh (N.C.) News &AMP;
Observer.
</P>
<P>
   New members are Walter E. Hussman Jr., president and CEO, WEHCO
Media Inc., Arkansas Democrat-Gazette; Julie Inskeep Walda,
publisher, Fort Wayne (Ind.) Journal Gazette; and Sue Mayborn,
president and publisher, Temple (Texas) Daily Telegram. Walda was
selected to fill one year left in the term of Richard J.
Harrington, who is stepping down. Mayborn was selected to represent
a city of less than 50,000 population.
</P>
<P>
   At a reorganization meeting later in the day, Newhouse,
president of Advance Publications Inc. and of The Star-Ledger of
Newark, N.J., was re-elected chairman of the AP. David E. Easterly,
president and COO of Cox Enterprises Inc., representing the Dayton
(Ohio) Daily News, was elected vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Boccardi was re-elected president and chief executive officer of
the news cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Other AP management officers re-elected to one-year terms were
Patrick T. O'Brien, senior vice president and chief financial
officer; James M. Donna, vice president and secretary; and vice
presidents Vincent J. Alabiso, Claude E. Erbsen, Mears, John W.
Reid, Thomas E. Slaughter, Wick Temple and James R. Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan P. Wolman, executive editor, also was elected vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel M. Boruch was re-elected treasurer, and Salvatore Focella
and Ann Randolph were re-elected assistant treasurers. Other AP
management officers re-elected were assistant secretaries Lilo
Jedelhauser and Greg Groce.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
