<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Faces Mideast Peace Dilemma  </HEADLINE>
By SARI BASHI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- In the wake of an inconclusive summit with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
found himself squeezed Monday between territorial demands from the
Palestinians and resistance to land concessions from his closest
political partners.
</P>
<P>
   Barak confirmed for the first time that he wants to give the
Palestinians full control over three West Bank suburbs of
Jerusalem, but that strong political opposition from members of his
own coalition is holding him back.
</P>
<P>
   His comments came in the midst of negotiations for a final peace
treaty meant to address lingering disputes between Israel and the
Palestinians. The Palestinians demand all of the West Bank, Gaza
and east Jerusalem, regions captured by Israel in the 1967 Mideast
War. Israel wants to annex large blocs of Jewish settlements in the
West Bank and Gaza and retain control over all of Jerusalem,
claimed by both sides as their capital.
</P>
<P>
   By handing over the Jerusalem suburbs as a goodwill gesture
during the negotiations, Barak hopes to persuade the Palestinians
to put off discussing a final interim troop withdrawal that will
spark even stronger political opposition in Israel. The troop
withdrawal would give the Palestinians control over more of the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, though, Barak can't appease either the
Palestinians or his own motley coalition. He said Monday that it
may take weeks or months to persuade coalition partners,
particularly the ultra-Orthodox Shas party, to agree to the land
transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Israel will hand over the territory ''when the conditions are
ripe, meaning when we will have the necessary agreement, also
politically, within the Israeli system,'' Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister said that in exchange for offering the
Palestinians control over the three West Bank suburbs of Jerusalem
-- Abu Dis, Izzarieh and Sawahrah a-Sharkieh -- he wants them to
postpone talks on the interim troop pullback until after an outline
of the final peace treaty has been negotiated. Palestinian
negotiator Saeb Erekat, however, said the Palestinians were to have
assumed full control over those villages a long time ago and that
he expected Israel to implement the partial pullback by June, as
per peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians say the concessions Barak is offering fall far
short of what Israel has promised.
</P>
<P>
   They broke off peace talks last week in anger over what they
said was an Israeli proposal to build a Palestinian state in just
two-thirds of the West Bank and part of the Gaza Strip. A
Barak-Arafat summit Sunday night ended with participants reporting
no progress.
</P>
<P>
   ''We still have a very difficult and complicated situation,''
Erekat said. ''The gaps are great.''
</P>
<P>
   In the West Bank towns of Ramallah and Bethlehem, scores of
Palestinians frustrated with the slow pace of negotiations threw
stones at Israeli troops Monday. The troops responded with
rubber-coated steel pellets. Demonstrators demanded that all
Palestinian prisoners be released from Israeli jails -- a key issue
in interim peace accords. At least one person was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators met Monday and were to resume talks Thursday, after
the Israeli holidays of Memorial Day and Independence Day. They are
to produce an outline of a final peace treaty within two months.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting unidentified Palestinian sources, Israel Radio said that
Barak asked Arafat in their meeting to delay most of the deadlines
of the peace accords, including the interim withdrawal due by June,
the planned transfer of the Jerusalem suburbs and the framework
agreement, which has now been set for the next two months. The
radio said Arafat did not agree.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Mideast envoy Dennis Ross, wrapping up a weeklong mediation
trip to the region, met Arafat Monday and said he saw the potential
for progress. But, he said, ''there is a lot of work to be done
here.''
</P>
<P>
   He is to return next week after consulting with President
Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. Albright may
come to the region next month if there is progress in the talks,
and Barak will meet Clinton in the United States on May 23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
