<HEADLINE> NBC Hires Lalas for Olympics  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Former U.S. soccer player Alexi Lalas will join
Andres Cantor, owner of the distinctive ''GOOOOAAAAL'' call, in the
NBC broadcast booth at the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Lalas, a defender with bright red hair and goatee, played in two
Olympics and two World Cups for the United States. He was also the
first American to play in the first division of the prestigious
Italian League.
</P>
<P>
   He and Cantor, who created a following for himself during the
past two World Cups with his drawn-out goal calls and fast-paced
broadcasts on Spanish-language Univision, will be the first NBC
Olympic broadcast pair seen from Sydney when they call a Sept. 13
preliminary round men's soccer game on MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Lalas retired from Major League Soccer after last season and has
been providing color commentary for the San Jose Earthquakes'
television broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Lalas' hiring was announced Monday. Cantor was brought aboard
more than a month ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
