<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car theft down nationally, up in four N.J. cities  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Car theft rose in New Jersey's four largest
cities last year despite a drop around the nation, according to
crime statistics released by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI statistics released Sunday showed crime overall rose 1.2
percent in Jersey City in 1999, dropped 13 percent in Elizabeth,
0.5 percent in Paterson and 8.2 percent in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Serious crime dropped nationally 7 percent, part of an
eight-year nationwide decline in the seven major types of crime
listed in the FBI's Uniform Crime Report.
</P>
<P>
   But while car theft dropped across the nation by 8 percent, it
was up 16 percent in Elizabeth, 14.1 percent in Paterson, 10.4
percent in Jersey City and 5.3 percent in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Mark Kurdyla, a spokesman for Elizabeth police, attributed
the increase to the dismantling of some auto theft task forces that
had worked with Elizabeth police and the opening of new shopping
malls like Jersey Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth and Newark, which each claim part of Newark
International Airport's car thefts since the airport sits in both
cities, flirted with the nation's highest car theft rate several
years ago, but have kept the rate down since then, Kurdyla said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Five or six years ago, it was an astronomical problem,''
Kurdyla said. ''They pretty much knocked it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Jersey City Police Sgt. Edgar Martinez said the city's growing
financial district has attracted new residents who drive expensive
vehicles but have no garages and are forced to park on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've redeployed manpower into areas where there's been an
increase,'' Martinez said. He said police expect the car theft rate
to flatten or decrease in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Newark officials blamed juveniles on the auto theft rate, saying
285 have been arrested more than once for car theft. One juvenile
was arrested 18 times for stealing cars, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Car theft has dropped 67 percent in Newark since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Paterson police didn't return telephone messages seeking comment
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Riley, director of the Rand Criminal Justice Program, a
research institute in Santa Monica, Calif., said auto theft rates
should be compared with the rates of other property crimes for a
sense of any trend.
</P>
<P>
   Absent an overall increase in property crime, an increase in
auto theft could have more to do with a new gang of car thieves
than an overall shift, Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   The murder rate rose 16.7 percent in Newark, increasing from 60
to 70 in 1999. Nine people were killed in Elizabeth in 1999, one
more than in 1998, a 16 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Newark's murders did not occur in 1999, but were included
in police statistics because they were solved last year by the
city's Cold Case Squad, police said. Four of the murders occurred
as a result of domestic violence, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Murders fell 23.5 percent in Paterson and 16.7 percent in Jersey
City in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Jersey City also reported a 10.5 percent decrease in burglaries
and a slight decrease in aggravated assault, but had increases in
all other major categories, including a 17.8 percent increase in
arson.
</P>
<P>
   Arson dropped 28.9 percent in Paterson and 14.4 percent in
Newark, but rose 4.5 percent in Elizabeth and 17.8 percent in
Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   In the largest change in any category, rapes in Elizabeth fell
44.1 percent, and burglaries were down 39.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Kurdyla said plainclothes detectives and extra officers assigned
on overtime had helped lower the burglary rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
