<HEADLINE> Gore: Bush Plans Bad for Families  </HEADLINE>
By RON FOURNIER, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Democrat Al Gore said Monday that George W.
Bush's Social Security plan would be ''bad for American families
and bad for our economy'' because retirement money would be exposed
to a fickle stock market.
</P>
<P>
   In an address to publishers and editors at The Associated Press'
annual meeting, Gore also asserted more broadly that his Republican
presidential rival would subject the nation to ''short-term
irresponsible decisions'' on many issues, including the budget,
taxes, education, the environment and guns.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore both were in New York to attend the funeral of
Roman Catholic Cardinal John O'Connor. Because of the funeral, Bush
postponed plans to unveil his Social Security initiative that would
allow Americans to invest a portion of their payroll taxes in the
stock market in hopes of yielding higher returns than the current
system.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor is to address many of the same executives by
satellite Wednesday at the convention of the Newspaper Association
of America.
</P>
<P>
   Gore wants to use interest savings from paying down the national
debt to shore up the Social Security system through 2054. By
raising alarms about Bush's intentions even before the Texas
governor described his plan, Gore was hoping to drive elderly and
baby boom voters away from the GOP campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that's bad for American families and bad for our
economy because it takes away our ability to pay down the national
debt,'' Gore said of reports that Bush would use budget surpluses
to help make the transition to his market-orientated plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''And it is associated with some risk because ideas that look
very beguiling when the markets are great may not look so great if
the market turns,'' the vice president said. ''I'm not saying the
market is overvalued. I don't know; there are a lot of people who
say that. I don't happen to buy into that, but I don't know. Nobody
knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett replied, ''What history has shown is
the market, over a period of time, has had a rate of return far
greater than the Social Security trust fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has long urged regular debates with Bush, called
Monday for a debate solely on the Social Security issue as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett, in response, noted that Democratic senators, Daniel
Patrick Moynihan of New York and Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, both
support investment of so-called personal savings accounts for
Social Security. ''It seems Al Gore needs first to debate members
of his own party,'' Bartlett said.
</P>
<P>
   While more Americans than ever are investing in the stock
market, and could be open to Bush's privatization plans, Gore's
political advisers believe the up-and-down nature of the market is
fueling anxiety among voters.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spoke for about 30 minutes and took a handful of questions.
In answer to one, he said he supported the continuing review of
regulations restricting cross-ownership among newspapers and TV and
radio stations in the same area.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also said the impact of estate taxes needs to
be examined.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a former newspaper reporter who followed his father into
politics, said Bush's $460 billion tax-cut plan would drive America
deeper into debt and shake the world's confidence in the U.S.
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think we should try to have short-term irresponsible
decisions now in our national economy that would cause our country
to have to borrow heavily again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He promised to keep the country's economy growing ''instead of
going back to the politics of drift and the economic paralysis of
the Bush-Quayle years.'' Gore is increasingly linking the Texas
governor to the economic policies of his father, former President
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Gore was attending two fund-raisers for the Democratic
National Committee in New York that were expected to raise $1
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 1931 </TRAILER>
