<HEADLINE> July-Like Heat, Texas to New England  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   A spring heat wave sizzled from Texas to New England
on Monday,
stressing utilities as residents cranked up air conditioners for a
second and -- in some spots -- third day.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The afternoon high in New York City's Central Park was 91
degrees, tying a record set in 1936. The American Red Cross handed
out bottles of water, giving out about 15,000 on Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Power companies in the mid-Atlantic region urged customers to
conserve electricity as temperatures peaked above 90, well over
usual spring readings in the 70s, the National Weather Service
said.
</P>
<P>
   PJM, which coordinates the transmission of power for
mid-Atlantic utilities, asked members to urge customers to cut back
on usage, including raising the setting on air conditioners or
turning them off because of heavy demand.
</P>
<P>
   The unseasonable heat came at a time when some generating units
were down for scheduled maintenance to get ready for the summer,
said PJM spokeswoman Melissa Josef.
</P>
<P>
   Potomac Electric Power Co. forecast a peak demand Monday of
5,200 megawatts, compared with the usual 3,000 megawatts for this
time of year, spokesman Robert Dobkin said. To reduce demand, Pepco
activated its program that cycles on and off the air conditioners
of customers who volunteered for the program, in exchange for
breaks on their bills.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Gas and Electric Co. activated a similar energy
management program for 300,000 customers.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in many areas issued heat stroke and air quality
warnings, with few problems reported.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures in Texas first rose on Friday and reached afternoon
highs Monday of 100 in Abilene, and 99 in Mineral Wells, Wink and
San Angelo. Fort Stockton reached 98 and Midland hit 96. Monday's
readings broke no records, but that wasn't the story over the
weekend. Records were broken Saturday and Sunday in Abilene, where
the high reached 106.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would even like to go fishing, but it is too cotton pickin'
hot for that,'' said 77-year-old Ben Parker in Abilene. ''I've been
here nearly all my life ... and I don't ever recall it being like
this in May.''
</P>
<P>
   Relief from the heat was expected as soon as Tuesday. In Texas,
the reprieve could be a short one since temperatures were expected
to climb again Thursday, the weather service said.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be soon enough for the animals at the Cape May Country
Park &AMP; Zoo on the southern New Jersey coast. Zookeepers scurried
from enclosure to enclosure helping out their charges in 90-degree
heat.
</P>
<P>
   The goats hid under a wooden walkway, cowering from the midday
sun. Tosh, a 350-pound Bengal tiger, lolled around in the shade,
pausing only for an occasional dip in his pool.
</P>
<P>
   ''They definitely don't like the heat, especially happening this
early in the season,'' said zookeeper Sheri Hickok. ''Most of these
animals, you've got to give them a little help. ... The panda bears
hate the heat. They don't like being hosed or misted, either, so we
put ice blocks in their cages so they can rub up against them.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Atlantic City International Airport, a 90-degree high
tied a 36-year-old record for the date, the weather service said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 1931 </TRAILER>
