<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian-American WWII Heroes Honored  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, is among about
20 Asian-American heroes of World War II who will receive the
United States' highest military honor next month, the White House
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Inouye led a platoon of the Japanese-American 442nd Regimental
Combat Team, which broke through German defenses in 1945 to help
end the Italian campaign. In two years of fighting, the
all-volunteer combat team and the similarly all Japanese-Amercian
volunteers 100th Infantry Battalion became the most decorated units
in U.S. military history.
</P>
<P>
   Inouye received the Distinguished Service Cross for throwing
grenades into three enemy machine gun nests in Italy. He lost his
right arm in combat, spent two years in Army hospitals and was
discharged a captain.
</P>
<P>
   He and the others to be recognized will receive Medals of Honor
at a White House ceremony June 21.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Akaka, D-Hawaii, sponsored legislation in 1996 that
ordered a study to identify Asian-Americans and Pacific Islanders
who had received the Distinguished Service Cross and recommend
those who might deserve the Medal of Honor, Akaka spokesman Paul
Cardus said.
</P>
<P>
   He said 104 names were submitted to the Army decorations board.
About 20 servicemen were recommended for upgrades, and those names
were forwarded to the secretary of the Army and then the secretary
of defense. The list was sent to the White House in December.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Inouye, 442nd exploits:
http://www.thehistorynet.com/WorldWarII/articles/07965--text.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
