<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Midwesterners Clean Up After Floods  </HEADLINE>
By JIM SALTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNION, Mo. (AP) -- This is what Ed Grammer found when he returned
to his mobile home Monday: a tree trunk through one window, a
barrel stuck in another, and his brand-new sofa, dripping wet and
dangling from a hole where a wall used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm living with my parents now. I really don't know what's
going to happen,'' Grammer said. The sleeveless shirt, shorts and
mud-caked tennis shoes he wore were the only clothes he had.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't even have time to grab my wallet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen inches of rain fell in about six hours Saturday night
and Sunday morning in Union. Two people died in Union, both
motorists who got caught on flooded roads. At least a dozen others
were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Flat Creek, normally little more than a trickle, came to life in
a wall of water that washed away a mobile home park along its
banks. In the flood's aftermath, Grammer's home and about two dozen
other trailers were strewn about like soda cans on a littered lot.
All appeared to be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Flash floods and rising rivers also caused damage in nearby
Washington, St. Clair, Cedar Hill. Damage in the region, mostly in
Franklin and Jefferson counties, was estimated at tens of millions
of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The National Guard was called in to help sort through the mess.
Gov. Mel Carnahan declared a flood emergency, freeing up state
money to help local governments.
</P>
<P>
   ''This destruction is as bad as I've ever seen,'' Carnahan said
after touring the area. ''It looks like an earthquake. The sheer
force and power of the water is almost incomprehensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Forecasts call for potentially heavy rain through Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this rain picks up again we're going to be in big trouble
because these rivers and creeks are full,'' said Tom Jensen, who
was helping to run the American Red Cross shelter set up at Union
City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, cleanup continued in northeastern Oklahoma after more
than 400 homes were affected by flooding over the weekend. One
woman was killed in south Tulsa when her car was trapped in rushing
water Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Gov. Frank Keating declared seven counties disaster
areas, qualifying them for federal assistance if it's offered.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the rivers that eventually flow into the Mississippi
-- the Bourbeuse, the Big, the Meramec -- were expected to crest up
to 10 feet above flood stage by Tuesday. Additional rain could push
them even higher. The Meramec was already flooding ball fields,
farmland and a few businesses and homes in Missouri's St. Louis
County town of Valley Park.
</P>
<P>
   Schools were closed in Union and Washington. About 1,000 people
who work at plants in Washington's industrial park took Monday off
while repairs were made to flood-damaged buildings.
</P>
<P>
   No place was hit harder than Union. About 200 of the town's
6,000 residents were left homeless. Only 10 spent the night in the
Red Cross shelter. Mayor Glenn Van Leer said most stayed with
family or friends.
</P>
<P>
   In a trailer next to Grammer's, two women were unable to get out
before the water tore the building from its concrete pad. They
clung to a tree for five hours, water eventually reaching just
below their necks, before they were rescued.
</P>
<P>
   Union residents credited police and firefighters with saving
dozens of lives. At the height of the storm shortly after midnight
Sunday, rescuers began rousting endangered people from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor of Grammer's, Don Vest, had seen enough. Vest, 67,
lived on slightly higher ground so the inside of his trailer was
not badly damaged. Still, he was loading up a pickup truck with his
belongings.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm moving out,'' Vest said. ''I never would have believed
this until I saw it. And I don't want to ever see it again. I was
scared to death.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 1939 </TRAILER>
