<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Little differences between four Republican Senate hopefuls indebate  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- From gun control to health insurance to
trade with China, the four Republicans were pretty much in
agreement. The only thing they disagreed on was who should be New
Jersey's newest U.S. Senator.
</P>
<P>
   The four candidates met in their first debate Monday in a forum
that allowed little back-and-forth between them.
</P>
<P>
   What brief invective there was in the hour-long exchange was
reserved for Democratic targets: Jim Florio's tax increase and Jon
Corzine's $300 million bankroll. The candidates met in the studios
of New Jersey Network and answered reporters' questions. The debate
was sponsored by NJN and The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, state Sen. William L. Gormley, R-Atlantic, said
he was the one who led the Republican charge against Florio when
the former governor raised the state sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   ''I voted against every one of Jim Florio's tax hikes,'' said
Gormley, who then boasted that he and other Republican state
leaders ''cut taxes 37 times.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're the party that took on Jim Florio. We cut his taxes. We
balanced his budgets,'' Gormley said.
</P>
<P>
   Essex County Executive Jim Treffinger said he knows ''2.8
billion reasons'' not to vote for Florio, another reference to the
tax increase that helped limit him to one term as governor.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Bob Franks, R-Union, cited his experience with
''fiscal discipline'' in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm the only candidate in this race who took on the
tax-and-spend liberals in Washington,'' Franks said.
</P>
<P>
   And even renegade Republican Murray Sabrin, a Ramapo College
professor, denounced Florio's tax increases. Sabrin then went on to
denounce all tax increases and said if elected he would support
''major tax cuts,'' the elimination of the capital gains tax, the
inheritance tax as well as the federal Department of Energy and the
department of Housing and Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   However conservative he sounded there, Sabrin was right in line
with the other three on some issues, including health care.
</P>
<P>
   All candidates said they favored some form of medical savings
account and tax breaks to help people shoulder the cost of medical
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ''More mandates from Washington, D.C. isn't the answer,'' said
Franks, who proposed ''incentives'' for small business.
</P>
<P>
   Treffinger also backed tax breaks for medical insurance
payments, saying it would ''give every family, every individual the
freedom and the opportunity to get tax credits.''
</P>
<P>
   On gun control, Gormley offered his record ''of standing up to
the NRA'' in a state vote to ban assault weapons. He said he favors
monitoring of sales at gun shows and wants more money to research
''smart guns.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to see tough penalties and I want to see the penalties
on the books enforced,'' Gormley said.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, too, wanted background checks at guns shows and a ban on
high-capacity ammunition clips. Treffinger said he wants penalties
for ''crimes with a handgun to go up appreciably.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabrin, on the other hand, opposes gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, Gormley and Treffinger also favored campaign finance
reforms, saying the federal government needs to do more than ban
soft money donations.
</P>
<P>
   Treffinger said he would ''abolish all PACs once and for all,''
while Gormley promised ''full disclosure, we need an end to soft
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Sabrin opposed, saying campaign limits violate individuals
rights to free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Florio and Corzine are scheduled to meet in a debate again
sponsored by New Jersey Network and the New York Times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-08-00 1941 </TRAILER>
