<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civil Servant Gives Smithsonian $2M  </HEADLINE>
By REBECCA SINDERBRAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A civil servant has donated $2 million to the
Smithsonian Institution's National Portrait Gallery, the largest
single donation in the gallery's history, Smithsonian officials
announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The donation from Paul Peck, a computer systems manager at the
U.S. Customs Service, is to finance a multimedia program at the
National Portrait Gallery to focus on the American presidency as an
adjunct to the gallery's Hall of Presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every time I walk through the Hall of Presidents, I feel
shivers,'' said Peck, who built his fortune through an off-duty
consulting sideline on information technology, real estate and
financial planning.
</P>
<P>
   Peck's gift will support the maintenance and improvements at the
gallery and its collections and sponsor activities ranging from
lectures, dramas and musicals to radio, television and Internet
programs about the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In honor of his gift, the National Portrait Gallery will name a
space after Peck when it reopens after renovations in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Peck began giving away his money in 1992 with the foundation of
a D.C.-area scholarship program and establishment of a humanities
institute at Montgomery College in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ''With a little luck,'' said Peck, ''when I die, I will have
given everything away.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Portrait Gallery also announced Monday that it is
sending on loan about 1,000 works to museums and other institutions
across the United States, Europe and Japan while its home, the Old
Patent Office Building, is closed for renovation.
</P>
<P>
   In other Smithsonian news, former Washington Post Co. president
Alan Spoon was named a member of the Smithsonian's board of
regents. Spoon, 48, is currently a partner with Polaris Venture
Partners.
</P>
<P>
   The regents also reappointed Manuel Ibanez, a biochemist and
professor at Texas A&AMP;M University in Kingsville, Texas, to the
board.
</P>
<P>
   Both men will serve six year terms.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: National Portrait Gallery: http://www.npg.si.edu/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 2004 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000508.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rules for Jersey shore development still in dispute  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Rules that are supposed to curb development
at the Jersey shore are in dispute -- again.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly Policy and Regulatory Oversight committee narrowly
approved a resolution Monday that says the rules carrying out the
Coastal Area Facility Review Act (CAFRA) violate the intent of the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Those rules, which were adopted by the state Department of
Environmental Protection in February, took six years and several
trips to court to be put in place.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody likes them.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say the rules don't go far enough and will
actually prompt more development at the shore. Shore-area lawmakers
say they go too far by outlawing any development in beach towns.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's happened here is that the rules and regulations that
are now in force severely restrict future development in the
coastal regions,'' said Assemblyman Ken LeFevre, R-Atlantic, a
resolution sponsor. ''They're trying to restrict development to the
point where there is going to be no development, and I don't think
that that was the intent of the Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists say the rules allow too much development.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our position is that, indeed, the regulations need to be a
great deal stronger,'' said Dery Bennett, executive director of the
American Littoral Society, a shore protection group.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said lawmakers intended for the state to force shore
towns to abide by the state master plan, which is supposed to guide
development in all towns. The rules fall short of doing that,
Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution still has to pass both legislative houses. If
that happens, then Department of Environmental Protection
Commissioner Bob Shinn would have 30 days to review the rules and
make changes. If he fails to do that, the Legislature can pass
another resolution that declares them void.
</P>
<P>
   The governor does not have to sign off on the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The CAFRA rules were supposed to be adopted in 1994. The process
stalled as developers and environmental groups tangled over what
should be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists in 1998 charged in court that the state was
dragging its feet while developers were gobbling up sensitive shore
land. A state Superior Court judge set a timetable for the state to
act, and officials pledged to have rules in place.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say the rules make it easier for developers to
build in targeted areas that are already developed -- and much more
difficult for them to build in undeveloped, environmentally
sensitive areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
