<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six die when air conditioner recycles carbon monoxide  </HEADLINE>
AP Photo pursuing
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSLYN HEIGHTS, N.Y. (AP) -- A Long Island doctor, annoyed by
buzzing from a carbon monoxide detector for no apparent reason,
disabled the device. Later he returned from work to find six
people, including a 2-year-old daughter, dead inside his home,
killed by carbon monoxide sucked in by an air conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said Dr. Andrei Kranz was sitting on his lawn crying
at 9:45 a.m. Sunday, after returning home from an overnight
hospital shift to find his young daughter, his parents, two family
friends and a baby sitter dead.
</P>
<P>
   Kranz had carried the body of his daughter out of the house in a
vain attempt to revive her, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was in shock,'' said neighbor Debbi Annunziata. ''He was
hysterical. He was crying and making noises.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife and 17-year-old step-daughter were visiting relatives
in Romania.
</P>
<P>
   Kranz told police he had disconnected the carbon-monoxide alarm
because it buzzed repeatedly and he thought it was malfunctioning.
</P>
<P>
   Police said both the air conditioner and home's furnace were on.
One of the air conditioner's intake vents was closed and another
was clogged with leaves, meaning it could draw air only from the
room it shared with the natural-gas furnace, causing it to recycle
carbon monoxide, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were pronounced dead around 10 a.m. They were
identified as Victoria Kranz, 74, and Marcus Kranz, 85, Kranz's
parents who lived in Rosyln Heights; Simina Kranz, 2, Kranz's
daughter; houseguests Emil Ioan Campeanu, 75, and his wife, Maria
Mihaela Campeanu, 68, and the family baby sitter, Emilia Dumtru,
58.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors and the baby sitter were from Romania.
</P>
<P>
   Kranz, a radiology resident at Nassau County Medical Center, was
being treated at his hospital's intensive care for exposure to
carbon monoxide. He was in stable condition early Monday afternoon
and was expected to be released later in the day, a hospital
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Police were investigating. Foul play had been ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   ''This could have all been so easily avoided,'' neighbor Donna
Bernstein said after learning that the detector had been turned
off.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled the death of tennis star Vitas Gerulaitis, killed
when his Long Island cottage was filled with carbon monoxide from a
swimming pool heater in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
