<HEADLINE> Monday's Baseball Notes and Quotes  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Royals-Tigers
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: Mac Suzuki will return to the Royals' rotation
Tuesday. The 6-foot-3, 205-pounder from Kobe, Japan, began the
season in the rotation but was demoted to the bullpen after
compiling a 5.40 ERA, allowing eight earned runs in 13 1-3 innings.
In his last three appearances, all in relief, he allowed two earned
runs in 11 1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: Damion Easley, who has been playing with a chipped bone
in his right wrist, was on the bench Monday night for the opening
of a three-game series with Kansas City and likely headed for the
disabled list. ''It's to the point where it's hard to deal with,''
Easley said. ''Every time I swing, I have to step out and gather
myself, but the pain never goes away completely.'' Easley said he
likely will be placed on the 15-day DL, perhaps on Tuesday.
Orioles-Blue Jays:
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: The Orioles held a team meeting before the game. ...
Baltimore entered having lost 10 straight games to Toronto, and 11
in a row at SkyDome. ... 2B Delino DeShields refuses to speak to
the media. Albert Belle also doesn't talk to the press.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: Jose Cruz Jr. was the American League player of the
week. Cruz hit .387 with five home runs and nine RBIs. ... Andy
Thompson's wife Christine gave birth to a girl on Sunday. Thompson,
who made his major league debut last week, left the team to be with
his wife in Wisconsin. ... The Blue Jays are on pace to hit 207
home runs at SkyDome this season. The club record at home is 112 in
1998.
Devil Rays-Yankees:
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: Closer Roberto Hernandez will likely miss 2-3 days
with a bruised right elbow after getting hit in his pitching arm by
a line drive from Nomar Garciaparra on Sunday. ... RHP Juan Guzman
threw off the mound for the first time since going on the DL with a
sore shoulder. LHP Wilson Alvarez, who is also on the DL, threw as
well in Florida. Neither pitcher is expected back until early June.
When they do return, manager Larry Rothschild will have the
opportunity to demote two starters to the bullpen or the minors.
He'll have many choices as Tampa Bay's rotation was 6-12 with a
6.88 ERA entering the game. ''The opportunity is there. Whoever
takes advantage of it will still be here. Whoever doesn't, won't.''
... Dwight Gooden, making his first appearance as a visitor in New
York, faced the Yankees once during the 1998 ALCS for Cleveland. He
allowed three runs in 4 2-3 innings and lost 4-0 in Game 4. The
only teams Gooden hasn't faced are Arizona and the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: 2B Chuck Knoblauch took infield and batting practice
but it is uncertain when he will return from his sore left wrist.
Knoblauch has missed the last six games. ''When we have Knobby at
the top of the lineup, it really makes the other pitcher work. He's
a tough out,'' manager Joe Torre said. ... Mariano Rivera's blown
save Sunday was the first time he blew a game when ahead by at
least two runs in the ninth inning or later since Aug. 2, 1996,
against Kansas City. ''You can expect him to do his job every day,
but it's not going to happen,'' Torre said. ... The Yankees-Rangers
game that was rained out April 12 will be replayed on Aug. 21 at
12:05 p.m. EDT. ... LHP Ed Yarnall was placed on the DL at Columbus
with back soreness.
White Sox-Red Sox:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: LHP Jim Parque began his three-game suspension for his
role in an on-field brawl April 22 against Detroit. The other six
White Sox suspended already have completed serving their penalties.
Chicago was 3-6 in the first nine games after the suspensions were
announced April 27. In the nine games before that, the White Sox
were 8-1. ... The White Sox offense has quieted down since they
scored 181 runs in April (an average of 7.2 per game), breaking the
major-league record for the month of 180 set by Texas in 1998. In
their first six games in May, they had 25 runs (an average of
4.17). ... Chicago opened a tough 18-game stretch in which they
play 11 times against Boston, Cleveland and the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: Only four players walked in the previous four games
against the Red Sox. And Brian Rose started Monday's game by not
issuing any walks in the first three innings. ... Trot Nixon made
it 21 games of the 24 he's played in which he reached base when he
singled in the first. ... Nomar Garciaparra and Troy O'Leary are
neck-and-neck in their race to 100 career homers. They were tied at
98 after O'Leary hit his fifth homer of the season Sunday.
Garciaparra had just two homers in his first 25 games after hitting
27 in 135 games last year.
Mariners-Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: The Mariners are playing at The Ballpark in Arlington
for the first time without Ken Griffey Jr., whose .382 average
there is his best in any stadium in the major leagues. During his
11 seasons in Seattle before going to Cincinnati this spring,
Griffey hit .315 with 30 home runs and 101 RBIs in all games vs.
Texas. Only against Toronto (.317) does he have a better average.
... P Brett Tomko, acquired from the Reds in the Griffey deal, made
his 11th career start against an AL team on Monday, the first
against an AL opponent not in the Central Division.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: Despite a strained hip flexor, David Segui started at
first base for the third straight game Monday while Rafael
Palmeiro, with his strained hamstring, remained the designated
hitter. Manager Johnny Oates said Segui can play based on how he
feels since the injury really can't be aggravated any worse, but he
says he won't give Palmeiro a chance to play first base again
''until his leg is 100 percent, or as close at it's going to get.''
... OF Rusty Greer, on the disabled list since April 13, took
batting practice again Monday. Oates said he is still not sure when
Greer will return to the lineup, but said it would be at least
another week. Greer originally went on the DL for the first time in
his career due to a strained left hamstring and an ankle problem,
but then decided to have arthroscopic surgery to remove bones spurs
from his right ankle.
Indians-Twins:
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: Bench coach Grady Little, who's filling in while
manager Charlie Manuel recovers from colon surgery, said Kenny
Lofton (strained left biceps) is improving: ''He's still getting
himself ready. All of his physical activities have been very
positive and he's got a big smile on his face. So, a lot of times,
that tells you how a kid's feeling. ... The Indians activated C
Sandy Alomar (hamstring) from the 15-day DL and designated C Bobby
Hughes for assignment. Hughes signed on April 20 but didn't appear
in a game.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: The Twins honored manager Tom Kelly before the game.
Kelly became the 46th manager in major league history to win 1,000
games with the Twins' 4-0 victory over Detroit on Sunday. Kelly is
the sixth manager to win 1,000 games with one team. The
longest-tenured coach or manager in professional sports received
donations in his name to several charities during pre-game
festivities that included congratulatory messages from several
other managers on the big screen scoreboard. Kelly was presented
with a Twins jersey No. 1,000.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Braves-Marlins:
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: First baseman Randall Simon, who batted .317 in 90
games for Atlanta last season, was released by the Marlins'
Triple-A affiliate in Calgary. ... Braves second baseman Quilvio
Veras, who left Sunday's game against Philadelphia in the fourth
inning because of a sore right wrist, was back in the lineup
Monday. ... Atlanta's pitching staff leads the National League in
ERA and has allowed the fewest homers and thrown the fewest wild
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: Florida's Ricky Bones, who will take Alex Fernandez's
turn in the rotation Thursday against Atlanta, began the week with
an 0.44 ERA in 20 1-3 innings.
Brewers-Cubs:
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: The wind was blowing out at Wrigley Field again
Monday night, and that was good news for the Brewers. Opponents
have hit 11 home runs in seven games when the wind was blowing out
so far this season. Manager Davey Lopes knows all about the Wrigley
Field wind after playing for the Cubs from 1984-86. ''Hitters love
to have the wind blowing out, pitchers hate it,'' Lopes said. ''You
don't necessarily have to have a power-hitting team to take
advantage of the wind here. You just have to get it up in the
air.'' ... With Geoff Jenkins out for a month with a broken finger,
Lopes plans to rotate Lyle Mouton and James Mouton in left field.
Lyle was in left Monday night. ''Depending on the pitcher,
depending on who's the one who gets hot,'' Lopes said. ''If one guy
gets hot, he'll play.'' ... Sammy Sosa has hit 18 home runs off
Milwaukee pitchers in the last two seasons, including No's. 60 and
61 in 1998. ''Sammy's going to get his no matter what,'' Lopes
said. ''It's like trying to shut down Michael Jordan -- you try to
minimize the damage.''
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: The Cubs released RHP Bobby Ayala from his minor league
contract and signed RHP Tim Worrell to a contract with the Triple-A
Iowa Cubs. Worrell was released by the Baltimore Orioles on May 1
after going 2-2 with a 7.36 ERA in five relief appearances. ''The
more he pitched, from the reports I got, his velocity varied up and
down. Then his numbers started to go up slightly,'' manager Don
Baylor said. ''Worrell we tried to sign right before spring
training.'' ... Eric Young was supposed to get Monday night off,
but he's playing too well. He's got a five-game hitting streak,
hitting .476 with three doubles, two homers and four RBIs during
the stretch. ''I just can't afford to take him out,'' Baylor said.
''He's a catalyst for us at the top of the lineup, he's exciting to
watch. Plus, he makes our offense go.'' So, when will Young get a
day off? ''He'll have to come to me, because I'm not going to
him,'' Baylor said, laughing. ... With a four-game losing streak
and the second-worst record in the NL, times are tough for the
Cubs. Baylor meets with his coaches every day trying to find ways
to give the team a spark. But the veteran players, who endured last
year's 67-95 record, might be taking it the hardest. ''Until we get
back to .500, I believe there's a sense of urgency for the guys
that were here last year,'' Baylor said. ''It's like, 'Oh, no, not
again. Here we go falling into this black hole again.' I'd like to
start climbing back and try to get closer to .500. Now that we have
(Ismael) Valdes and (Kerry) Wood back in the starting rotation, we
have to get better with those two guys. There's no doubt about
it.''
Rockies-Astros:
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: Despite Sunday's rainout in San Francisco, the one
thing the Rockies didn't want to do was disrupt Pedro Astacio's
spot in the rotation. He was on the mound to start Monday night
against the Astros. ''What we do know is we want to keep Pedro on
his turn,'' manager Buddy Bell said. ''He's the No. 1 guy. We want
to get him out there as much as possible.'' Scott Karl, scheduled
to start on Sunday, will now start Tuesday against the Astros.
''That's why you number your starters,'' Karl said. ''You want the
No. 1 guy to stay on course as much as possible. There's nothing
you can do about the schedule, except adjust.'' ... CF Tom Goodwin
returned to the lineup after missing two games with a strained leg
muscle.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: Perennial leadoff hitter Craig Biggio and No. 2 hitter
Roger Cedeno were flip-flopped in Monday night's lineup by Astros
manager Larry Dierker. ''If Cedeno gets on he can steal at any
juncture,'' Dierker said. ''Biggio has to pick his spots. Cedeno
could steal more bases if he leads off.'' Cedeno entered the game,
leading the NL with 10 stolen bases. ... The Astros skipped batting
practice Monday after completing a 5-5 road trip for a 9-9 season
record on the road. They entered Monday's game with a 3-9 record at
Enron Field.
</P>
</TEXT>
