<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Boy Scout who told the world about AIDS dies in crash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- Henry J. Nicols, an AIDS activist and
Boy Scout who gained the world's attention after announcing that he
was HIV postive, died Monday from injuries received in a car crash.
He was 26.
</P>
<P>
   Nicols was hospitalized in critical condition after his car
struck a tree last month on county Route 31 in Springfield, Otsego
County Sheriff's Investigator Richard Devlin Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Devlin, Nicols was traveling north in his Pontiac
Fiero when he drove onto the right-hand shoulder, briefly returned
to his lane and then crossed the opposite lane and hit a tree.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Nicols launched an Eagle Scout project that grew into a
worldwide education campaign to dispel ignorance and stereotypes
surrounding AIDS. Nicols, a hemophiliac, contracted the HIV virus
during a blood transfusion in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our grief at Henry's untimely death is lessened by the
knowledge that during his life he touched the hearts of millions,''
said the Nichols family in a statement released by Bassett Health
Care.
</P>
<P>
   His activism took him to Ireland and Japan and landed him an
audience with Presidents Bush and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He testified before a congressional committee studying whether
AIDS testing for health-care workers should be mandatory and was
the subject of an award-winning documentary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
