<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Perot May Not Address Reform Party  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE KELLMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Reform Party founder Ross Perot is not
expected to address the party's August convention, where former
Republican Pat Buchanan is likely to become the third party's
nominee for president, officials close to the event said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has a very tight travel schedule for business this summer
and no definite plans have been made one way or the other with
respect to appearing at the convention,'' Perot's top lieutenant,
Russell Verney, said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   But senior party officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said Perot has indicated he will not attend the convention or make
a statement in support of the nominee, which would be a first since
he founded the party in 1992. His absence could further demoralize
a party riven by fierce infighting for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's campaign manager and sister, Bay, said they would
welcome Perot at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has decided throghout this process to remain neutral and we
respect that,'' she said. ''If he chooses to attend the convention
and speak we will be thrilled, and if he chooses not to, we'll
respect that decision too.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan has never figured the Texas billionaire into his plans
for capturing the presidential nomination, anyway. For his part,
Perot never warmed to the conservative commentator. Shortly after
Buchanan bolted the GOP last year, Perot rejected his proposal for
a telephone conversation but sent word that he welcomed him into
the party like anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Buchanan has clashed with Perot supporters in
several states over everything from the way he is pursuing delegate
votes to his positions on social issues.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday in Perot's home state, Buchanan
referred to it as ''my convention'' even as he acknowledged that
his presence in the party has inspired unprecedented upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not want to be at my convention, the Reform Party
convention, and get nominated and then have some (states) say,
'Rather than put him on our ballot, we are going to disaffiliate'
then you're not on the ballot,'' Buchanan said. Instead of being
blocked out of those delegations, Buchanan has acquired enough
signatures to get on the ballot in those states as an independent.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, for example, Buchanan announced Monday that he has
submitted 129,000 signatures, more than twice the number required,
to get on the ballot as an independent.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan has left a trail of outraged Perot supporters in his
pursuit of convention delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Even though his opposition to abortion and views on other social
issues clash sharply with the principles on which Perot founded the
party, Buchanan says common ground exists on trade and other
foreign policy. Both he and the party oppose free trade agreements,
for example.
</P>
<P>
   The party platform is silent on social issues like homosexuality
and abortion because it does not believe government should weigh in
on such private matters.
</P>
<P>
   Verney declined to say whether Buchanan's statements inspired
Perot to stay away from the convention. But he did issue a warning.
</P>
<P>
   ''If social issues start to become the focal point of the
campaign and the members feel that that does not represent their
goals and ambitions, you're going to get some growing problems,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   That dustup is the most recent between Buchanan and Perot's
supporters. A string of state parties have made known that they'd
rather follow the Minnesota Reform Party -- and disaffiliate from
the national organization -- rather than accept Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential problem for Buchanan is the abrupt resignation
of chairman Pat Choate, who was Perot's running mate in 1996 and
Buchanan's campaign chairman earlier this year. Citing a serious
family illness, Choate on Friday turned the chairmanship over to
vice chairman Gerry Moan, who has been neutral in the disputes
between the Buchanan and Perot camps.
</P>
<P>
   Moan, a 52-year-old Tucson, Ariz. business executive, said he
believes the party can be unified.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see the relationship between the party and the campaigns as
a partnership,'' Moan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 2046 </TRAILER>
