<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Cos. Warned of US Boycott  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- German companies who fail to fund compensation for
Nazi-era forced and slave laborers could risk having their products
boycotted in the United States, a German official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The warning by Otto Lambsdorff, Germany's chief negotiator in
talks on a settlement, was part of the growing pressure on
companies that benefited from the forced labor to quit stalling on
the planned $4.6 billion fund.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we really don't get the payments that were promised, there
will be considerable boycotts and sanctions against German
companies, particularly in the United States,'' Lambsdorff told
Berlin's InfoRadio station.
</P>
<P>
   German industry agreed last December to contribute half the
total, with the government to pay the other half. But the fund says
companies have so far contributed only $1.3 billion -- just over
half their share.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament president Wolfgang Thierse, the country's
second-highest public official, warned of a ''disgrace for
Germany'' if the compensation drive collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   And German President Johannes Rau also repeated his call on
German industry to fully participate in the compensation effort
Monday, the 55th anniversary of Germany's capitulation in World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   ''The compensation must now finally take place,'' he said in
Berlin. ''Therefore I appeal once more to German industry: Accept
your responsibility. We owe it to the victims, and that is in the
German interest.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the settlement, Germany also is trying to win U.S.
government support for shielding German firms against future claims
and lawsuits by victims.
</P>
<P>
   Lambsdorff voiced confidence that industry will ultimately find
the money and that payments to the aging survivors -- a
long-forgotten group of Nazi victims -- will start this year.
</P>
<P>
   Thierse appealed to industry to show a ''sense of morality'' and
''not calculate in a small-minded way.''
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said the compromise made on the
compensation carried great meaning for how Germany is perceived in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''This cannot run badly, it must succeed,'' he said Monday on
N24 television.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the opening of a Berlin exhibition on the history of
the city's Jews, Schroeder named the labor fund as one of the
proofs that Germans hadn't pushed aside their past.
</P>
<P>
   The fund, launched last year by major German corporations, said
Sunday it might publicly name firms that have failed to contribute
to pressure them to pay. Jewish leaders in Germany also called for
exposing the holdouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 2124 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
