<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Talks Resume To End Norway Strike  </HEADLINE>
By DOUG MELLGREN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway (AP) -- Norway's largest union and employers
negotiated late into the evening Monday in hopes of ending a
national strike before it escalates into the second biggest labor
conflict in this small nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   The resumption of formal talks broke a stalemate between the two
sides that had lasted since 84,600 workers began the strike on
Wednesday after the union rank and file had rejected a new
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Yngve Haagensen, leader of the 800,000-member Norwegian
Confederation of Trade Unions, revealed that informal talks had
been going on throughout the strike and that he had secretly met
the employer's top representatives late Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   New, formal negotiations, led by national labor mediator Reidar
Webster, began Monday afternoon after both sides said they were
looking for ways to quickly end the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators were facing a 6 a.m. Tuesday deadline, when by the
union planned to step up the strike to include more than 102,000
people. That would make it Norway's worst labor conflict since
1921, when 150,000 people walked off the job over proposed pay
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The government, and the Norwegian Confederation of Business and
Industry has been under pressure because the strike could disrupt
automobile production in Europe as supplies of Norwegian-made parts
dry up.
</P>
<P>
   Automaker Saab stopped its Swedish production lines on Monday,
and Germany's BMW was reported to have threatened to drop Norwegian
suppliers if the strike forces it to shut down its plants.
</P>
<P>
   The strike could force tens of thousands of layoffs in the
European car industry. However, some Norwegian parts makers were
planning night shifts to catch up as soon as the strike ends.
</P>
<P>
   This nation of 4.5 million people is the world's second largest
oil exporter, but the union has so far allowed the nation's 3.2
million barrel per day oil production to continue unhampered.
</P>
<P>
   The strike was called when members of the Norwegian
Confederation of Trade Unions, an umbrella group for 27 unions,
rejected a contract offer in a national vote. That offer had been
for 3.5 percent to 4 percent in pay increases and a minimum fifth
week of paid vacation, a deal the union leadership had recommended.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
