<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.African Airline Brought To Court  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- A young man who had dreams of
being a flight attendant clashed in court Monday with South
Africa's biggest airline, which rejected him as a job candidate
when blood tests showed he has the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is the first time a company has been brought to Labor
Court for allegedly discriminating against a person with HIV or
AIDS. A similar case is pending before the Constitutional Court,
the nation's highest tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   The stigma associated with the virus that has infected an
estimated 10 percent of South Africa's 40 million people is so
great that Judge Deon Basson ordered the prospective flight
attendant's identity withheld. During the trial, which began
Monday, he is being identified only as ''Mr. A.''
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen activists wearing T-shirts emblazoned ''HIV
positive'' appeared in support of Mr. A and quietly observed the
proceedings in the small wood-panelled courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   With AIDS beginning to hit South Africa's work force, the
unprecedented case sheds light on how many corporations treat
victims of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a great deal of denial and ignorance,'' said Karen
Michael, an AIDS expert and researcher at the University of Natal
in Durban.
</P>
<P>
   Some business executives look at AIDS as an answer to South
Africa's 40 percent unemployment rate and do not think it will
affect their own workers, Michael said.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1997, the plaintiff applied for a job at SAA as a
flight attendant. After he was given a battery of tests he was told
he was a good candidate. But days later, blood tests revealed he
had the human immunodeficiency virus, and he was summarily rejected
as a candidate. He was sent home with no counseling.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for SAA, Ishmael Semenya, said the airline did not
want to employ Mr. A because they believed if he was given a yellow
fever vaccine, required for most travel within Africa, it could
damage his health. Mr. A's legal team, including AIDS experts,
insisted the vaccine would not threaten his health and said he was
being discriminated against.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I was badly treated,'' the young man murmured to a
reporter during a break. ''I don't think I deserved this.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiff is seeking unspecified damages and wants an end to
SAA's policy of excluding people with HIV from being hired.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 2159 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000508.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israelis Honor Fallen Soldiers  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- With a wail of sirens, Israel slowed its usual
frenetic activity Monday and began a solemn, nationwide tribute to
nearly 20,000 soldiers killed in the nation's wars and terror
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In a uniquely Israeli contrast, Memorial Day is followed
immediately by raucous Independence Day celebrations, underlining
the link the people see between the wars and their nation's fate.
</P>
<P>
   Since Nov. 29, 1947, when the United Nations approved the
creation of the state of Israel, 19,109 people have been killed in
military service or in hostile acts, according to the Defense
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   In a close-knit country of 6 million people, that translates
into a personal sense of mourning.
</P>
<P>
   Most businesses close early for the ceremonies that run from
Monday evening to Tuesday evening, and Israelis visit cemeteries to
honor fallen friends, relatives and schoolmates.
</P>
<P>
   Air raid sirens sound twice on Memorial Day, once Monday night
and again Tuesday morning, directing Israelis to stop what they are
doing and pay tribute. Traffic comes to a halt, and drivers stand
next to their cars on streets and highways.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak and President Ezer Weizman, both
ex-generals, attended the opening ceremony at the Western Wall in
the Old City of Jerusalem, Judaism's holiest site.
</P>
<P>
   ''Again we are with you, my brothers,'' army chief Lt. Gen.
Shaul Mofaz said at the ceremony, ''and the pain that scorches like
the burn of forged iron is too hard to bear.''
</P>
<P>
   After the two-year war that followed the creation of the state,
Israeli soldiers went to battle again in 1956, 1967, 1973 and 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, a transition ceremony is to take place at the Mt.
Herzl military cemetery in Jerusalem, marking the end of Memorial
Day and the beginning of Independence Day, complete with a
fireworks display.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 2200 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000508.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Contest Plea in Desert Death  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE KOIDIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, N.M. (AP) -- A man who claimed his best friend begged
him to put him out of his misery after they got lost in the desert
without water pleaded no contest Monday to murder.
</P>
<P>
   Raffi Kodikian, 26, of Boston admitted stabbing to death his
friend, David Coughlin, last August during a camping trip in the
backcountry of Carlsbad Caverns National Park. He pleaded to
second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   ''You start understanding people in dehydrated states do some
crazy things,'' said defense attorney Gary Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian could get up to 20 years in prison at the end of a
sentencing hearing that is expected to end on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plea bargain, Kodikian preserves the right to appeal a
judge's ruling barring him from mounting a defense of temporary
insanity based on dehydration-induced dementia.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian said Coughlin, 26, of Millis, Mass., pleaded with him
to end his pain after the two got lost and ran out of water.
Kodikian said he and his friend believed Coughlin would die.
</P>
<P>
   ''David pleads with Raffi to end his life, and Raffi -- in what
most people call a mercy killing -- does as his best friend
wishes,'' Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   Park workers rescued Kodikian about six hours after his friend
died.
</P>
<P>
   State investigators said that Coughlin had moderate to severe
deydration but that his body fluids were not at a lethal level when
he was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dennis Klein, who performed an autopsy on Coughlin, said
Coughlin had three cuts on his right wrist that could have been the
result of a suicide attempt. While Coughlin was dehydrated, Klein
said, the cause of death was two stab wounds to the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Hopkins, who treated Kodikian at Carlsbad Medical
Center the day he was found, testified that Kodikian was
dehydrated, had a fever of 102 and had an extremely elevated sodium
level and pulse rate. Kodikian was treated and released in three
hours, Hopkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Les Williams said that Kodikian had agreed to kill
himself as part of a pact they made after running out of water and
getting lost.
</P>
<P>
   Kodikian ''did have marks on his wrist, across his wrist, but
they were not deep,'' and he said his knife was too dull, Williams
said. He was dehydrated, ''but not to the point that he didn't know
what he was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said the two men didn't take enough water and were
totally unprepared for the possibility that their one-day trip
could turn into four.
</P>
<P>
   ''The boys were the best of friends, never meant any harm to
anybody, including themselves,'' he said. ''They get lost, have no
water for three days, are severely dehydrated, both in extreme
agony, and both attempt suicide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 2200 </TRAILER>
