<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earthquake Series Rattles Italy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP)-- A series of moderate-intensity earthquakes jarred
central Italy on Monday, sending some people running into the
streets but causing no reported damage or injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest of the quakes had a preliminary magnitude of 4.4,
Italy's National Geophysics Institute said.
</P>
<P>
   The epicenter was near the small towns of Faeza and Forli, 285
miles northeast of Rome.
</P>
<P>
   The 4.4 jolt was the strongest of more than 200 to hit the area
since April 20, the geophysics institute said.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual amount of seismic activity is wearing on the nerves
of some residents. Although authorities checked buildings and found
no damage, an unknown number of residents left their homes after
the mid-afternoon quake and declined to go back -- preferring to
remain out in the open.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
