<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, May 8, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McCain Is About To Endorse Bush
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Despite misgivings about George B. Bush's agenda, failed
Republican presidential candidate John McCain has decided to endorse Bush at
their summit tomorrow, advisers close to McCain said today. The Arizona senator
is said to have determined after a series of events -- including a weekend
telephone conversation with the presumptive GOP nominee -- that he didn't want
to wait any longer.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
O'Connor's Funeral Is Held
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Differences seemed to disappear as politicians many stripes
and faiths sat in St. Patrick's Cathedral for the funeral of Cardinal John
O'Connor, who was buried today beneath the church's altar that was his pulpit
for 16 years. O'Connor, 80, died Wednesday of a brain tumor. Attending the
funeral were President Clinton, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton; ex-President
George Bush; presidential candidates Al Gore and George W. Bush; Gov. George
Pataki, and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fire Burns Near Los Alamos
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) -- A forest fire spread today, virtually shutting down
the Los Alamos national nuclear lab. Its explosive materials are secured in
nonflammable concrete and metal buildings surrounded by earthen berms about a
half-mile from the fire, lab spokesman John Gustafson said. The closest
radioactive materials were about three miles from the fire, spokesman Kevin
Roark said. Only essential personnel reported for work at the lab, Department of
Energy officials said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Food Makers Unveil Caloric Products
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- With Americans worrying less about fat and calories these
days, food makers are rolling out a raft of fat-laden, calorie-packed new
products at the supermarket industry's annual trade show. Sara Lee Corp.'s new
Calzone Creations microwavable sandwiches has as much as 12 grams of
artery-clogging saturated fat, 60 percent of the recommended daily intake for an
average person. Industry research indicates consumer concern about fat has been
falling in recent years. Just 46 percent of consumers say they are worried about
the fat content, down from 60 percent in 1996, according to a poll sponsored by
the Food Marketing Institute.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Love Bug Suspect Is Arrested
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- Philippine police and FBI agents raided an
apartment in Manila on Monday and arrested a bank employee who along with his
girlfriend is suspected of links to the ''ILOVEYOU'' virus that hit computer
networks around the world. But relatives of the man, Reomel Ramones, said they
believe the real culprit may be a third person who lived in the apartment -- the
girlfriend's unemployed sister, who recently graduated from a computer school
that a U.S. security firm has linked to the ''Love Bug'' virus.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
4 Killed at Sierra Leone Rally
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- A rally in Sierra Leone's capital on Monday
turned into a shooting spree, with rebel soldiers gunning down at least four
protesters. The United Nations ordered the evacuation of most of its civilian
staff, and U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said he was ''extremely concerned
about the rapidly deteriorating situation.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Priest May Not Testify Vs. Attacker
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIDDLETOWN, Ohio (AP) -- A Roman Catholic priest who was stabbed after
hearing a confession has identified his attacker but is reluctant to testify
against him. The Rev. Charles Mentrup, 41, was stabbed in the abdomen at his
home Friday after hearing the confession. He was in good condition today at
Middletown Regional Hospital. Mentrip identified the attacker, leading to an
arrest warrant, but is reluctant to help with the prosecution because of the
seal of secrecy involving confession. Marcus A. Finefrock, 25, turned himself in
and pleaded innocent Monday to one charge of felonious assault. He faces up to
eight years in prison if convicted.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall; Dollar Up Vs Yen
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell early Tuesday following a retreat in
technology shares on Wall Street. The Nikkei shed 224.49 points, to 17,975.47 in
early trading. In New York, the Nasdaq was down 147.44 at 3,669.38 and the Dow
Jones industrial average ended up 25.77 at 10,603.63.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Devils 3, Maple Leafs 0
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Petr Sykora scored 18 seconds after the opening
faceoff and Jason Arnott got a goal 25 seconds into the second period as the New
Jersey Devils beat Toronto 3-0 tonight to win the best-of-seven second-round NHL
playoff series in six games. New Jersey will play the winner of the
Philadelphia-Pittsburgh series which Philadelphia leads 3-2 with Game 6 in
Pittsburgh tomorrow night.
</P>
