<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ad Actors Announce Interim Deal  </HEADLINE>
By LYNN ELBER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- More than 300 commercial producers, including
a media consulting firm for Al Gore's campaign, have signed interim
agreements with striking actors' unions, the unions said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Screen Actors Guild and the American Federation of
Television and Radio Artists, which represent about 135,000 actors,
went on strike May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hattaway, a spokesman for the Democratic presidential
contender, said their campaign consultant had agreed to the wages
and working conditions the unions are seeking from advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ''They obviously want to stand with the union workers here,''
Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
   The unions said that a media firm working for Republican
candidate George W. Bush also signed an agreement, but the Bush
campaign said it could not confirm that Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a three-week 1988 strike, about 500 commercial producers
accepted interim agreements, compared with the 300 who signed this
time in one week, SAG spokesman Greg Krizman said.
</P>
<P>
   Krizman declined to estimate the total number of commercial
producers. A major trade group, the American Association of
Advertising Agencies, includes about 750 members.
</P>
<P>
   Ira Shepard, a Washington lawyer negotiating for the
advertisers, suggested that only smaller, ''peripheral'' ad
agencies agreed to deal with the unions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ad industry is united and firmly behind its decision to
stand by its last and best offer,'' Shepard said. ''There have been
no defections from any major advertiser or major ad agency in
regard to the interim agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Political consultants, he added, ''don't have the same economic
interest that commercial advertisers do.''
</P>
<P>
   The pay structure for commercials is at issue in the strike.
Actors get a minimum of about $478 for a day's work and also get
''pay-per-play'' residuals of roughly $50 to $120 each time a spot
airs on network television.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to cable TV commercials, performers receive only a
flat fee of $1,000 or less for each 13-week, unlimited run. With
two-thirds of all TV ads now being made for cable, actors are
demanding that pay-per-play be extended to cable.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers want to extend the flat fee from cable to the
networks.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
