<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> KLLM Board Gets Two Buyout Bids  </HEADLINE>
By MATT MOORE, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Two offers to buy KLLM Transport Services
Inc. are before a special company panel, including one from a
tandem that includes WorldCom chief Bernie Ebbers.
</P>
<P>
   Ebbers and KLLM chairman, president and CEO Jack Liles III are
sparring with Robert Low, owner of a privately held trucking firm
in Missouri, for ownership of the Richland-based trucking company.
</P>
<P>
   Low owns New Prime Inc., a Springfield, Mo.-based trucking
company.
</P>
<P>
   KLLM's board of directors formed a subcommittee, including board
member Leland Speed, who will chair the panel, to consider both
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Other committee members include Walter Neely, a finance
professor at Millsaps College in Jackson, and David Metzler, a
trucking company executive from Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Broughton, a transportation analyst with A.G. Edwards &AMP;
Sons Inc. in St. Louis, said the subcommittee's job is to ensure
KLLM's shareholders get the maximum amount of money for their
shares.
</P>
<P>
   ''They'll look at it and figure who is offering the best value
to shareholders and that process may end up including a process by
which they hold an informal auction between the two bidders,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Liles and Ebbers had offered on April 20 to pay $8.25 per share,
or $35 million, for KLLM's 4.25 million outstanding shares. Low,
who holds a 13.7-percent stake in the company, had offered $7.75
per share, or $32.9 million, on April 12.
</P>
<P>
   Broughton said the book value for KLLM is approximately $12.38
per share, higher than the initial offers by Low and Liles-Ebbers.
</P>
<P>
   The amounts may have changed in the offers made to the
subcommittee, which is keeping the bid amounts secret because the
bidding is ''an ongoing process.''
</P>
<P>
   Liles and Low have both signed confidentiality agreements
barring them from discussing their bids. Ebbers has not discussed
his participation in the process.
</P>
<P>
   In trading Monday on the Nasdaq, shares of KLLM were unchanged
from Friday at $8.31\.
</P>
<P>
   KLLM has more than 2,000 refrigerated trailers that haul food,
medicine and cosmetics across North America. The company employs
nearly 2,000 workers and had 1999 sales of $234.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   New Prime has more than 3,100 refrigerated, flatbed and tanker
trailers. It employs nearly 3,350 workers.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.kllm.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.newprime.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 2222 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000508.0215 </DOCNO>
