<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, May 8, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McCain Is About To Endorse Bush
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- John McCain has decided to endorse George W. Bush, his
ex-Republican presidential rival at their summit tomorrow, despite the senator's
misgivings about the Bush's agenda, advisers close to McCain said. The Arizona
senator is said to have determined after a series of events -- including a
weekend telephone conversation with the presumptive GOP nominee -- that he
didn't want to wait any longer.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fire Burns Near Los Alamos
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) -- A fire set to clear underbrush at a national
monument that lost control forced the closure of the Los Alamos National
Laboratory today and sent at least 500 people from their homes. A separate fire
200 miles southeast near Ruidoso burned 4,500 acres and forced the evacuation of
at least 200 homes. High wind caused problems with both fires, and Gov. Gary
Johnson declared a state of emergency. ''we're going to stay as long as we
can,'' said former Rep. Bill Redmond, R-N.M., a Senate candidate whose home was
among 1,000 placed on evacuation alert in Los Alamos.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Love Bug Suspect Is Arrested
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- Accompanied by FBI agents, Philippine police
raided an apartment in Manila on Monday and arrested a bank employee who along
with his girlfriend is suspected of links to the ''ILOVEYOU'' virus that has
overwhelmed computer networks around the world. But relatives of the man, Reomel
Ramones, said they believe the real culprit may be a third person who lived in
the apartment -- the girlfriend's unemployed sister, who recently graduated from
a computer school that a U.S. security firm has linked to the ''Love Bug''
virus.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
O'Connor's Funeral Is Held
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Differences seemed to disappear as politicians of many
stripes and faiths sat in St. Patrick's Cathedral for the funeral of Cardinal
John O'Connor, who was buried today beneath the church's altar that was his
pulpit for 16 years. O'Connor, 80, died Wednesday of a brain tumor. Attending
the funeral were President Clinton, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton;
ex-President George Bush; presidential candidates Al Gore and George W. Bush;
Gov. George Pataki, and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Philly Adopts All-Uniform Rule
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Philadelphia adopted a policy tonight requiring all
students to wear uniforms in 256 public schools, the first big-city district to
do so. Most parents who spoke opposed uniforms for Philadelphia's 217,000
public-school students. The measure, which goes into effect immediately, does
not call for a single, Roman Catholic-school-style uniform; instead, schools
could decide individually how students should dress.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Food Makers Unveil Caloric Products
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- With Americans worrying less about fat and calories these
days, food makers are rolling out a raft of fat-laden, calorie-packed new
products at the supermarket industry's annual trade show. Sara Lee Corp.'s new
Calzone Creations microwavable sandwiches has as much as 12 grams of
artery-clogging saturated fat, 60 percent of the recommended daily intake for an
average person. Industry research indicates consumer concern about fat has been
falling in recent years. Just 46 percent of consumers say they are worried about
the fat content, down from 60 percent in 1996, according to a poll sponsored by
the Food Marketing Institute.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Priest May Not Testify Vs. Attacker
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIDDLETOWN, Ohio (AP) -- A Roman Catholic priest who was stabbed after
hearing a confession has identified his attacker but is reluctant to testify
against him. The Rev. Charles Mentrup, 41, was stabbed in the abdomen at his
home Friday after hearing the confession. He was in good condition today at
Middletown Regional Hospital. Mentrip identified the attacker, leading to an
arrest warrant, but is reluctant to help with the prosecution because of the
seal of secrecy involving confession. Marcus A. Finefrock, 25, turned himself in
and pleaded innocent Monday to one charge of felonious assault. He faces up to
eight years in prison if convicted.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall; Dollar Up Vs Yen
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell early Tuesday following a retreat in
technology shares on Wall Street. The Nikkei shed 224.49 points, to 17,975.47 in
early trading. In New York, the Nasdaq was down 147.44 at 3,669.38 and the Dow
Jones industrial average ended up 25.77 at 10,603.63.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Marlins Defeat Braves 3-2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- John Rocker balked home the winning run with two outs in the
ninth inning, and the Florida Marlins scored three unearned runs to beat the
Atlanta Braves 3-2 tonight. With a 2-2 count on Cliff Floyd and Danny Bautista
at third, Rocker took his position on the rubber and the ball fell out of his
glove to the ground. Second base umpire Mike DiMuro signaled a balk, and
Bautista trotted home.
</P>
