<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nationwide Strike Ends in Norway  </HEADLINE>
By DOUG MELLGREN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway (AP) -- A strike that threatened European automobile
production was called off Tuesday after Norway's largest union and
employers agreed on a new contract in all-night talks.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was reached in the sixth day of a strike by 84,600
union members, which the union had threatened to turn into Norway's
second largest labor conflict by pushing the number of strikers to
over 102,000 on Tuesday. The deal was reached just two hours before
that deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the new offer also has to be put to a vote by union
members, strikers were returning to work immediately pending the
outcome of that referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The strike had sent a chill through Europe's car industry
because it stopped supplies of Norwegian-made parts, which could
have caused widespread layoffs as production lines outside Norway
were forced to shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Automaker Saab stopped its Swedish production lines on Monday,
and Germany's BMW was reported to have threatened to drop Norwegian
suppliers if the strike forces it to shut down its plants.
</P>
<P>
   The new contract includes across the board raises of 16 cents
per hour for all union members, while the lowest paid members would
get 38 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the union nor the employers immediately estimated the
percentage increase in pay.
</P>
<P>
   The strike began Wednesday, after union members rejected a
contract package, even though it had been recommended by their
leadership. That offer included pay raises of 3.5 percent to 4.5
percent -- an average of about 8 cents per hour plus a minimum fifth
week of paid vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Yngve Haagensen, leader of the powerful Norwegian Confederation
of Trade Unions, revealed on Monday that union representatives had
quietly been meeting employers throughout the strike. He said he
and other top leaders met secretly on Sunday evening to sketch out
a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the wage increases raised immediate fears of
pressure on the Norwegian economy, which is already booming on oil
wealth. The nation of 4.5 million people is the world's second
largest oil exporter.
</P>
<P>
   The strike affected road transport, some passenger ferries,
hotels, the construction industry and some private security
companies. It also has forced many newspapers, including the
nation's largest, to stop their printed editions because their
graphics staffs walked out.
</P>
<P>
   The strike could have forced tens of thousands of layoffs in the
European car industry, but the Norwegian news agency NTB said some
of the Norwegian parts makers were ready to start night shifts to
get back on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The union had threatened to increase the number of strikers to
more than 102,000 after 6 a.m. Tuesday. That would have made it
Norway's worst labor conflict since 1921, when 150,000 people
walked off the job over proposed pay cuts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 2306 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000508.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pacers 103, 76ers 97  </HEADLINE>
By HANK LOWENKRON, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Jalen Rose scored 30 points and the Indiana
Pacers, despite not making a field goal over the final seven
minutes, beat the Philadelphia 76ers 103-97 Monday night to take a
2-0 lead in the Eastern Conference semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers scored their final 10 points on free throws, starting
with two by Rose that put Indiana ahead 95-73 with 5:53 to play.
</P>
<P>
   The 76ers rallied with a 33-14 run in the fourth quarter,
including scoring 17 straight points.
</P>
<P>
   The best-of-seven series shifts to Philadelphia for Game 3 on
Wednesday and Game 4 on Saturday. Only seven teams in NBA history
have rallied from a 2-0 deficit to win a series.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Iverson led the 76ers with 28 points, but was only
9-for-25 from the field. He had 10 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia, which trailed by as many as 26 points in the third
quarter, got within 95-88 when Iverson made two free throws with
2:44 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Two free throws by Rose made it 97-88 with 1:15 to play. Tyrone
Hill's layup made it 97-90, but he missed two free throws with 37
seconds to go. A free throw by Austin Croshere gave Indiana a 98-90
lead and a 3-pointer by Toni Kukoc made it 98-93.
</P>
<P>
   Rose then made one free throw with 18 seconds to go. After a
basket by Iverson, Reggie Miller made two free throws for Indiana
with 12 remaining and Rose sealed the victory by making two more
with 4.3 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   Croshere had a career playoff-high 20 points, including 4-for-4
from 3-point range, for Indiana, which pulled away as it shot 55
percent in the first half. Miller, who like Rose had 40 points in
Game 1, scored 19 and Rik Smits contributed 14 points on 7-of-9
shooting from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jackson scored seven points but had 14 assists and also did
much of the defensive work against Iverson.
</P>
<P>
   Hill added 15 points for Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The 76ers went over six minutes without a field goal in the
second quarter. A jumper by Aaron McKie brought the 76ers within
42-33 with 6:47 left in the half. The 76ers, who shot 22 percent in
the second quarter, didn't get another field goal until Matt
Geiger's dunk in the final second of the half.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana led 55-40 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana, which swept the 76ers in the semifinals last year, came
out hot for the second consecutive game. The Pacers, who never
trailed, made 11 of their first 15 shots and the 76ers were unable
to match the pace.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana led 31-26 after one quarter and scored eight straight in
the first two minutes of the second quarter. All of the baskets
came up layups.
</P>
<P>
   The 76ers, who were 4-for-19 from the field in the quarter,
missed their first six field goals in the period and later missed
eight consecutive shots as Indiana took its biggest lead of the
half, 53-35 with 2:10 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The 76ers fell behind by 26 when Croshere hit a 3-pointer with
4:08 left in the third quarter. Indiana shot 55 percent (12-of-22)
in the quarter and led 84-63 going into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers began the final period with four reserves on the
court and the 76ers capitalized. Indiana returned its starters, but
went only 3-of-14 from the field in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Miller, who scored 16 points in the first quarter of Game
1, had 11 points in the opening quarter Monday. ... The Pacers
extended their streak of sellouts at Conseco Fieldhouse to 46. ...
Indiana made eight 3-pointers and is 19-for-42 from behind the arc
in the series. ... Croshere's previous high in the playoffs was 16
in the opening round against Milwaukee. ... Rose played 46 minutes
and Iverson played 45.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-08-00 2315 </TRAILER>
